===Union cavalry supremacy 1864–1865===
{{expand section|date=February 2023}}
It also moved with the cavalry corps on Gen. Sheridan's first raid. May 9, 1864, until within 3 miles of Richmond.{{sfnp|Johnson & Buel, ''Retreat with Honor'' Battles and Leader, vol. IV (1887)|p=95-96|loc={{sp}}|ps=<br />''"Kilpatrick's and Dahlgren's Raid to Richmond," by George E. Pond'' }}  In the engagement at Trevilian Station, June 24, 1864, its loss was 10 officers and 58 enlisted men. During August of this year its loss in killed, wounded and missing was 49 men and 75 horses, and the total casualties during 1864 amounted to 295 officers and enlisted men.

In August 1864, seven companies of the 1st D. C. cavalry were transferred and assigned to the several companies of this regiment by a special order of the war department. The original members of the regiment whose term of service expired November 4, 1864, were mustered out at Augusta, ME, on November 25, while the regiment, now composed of veterans, recruits and members of the 1st D. C. cavalry whose term had not expired, participated in the closing battles of the war; was mustered out of the U. S. service at Petersburg, VA, August 1, 1865, and arrived in Augusta, ME., on August 9, 1865.

Joshua Chamberlain, in his book "Passing of Armies" states that the First Maine Calavlry was at the Appomattox fighting with General Sheridan. Chamberlain says:

"I was proud to learn that Smith's Brigade-our First Maine Cavalry in the van had waged the most critical part of the glorious fight."

Similar reference is found for the First Maine Cavalry in the order of battle list in Wikipedia reference for "Appomattox campaign Union order of battle."

"1st Maine Cavalry: Ltc Jonathan P. Cilley"

==Affiliations, battle honors, detailed service, and casualties==

===Organizational affiliation===
The 1st Maine Volunteer Cavalry Regiment was organized at Augusta, ME and served with the following organizations:{{sfnp|Dyer|1908|p=1215}}
* March 1862, [[Dixon Stansbury Miles|Miles']] Brigade defending [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] (2nd Battalion)
* April 1862, [[John P. Hatch|Hatch's]] Cavalry Brigade. [[Nathaniel P. Banks|Brig., Banks']] [[V Corps (Union Army)|V Corps]], and [[Department of the Shenandoah]] (2nd Battalion).{{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 12/3|p=312|ps='' - Organization of the Department of the Shenandoah, Maj. Gen. Nathaniel Banks commanding, Washington, May 31, 1862, pp. 312-313''}}
* March 1862, Abercrombie's Cavalry Brigade, [[Irvin McDowell|McDowell's]] [[Department of the Rappahannock]] (1st and 3rd Battalions)
* April 1862, [[George Dashiell Bayard|Bayard's]] Cavalry Brigade, Department of the Rappahannock (1st and 3rd Battalions).
* May 1862, [[Edward Ord]]'s Divisional Cavalry, McDowell's Department of the Rappahannock. (1st and 3rd Battalions){{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 12/3|p=310|ps='' - Organization of the Department of the Rappahannock, Maj. Gen. Irvin McDowell commanding,, Washington, May 31, 1862, pp. 309-312''}}
* June 1862, Bayard's Cavalry Brigade, [[III Corps (Union Army)|III Corps]], [[Army of Virginia]] (Reunited Regiment.).
* September 1–14, 1862, Bayard's Cavalry Brigade, [[Cavalry Corps (Union Army)|Cavalry Division]], [[Army of the Potomac]].{{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 12/2, Supp. 1886|ps='' -  The Fitz John Porter Court-Martial, Washington, November 25, 1862, p. 957''}}
* September 14–17, [[Fitz John Porter|Porter's]] V Corps Esort, Army of the Potomac (Company A){{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 19/1|p=174|ps='' - Organization of the Army of the Potomac, Maj. Gen. George B. McClellan, U.S. Army commanding, September 14–17, 1862, pp. 169-180''}}
* September 14–17, [[Jesse L. Reno|Reno's]] IX Corps Esort, Army of the Potomac (Company G){{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 19/1|p=177|ps='' - Organization of the Army of the Potomac, Maj. Gen. George B. McClellan, U.S. Army commanding, September 14–17, 1862, pp. 169-180''}}
* September 14–November 2, Cavalry Division Unattached,  [[Alpheus S. Williams|Williams']] XII  Corps, Army of the Potomac (Remainder of Regiment){{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 19/1|p=180|ps='' - Organization of the Army of the Potomac, Maj. Gen. George B. McClellan, U.S. Army commanding, September 14–17, 1862, pp. 169-180''}}
* December 11–15, Reynolds' I Corps Esort, Franklin's Left Grand Division, Army of the Potomac (Company L){{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 21|p=57|ps='' - Organization of Union forces at the Battle of Fredericksburg, Va., December 11–15, 1862, pp. 48-61''}}
* November 2–December 15, Bayard's Cavalry Brigade, Newton's 3rd Division, Smith's VI Corps, Franklin's Left Grand Division, Army of the Potomac (Remainder of Regiment){{sfnp | U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 21|p=61|ps='' - Organization of Union forces at the Battle of Fredericksburg, Va., December 11–15, 1862, pp. 48-61''}}
* December 31, 1862, Gregg's's Cavalry Brigade, [[III Corps (Union Army)|III Corps]], [[Army of the Potomac]].{{sfnp|U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 25/2|p=26|ps='' -  MGEN Hooker to Secy Stanton, Organization of Army of Potomac, January 31, 1863, pp. 16-29''}}
* February 1863, 1st Brig., 3rd Division, [[Cavalry Corps (Union Army)|Cavalry Corps]], Army of the Potomac.{{sfnp|U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 25/2|p=72, 82|ps='' -  HQ Cavalry Corps, General Orders No. 4, February 12, 1863, pp. 71-72; HQ 3rd Cavalry Division, General Orders No. 13, February 16, 1863, pp. 82-83''}}
* June 1863, 3rd Brig., 2nd Division, Cavalry Corps, Army of the Potomac.{{sfnp|U.S. War Dept., ''Official Records'', Vol. 25/2|p=575, 584|ps='' -  MGEN Hooker to Secy Stanton, Organization of Army of Potomac, May 31, 1863, pp. 575-586''}}
* August 1863, 2nd Brig., 2nd Division, Cavalry Corps, Army of the Potomac.
* October 1864, 3rd Brig., 2nd Division, Cavalry Corps, Army of the Potomac.
* May 1865, [[Department of Virginia]]
Mustered out August 1, 1865.

