* {{cite news|last=Walker|first=Shaun|date=3 September 2020|title='This gentleman': Alexei Navalny, the name Putin dares not speak|newspaper=The Guardian|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/sep/03/this-gentleman-alexei-navalny-the-name-putin-dares-not-speak|access-date=3 September 2020|archive-date=3 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200903170455/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/sep/03/this-gentleman-alexei-navalny-the-name-putin-dares-not-speak|url-status=live}}
* {{cite magazine|last=Roache|first=Madeline|date=18 January 2021|title='His Fight Is in Russia.' Why Navalny Flew Home Straight into Putin's Clutches|url=https://time.com/5930595/alexei-navalny-return-russia-why/|access-date=28 March 2021|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|archive-date=15 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210315011044/https://time.com/5930595/alexei-navalny-return-russia-why/|url-status=live}}
* {{cite web|last=Ward|first=Alex|date=29 January 2021|title=Alexei Navalny, the Russian opposition leader threatening Putin's rule, explained|url=https://www.vox.com/22254292/alexei-navalny-russia-protests-vladimir-putin-palace-video|access-date=28 March 2021|website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|archive-date=2 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210302175259/https://www.vox.com/22254292/alexei-navalny-russia-protests-vladimir-putin-palace-video|url-status=live}}</ref> He founded the [[Anti-Corruption Foundation]] (FBK) in 2011. He was [[List of Amnesty International-designated prisoners of conscience|recognised]] by [[Amnesty International]] as a [[prisoner of conscience]] and was awarded the [[Sakharov Prize]] for his work on human rights.

Through his social media accounts, Navalny and his team published material about corruption in Russia, organised political demonstrations and promoted his campaigns. In a 2011 interview, he described Russia's ruling party—[[United Russia]]—as a "[[party of crooks and thieves]]", which became a popular byname. Navalny and the FBK have published investigations detailing alleged corruption by high-ranking Russian officials and their associates.

Navalny twice received a suspended sentence for [[embezzlement]], in 2013 and 2014. Both criminal cases have been widely considered [[Political trial|politically motivated]] and intended to bar him from running in future elections. He ran in the [[2013 Moscow mayoral election]] and came in second with 27.2% of the vote,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-24004840|title=Putin ally Sergei Sobyanin wins Moscow mayor election|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=9 September 2013|access-date=16 July 2024|quote=His main rival, opposition leader Alexei Navalny, polled 27.2%.}}</ref> but was barred from running in the [[2018 Russian presidential election|2018 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/putin-critic-alexei-navalny-barred-from-running-in-2018-russian-election-11184386|title=Putin critic Alexei Navalny barred from running in 2018 Russian election|date=25 December 2017|access-date=16 July 2024|work=[[Sky News]]}}</ref>

In August 2020, Navalny was hospitalised after being [[Poisoning of Alexei Navalny|severely poisoned]] with a [[Novichok]] nerve agent. He was medically evacuated to Berlin and discharged a month later. He accused President [[Vladimir Putin]] of being responsible for his poisoning, and an investigation implicated agents from the [[Federal Security Service]]. In January 2021, Navalny returned to Russia and was immediately detained on accusations of violating [[parole]] conditions while hospitalised in Germany. Following his arrest, [[2021 Russian protests|mass protests]] were held across Russia.<ref name="tmt-putin"/> The next month, Navalny's suspended sentence was replaced with a prison sentence of over {{frac|2|1|2}} years' detention, and his organisations were later designated as extremist and liquidated. In March 2022, Navalny was sentenced to an additional nine years in prison after being found guilty of embezzlement and contempt of court in a new trial described as a sham by Amnesty International.<ref name="2022-conviction-bbc" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press-releases/russia-navalny-facing-possible-15-year-jail-term-sham-trial-set-take-place-prison|title=Russia: Navalny facing possible 15-year jail term in 'sham' trial set to take place in prison|website=Amnesty.org.uk|date=14 February 2022|access-date=19 May 2022|archive-date=31 October 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231031230139/https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press-releases/russia-navalny-facing-possible-15-year-jail-term-sham-trial-set-take-place-prison|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the rejection of his appeal, Navalny was transferred to a high-security prison in June.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Faulconbridge |first=Guy |date=14 June 2022 |title=Russian opposition leader Navalny moved to high-security penal colony |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/jailed-kremlin-critic-navalny-transferred-unknown-location-2022-06-14/ |access-date=18 June 2022 |archive-date=12 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220712050214/https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/jailed-kremlin-critic-navalny-transferred-unknown-location-2022-06-14/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2023, he received another sentence of 19 years on extremism charges.<ref>{{Cite news |date=4 August 2023 |title=Alexei Navalny: Russian opposition leader handed further 19 year jail term |language=en-GB |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-66408444 |access-date=4 August 2023 |archive-date=4 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230804141526/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-66408444 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2023, Navalny went missing from prison for almost three weeks. He re-emerged in an Arctic Circle [[FKU IK-3, Kharp|corrective colony]] in the [[Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug]].<ref name="disappear">{{Cite web |last1=Trevelyan |first1=Mark |date=11 December 2023 |title=Navalny aides says he has disappeared within Russia's prison system |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russias-navalny-removed-prison-colony-whereabouts-unclear-supporters-2023-12-11/ |work=Reuters |access-date=25 December 2023 |archive-date=12 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231212152705/https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russias-navalny-removed-prison-colony-whereabouts-unclear-supporters-2023-12-11/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Алексея Навального доставили в ИК-3 в Ямало-Ненецком автономном округе. С ним не было связи почти три недели |url=https://meduza.io/news/2023/12/25/alekseya-navalnogo-dostavili-v-ik-3-v-yamalo-nenetskom-avtonomnom-okruge-s-nim-ne-bylo-svyazi-primerno-tri-nedeli |access-date=25 December 2023 |website=Meduza |language=ru |archive-date=25 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231225124541/https://meduza.io/news/2023/12/25/alekseya-navalnogo-dostavili-v-ik-3-v-yamalo-nenetskom-avtonomnom-okruge-s-nim-ne-bylo-svyazi-primerno-tri-nedeli |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2024, the Russian prison service reported that Navalny [[Death and funeral of Alexei Navalny|had died]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/feb/16/russian-activist-and-putin-critic-alexei-navalny-dies-in-prison|title=Russian activist and Putin critic Alexei Navalny dies in prison|date=16 February 2024|first1=Helen|last1=Sullivan|first2=Andrew|last2=Roth|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=16 February 2024|archive-date=16 February 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240216120616/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/feb/16/russian-activist-and-putin-critic-alexei-navalny-dies-in-prison|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=16 February 2024 |title=Адвокат Навального сообщил о последнем визите к нему |trans-title=Navalny's lawyer announced his last visit to him |url=https://www.rbc.ru/politics/16/02/2024/65cf47909a794754d6646c58 |access-date=16 February 2024 |website=РБК |language=ru |archive-date=16 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240216120617/https://www.rbc.ru/politics/16/02/2024/65cf47909a794754d6646c58 }}</ref> which subsequently sparked protests in both Russia and various other countries. Accusations against Putin's government in connection with his death have been made by many Western governments and international organisations.

==Early life==
Navalny was born on 4 June 1976<ref>{{cite news|last=Rivkin|first=Amanda|title=Alexei Navalny marks 45th birthday in prison|url=https://www.dw.com/en/alexei-navalny-marks-45th-birthday-in-prison/a-57784005|work=[[Deutsche Welle]]|date=4 June 2021|access-date=18 June 2024|archive-date=19 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240619011550/https://www.dw.com/en/alexei-navalny-marks-45th-birthday-in-prison/a-57784005|url-status=live}}</ref> in [[Butyn, Russia|Butyn]], a [[Classification of inhabited localities in Russia#Rural|rural locality]] in [[Odintsovsky District]], Moscow Oblast, [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russia]], then part of the [[Soviet Union]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Aden|first=Mareike|date=5 September 2013|title=Alexej Nawalny: Der dunkle Star|trans-title=Alexei Navalny: The Dark Star|url=https://www.zeit.de/2013/37/russland-opposition-alexej-nawalny|url-access=subscription|access-date=26 October 2020|newspaper=[[Die Zeit]] Online|language=de|archive-date=15 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230815145545/https://www.zeit.de/2013/37/russland-opposition-alexej-nawalny|url-status=live}}</ref> His mother, Lyudmila Ivanovna Navalnaya (born 1954), is a [[Russians|Russian]] originally from [[Zelenograd]], Moscow, and his father, Anatoly Ivanovich Navalny (born 1947), is a [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] from Zalissia, a village near the [[Belarus–Ukraine border]] which was relocated due to [[Chernobyl exclusion zone|nuclear contamination]] caused by the [[Chernobyl disaster]].<ref>[https://vk.com/wall-33407101_12572 Navavalny's mother and father attending their son's court hearing]</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=uk:Село Навальних. Як в Україні земляки і родичі згадують головного ворога Путіна|trans-title=The village of Navalnykh. How in Ukraine compatriots and relatives remember Putin's main enemy|language=uk|work=BBC News Україна|url=https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/features-55903459|access-date=19 February 2021|archive-date=8 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210208200320/https://www.bbc.com/ukrainian/features-55903459|url-status=live}}</ref> Navalny identified as half Russian and half Ukrainian. Media regularly asked him whether he identified more as Russian or Ukrainian, and in his posthumously published memoir, ''Patriot'', he stated, "It was like being asked who you loved more, your mother or your father."<ref name="Cadwalladr">{{Cite news |last=Cadwalladr |first=Carole |date=2024-10-27 |title=Patriot by Alexei Navalny review – the man who dared to defy Putin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2024/oct/27/patriot-by-alexei-navalny-review-the-man-who-dared-to-defy-putin |access-date=2024-11-05 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Navalny grew up in the city of [[Obninsk]], Kaluga Oblast, about {{convert|100|km}} southwest of Moscow, and spent his summers with Anatoly's parents in Zalissia until the age of eight, acquiring proficiency in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]].<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ru:Алексей Навальный|trans-title=Alexey Navalny|url=http://esquire.ru/wil/alexey-navalny|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120720071606/http://esquire.ru/wil/alexey-navalny|archive-date=20 July 2012|access-date=31 July 2012|publisher=[[esquire.ru]]|language=ru |work=Журнал Esquire }}</ref><ref name="day">{{cite web|last=Hrabovskyi|first=Serhii|script-title=uk:Олексій Навальний як дзеркало російської революції|trans-title=Alexei Navalny as a mirror of the Russian revolution|url=https://day.kyiv.ua/uk/article/svitovi-diskusiyi/oleksiy-navalniy-yak-dzerkalo-rosiyskoyi-revolyuciyi|date=14 February 2012|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200922080236/https://day.kyiv.ua/uk/article/svitovi-diskusiyi/oleksiy-navalniy-yak-dzerkalo-rosiyskoyi-revolyuciyi|archive-date=22 September 2020|access-date=20 January 2021|publisher=day.kyiv.ua|language=uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2023-10-27 |title=For Putin foe Alexey Navalny, Ukraine has long been a volatile issue |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/10/27/navalny-ukraine-putin-russia/ |access-date=2024-03-03 |newspaper=Washington Post |language=en |archive-date=11 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231211082126/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/10/27/navalny-ukraine-putin-russia/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Anatoly and Lyudmila privately own a [[Basket weaving|basket-weaving]] factory—which the couple have run since 1994—in Kobyakovo, a village in [[Vologda Oblast]]. They were still running the factory as of 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kanygin|first=Pavel|author-link=Pavel Kanygin|date=20 December 2012|script-title=ru:Непр(е)ступная фабрика Навальных. Специальный репортаж из родительского гнезда лидера оппозиции|language=ru|trans-title=Impenetrable Navalny factory. Special report from the parental nest of the opposition leader|newspaper=Novaya Gazeta|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2012/12/21/52891-nepr-e-stupnaya-fabrika-navalnyh-spetsialnyy-reportazh-iz-roditelskogo-gnezda-lidera-oppozitsii|url-status=live|access-date=1 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125223657/https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2012/12/21/52891-nepr-e-stupnaya-fabrika-navalnyh-spetsialnyy-reportazh-iz-roditelskogo-gnezda-lidera-oppozitsii|archive-date=25 November 2018}}</ref>

==Education==
Navalny graduated from [[Kalininets]] secondary school (level 3 according to the [[International Standard Classification of Education|ISCED]]) in 1993.<ref name="Lenta.ru">{{cite news|url=https://lenta.ru/lib/14159595|script-title=ru:Навальный Алексей, российский общественный деятель|trans-title=Navalny Alexey, Russian public figure|publisher=[[Lenta.ru]]|access-date=3 March 2022|archive-date=28 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128052836/http://lenta.ru/lib/14159595/|url-status=live}}</ref> He graduated from the [[Peoples' Friendship University of Russia]] in 1998 with a [[law degree]].<ref name="BBC 2024-02-16"/> He then studied [[Security (finance)|securities]] and exchanges at the [[Financial University under the Government of the Russian Federation]], graduating in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|date=28 February 2012|title=Alexei Navalny|newspaper=The Moscow Times |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mt_profile/alexei-navalny/433932.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130204081530/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/mt_profile/alexei-navalny/433932.html|archive-date=4 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy|date=11 December 2011|title=Newsmaker – Protests pitch Russian blogger against Putin |publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/russia-navalny-idUSL5E7N63JP20111211|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227064132/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/11/russia-navalny-idUSL5E7N63JP20111211|archive-date=27 December 2011}}</ref>

In 2010, upon recommendation from [[Garry Kasparov]], [[Yevgeniya Albats]] and [[Sergey Guriev]], Navalny received a scholarship to the [[Yale World Fellows]] program at [[Yale University]], where he studied political science and world affairs.<ref>{{cite news|date=14 August 2013|title=Kremlin critic Navalny: To Moscow via Yale|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/kremlin-critic-navalny-to-moscow-via-yale/a-17021240|url-status=live|access-date=16 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116225659/https://www.dw.com/en/kremlin-critic-navalny-to-moscow-via-yale/a-17021240|archive-date=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alexey Navalny &#124; Yale Greenberg World Fellows |url=https://worldfellows.yale.edu/alexey-navalny|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116225708/https://worldfellows.yale.edu/alexey-navalny|archive-date=16 November 2019|access-date=16 November 2019|website=worldfellows.yale.edu}}</ref> As a World Fellow at Yale University's World Fellows Program, Navalny aimed at "creating a global network of emerging leaders and to broaden international understanding" in 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The World Fellows: Alexey Navalny |url=http://www.yale.edu/worldfellows/fellows/navalny.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707100956/http://www.yale.edu/worldfellows/fellows/navalny.html |archive-date=7 July 2011 |access-date=9 February 2011 |publisher=[[Yale University]]}}</ref>

==Legal career==
From 1998 onward, Navalny worked as a [[corporate lawyer]] for various Russian companies.<ref name="Lenta.ru"/>

In 2009, Navalny became an [[advocate]] and a member of advocate's chamber ([[bar association]]) of [[Kirov Oblast]] (registration number 43/547). In 2010, due to his move to Moscow, he ceased to be a member of advocate's chamber of Kirov Oblast and became a member of advocate's chamber of Moscow (registration number 77/9991).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawyers.minjust.ru/lawyers?fullName=%D0%9D%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BD%D1%8B%D0%B9+%D0%90%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BA%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%B9+%D0%90%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%87|title=Russian register of Advocates – Search Result – Navalny Alexey Anatolievich|publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (Russia)|Ministry of Justice of the Russian Federation]]|access-date=15 March 2022|archive-date=30 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220330074849/http://lawyers.minjust.ru/lawyers?fullName=%D0%9D%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BD%D1%8B%D0%B9+%D0%90%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BA%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%B9+%D0%90%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%B8%D1%87|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=ru:СК считает адвокатский статус Навального незаконным|trans-title=UK considers Navalny's legal status illegal|date=27 February 2013|publisher=[[BBC Russian Service]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2013/02/130215_navalny_status_inquiry|access-date=3 March 2022|archive-date=20 November 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211120213322/https://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2013/02/130215_navalny_status_inquiry|url-status=live}}</ref>

In November 2013, after the judgement in the [[#Kirovles case|Kirovles case]] had entered into force, Navalny was deprived of advocate status.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ru:Адвокатская палата Москвы лишила Навального статуса адвоката из-за приговора по делу "Кировлеса"|trans-title=The Moscow Chamber of Advocates deprived Navalny of the status of a lawyer due to the verdict in the Kirovles case|date=4 December 2013|publisher=[[Pravo.ru]]|url=https://pravo.ru/news/view/95366/|access-date=3 March 2022|archive-date=18 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210418212546/https://pravo.ru/news/view/95366/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2023/12/11/europe/russian-opposition-leader-alexey-navalny-missing-intl/index.html|title=Russian opposition leader Alexey Navalny missing from prison, says his team|date=11 December 2023 |publisher=CNN|access-date=11 December 2023|archive-date=11 December 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231211165343/https://edition.cnn.com/2023/12/11/europe/russian-opposition-leader-alexey-navalny-missing-intl/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Political activity==
===Yabloko===
[[File:Алексей Навальный 2006 год пикет движения ДА в защиту ПТУ.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Navalny in 2006]]
In 2000, following the announcement of a new law that raised the [[electoral threshold]] for [[Elections in Russia#Parliament|State Duma elections]], Navalny joined the Russian United Democratic Party [[Yabloko]]. According to Navalny, the law was stacked against Yabloko and [[Union of Right Forces]], and he decided to join, even though he was not "a big fan" of either organisation.<ref name="vedomosti" /> In 2001, he was listed as a member of the party.<ref name="vedomosti" /> In 2002, he was elected to the regional council of the Moscow branch of Yabloko.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Navalny|url=http://www.navalny.ru/about|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904150654/http://navalny.ru/about/|archive-date=4 September 2012|access-date=12 December 2011|publisher=navalny.ru|language=ru}}</ref> In 2003, he headed the Moscow subdivision of the election campaign of the party for the [[2003 Russian legislative election|parliamentary election held in December]]. In April 2004, Navalny became Chief of Staff of the Moscow branch of Yabloko, where he remained until February 2007. Also in 2004, he became Deputy Chief of the Moscow branch of the party. From 2006 to 2007, he was a member of the Federal Council of the party.<ref name="lenta">{{cite news|title=Navalny, Alexei|url=http://www.lenta.ru/lib/14159595|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120803124746/http://lenta.ru/lib/14159595/|archive-date=3 August 2012|access-date=13 December 2011|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref>
[[File:Navalny.JPG|thumb|Navalny in 2007]]
In August 2005, Navalny was admitted to the Social Council of the [[Central Administrative Okrug]] of Moscow, created before the [[2005 Moscow City Duma election|Moscow City Duma election held later that year]], in which he took part as a candidate. In November, he was one of the initiators of the Youth Public Chamber, intended to help younger politicians take part in legislative initiatives.<ref name="lenta" /> At the same time, in 2005, Navalny started another youth social movement, named "DA! – Democratic Alternative".{{efn|The Russian word "да" (''da'') means "yes".}} The project was not connected to Yabloko or any other political party. Within the movement, Navalny participated in several projects. In particular, he was one of the organisers of the movement-run political debates, which soon resonated in the media.<ref name="lenta" /> Navalny also organised television debates via state-run Moscow channel [[TV Center]]; two initial episodes showed high ratings, but the show was suddenly canceled. According to Navalny, the authorities prohibited the appearance of certain people on television.<ref name="lenta" />

In late 2006, Navalny appealed to the Moscow City Hall, asking it to grant permission to conduct the nationalist [[2006 Russian march]]. However, he added that Yabloko condemned "any ethnic or racial hatred and any xenophobia" and called on the police to oppose "any fascist, Nazi, xenophobic manifestations".{{efn|Argued as following: "It is clearly stated in the preamble of our declaration that the Yabloko Party thoroughly and sharply opposes any national and racial discord and any [[xenophobia]]. However, in this case, when we know ... that the Constitution guarantees us the right to gather peacefully and without a weapon, we see that in these conditions the prohibition of the Russian March as it was announced, provokes the organisers to some activities that could end not so well. Thus we appeal to the Moscow City Hall ... for permission."<ref>{{Cite news |title=Московское "Яблоко" поддержало проведение "Русского марша"  |trans-title=Moscow "Yabloko" supported the "Russian March" |url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/269476.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116225659/https://www.svoboda.org/a/269476.html |archive-date=16 November 2019 |access-date=16 November 2019 |website=Радио Свобода|date=November 2006 |last1=Багров |first1=Юрий |last2=Казнин |first2=Дмитрий }}</ref>}}

In December 2007, Yabloko lost [[2007 Russian legislative election|legislative election]] to Russian [[State Duma]] by receiving [[2007 Russian legislative election#Results|only 1.6% votes]]. At a meeting of the party bureau, Navalny had proposed to reform the party and change its leadership because of the failure in the elections. He sharply criticized many actions by the party and asked for "immediate resignation of the party chairman and all his deputies, re-election of at least 70 percent of the bureau".<ref name="lenta" /><ref name="biography">''Navalny. The man who stole the forest. The history of a blogger and a politician.'' by Byshok Stanislav Olegovich and Semyonov Alexander Alexandrovich. (''Навальный. Человек, который украл лес. История блогера и политика.'', by Бышок Станислав Олегович, Семенов Александр Александрович.) Книжный мир, 2014, ISBN 978-5-8041-0670-7, pages 5–6: [https://kniga-online.org/books/dokumentalnye-knigi/publicism/page-6-357997-navalnyi-chelovek-kotoryi-ukral-les-istoriya-blogera.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240225233518/https://kniga-online.org/books/dokumentalnye-knigi/publicism/page-6-357997-navalnyi-chelovek-kotoryi-ukral-les-istoriya-blogera.html|date=25 February 2024}}.</ref> He said: "Yabloko completely failed in these elections ... This is not a matter of counting [the votes]. The elections were dishonest and unfair. But we would get even less in fair elections. Because fair elections should not be just a live broadcast for [[Grigory Yavlinsky|Grigory Alekseevich]]. Everyone must be able to participate. This means that the more popular [[Garry Kasparov|Kasparov]] and [[Vladimir Ryzhkov|Ryzhkov]] would have been on the same live broadcast. This means that [[Mikhail Kasyanov|Kasyanov]] with his financial resources would take part in the elections. ... I argue that Yabloko has collapsed because it has turned itself to a [[sect]]. We demand that everyone must be a democrat, but we don't want to be democrats ourselves. ... And the worse the results, the stronger the leadership's position."<ref name="biography"/> He was expelled from Yabloko at the same meeting for his nationalist views and for participating in the Russian March.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/who-was-alexei-navalny-what-did-he-say-russia-putin-death-2024-02-16/ |title=Who was Alexei Navalny and what did he say of Russia, Putin and death? |first=Guy |last=Faulconbridge |work=Reuters |date=17 February 2024 |access-date=25 February 2024 |archive-date=27 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240227121720/https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/who-was-alexei-navalny-what-did-he-say-russia-putin-death-2024-02-16/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2021/03/18/europe/alexey-navalny-fast-facts/index.html |title=Alexey Navalny Fast Facts |date=21 February 2024 |access-date=25 February 2024 |publisher=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240221081636/https://edition.cnn.com/2021/03/18/europe/alexey-navalny-fast-facts/index.html |archive-date=21 February 2024}}</ref><ref name="aljazeera2021"/> According to Russian opposition politician [[Ilya Yashin]], Navalny was expelled from Yabloko because he challenged party leader [[Grigory Yavlinsky]].<ref>[https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20230804-putin-nemesis-navalny-in-10-dates Putin nemesis Navalny in 10 dates] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230805111432/https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20230804-putin-nemesis-navalny-in-10-dates |date=5 August 2023 }} by [[Agence France-Presse]].</ref>

=== 2011 parliamentary election and protests ===
{{main|2011 Russian legislative election|2011–2013 Russian protests}}

[[File:Навальный 6 декабря 2011 года в суде.jpg|thumb|Navalny at the courthouse, 6 December 2011]]
In December 2011, after [[2011 Russian legislative election|parliamentary elections]] and accusations of electoral fraud,<ref>{{cite magazine|author=[[Julia Ioffe (journalist)|Julia Ioffe]]|date=5 December 2011|title=Russian Elections: Faking It|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2011/12/russian-elections-faking-it.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120905015533/http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2011/12/russian-elections-faking-it.html|archive-date=5 September 2012}}</ref> approximately 6,000 people [[2011 Russian protests|gathered in Moscow]] to protest the contested result, and an estimated 300 people were arrested, including Navalny. Navalny was arrested on 5 December.<ref name= Blog2011/><ref name= Ioffe/> After a period of uncertainty for his supporters, Navalny appeared in court and was sentenced to a maximum of 15 days "for defying a government official". [[Alexei Venediktov]], editor-in-chief of [[Echo of Moscow]] radio station, called the arrest "a political mistake: jailing Navalny transforms him from an online leader into an offline one".<ref name="Ioffe">{{cite magazine|author=[[Julia Ioffe (journalist)|Julia Ioffe]]|date=6 December 2011|title=Putin's Big Mistake?|magazine=The New Yorker|url=http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2011/12/putins-big-mistake.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120907032947/http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/newsdesk/2011/12/putins-big-mistake.html|archive-date=7 September 2012}}</ref> After his arrest, his blog became available in English.<ref name="Blog2011">{{cite web|title=The Blog on Navalny in English|url=http://navalny-en.livejournal.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122174405/http://navalny-en.livejournal.com/|archive-date=22 January 2012|access-date=6 December 2011|publisher=[[LiveJournal]]}}</ref> Navalny was kept in the same prison as several other activists, including [[Ilya Yashin]] and [[Sergei Udaltsov]], the unofficial leader of the [[Vanguard of Red Youth]], a radical Russian communist youth group. Udaltsov went on a [[hunger strike]] to protest against the conditions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Parfitt|first=Tom|date=17 December 2011|title=Vladimir Putin's persecution campaign targets protest couple|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/17/putin-protest-organiser-hunger-strike|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001091854/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/17/putin-protest-organiser-hunger-strike|archive-date=1 October 2013}}</ref>

[[File:Moscow rally 10 March 2012 5.JPG|thumb|Navalny at a Moscow rally, 10 March 2012]]
Upon his release on 20 December 2011, Navalny called on Russians to unite against Putin, who Navalny said would try to claim victory in the [[2012 Russian presidential election|presidential election]], which was held on 4 March 2012.<ref name="reuters.com">{{cite news|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy|date=20 December 2011|title=Navalny challenges Putin after leaving Russian jail|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-navalny-idUSTRE7BK05Z20111221|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419064425/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/21/us-russia-navalny-idUSTRE7BK05Z20111221|archive-date=19 April 2012}}</ref>

After his release, Navalny informed reporters that it would be senseless for him to run in the presidential elections because the [[Moscow Kremlin|Kremlin]] would not allow the elections to be fair, but if free elections were held, he would "be ready" to run.<ref name="reuters.com"/> On 24 December, he helped lead a demonstration, estimated at 50,000 people, which was much larger than the previous post-election demonstration. Speaking to the crowd, he said, "I see enough people to take the Kremlin right now".<ref>{{cite news|last=Weir|first=Fred|date=24 December 2011|title=Huge protest demanding fair Russian elections hits Moscow|publisher=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2011/1224/Huge-protest-demanding-fair-Russian-elections-hits-Moscow|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120904005138/http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2011/1224/Huge-protest-demanding-fair-Russian-elections-hits-Moscow|archive-date=4 September 2012}}</ref>

In March 2012, after Putin was elected president, Navalny helped lead an anti-Putin rally in Moscow's [[Pushkinskaya Square]], attended by between 14,000 and 20,000 people. After the rally, Navalny was detained by authorities for several hours, and then released.<ref>{{cite news|date=5 March 2012|title=Russia election: Police arrest 550 at city protests|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-17265820|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307190519/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-17265820|archive-date=7 March 2012}}</ref> On 8 May 2012, the day after Putin was inaugurated, Navalny and Udaltsov were arrested after an anti-Putin rally at [[Clean Ponds]], and were each given 15-day jail sentences.<ref>{{cite news|date=8 May 2012|title=Police keep anti-Putin protesters on the run|publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]|agency=Associated Press|url=https://news.yahoo.com/police-keep-anti-putin-protesters-run-175929367.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413150649/http://news.yahoo.com/police-keep-anti-putin-protesters-run-175929367.html|archive-date=13 April 2014}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] designated the two men [[Prisoner of conscience|prisoners of conscience]].<ref name="RFE185">{{cite news|date=18 May 2012|title=Amnesty Calls Navalny, Udaltsov 'Prisoners of Conscience'|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/amnesty-navalny-udaltsov-prisoners-of-conscience/24584838.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130113113510/http://www.rferl.org/content/amnesty-navalny-udaltsov-prisoners-of-conscience/24584838.html|archive-date=13 January 2013|access-date=18 May 2012|publisher=RFE/RL}}</ref> On 11 June, Moscow prosecutors conducted a 12-hour search of Navalny's home, office, and the apartment of one of his relatives.<ref>{{cite news |date=11 June 2012 |title=В квартирах активистов оппозиции прошли обыски |trans-title=The apartments of opposition activists were searched |url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2012/06/120611_opposition_search |access-date=23 December 2020 |publisher=BBC Russian Service |language=ru |archive-date=18 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210418173929/https://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2012/06/120611_opposition_search |url-status=live }}</ref> Soon afterwards, some of Navalny's personal emails were posted online by a pro-government blogger.<ref name="data release"/>

===New party===
{{main|Russia of the Future}}

On 26 June 2012, it was announced that Navalny's comrades would establish a new political party based on [[e-democracy]]; Navalny declared he did not plan to participate in this project at the moment.<ref>{{cite web|date=26 June 2012|title=Соратники Навального создадут партию без него: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2012/06/26/party/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310084216/https://lenta.ru/news/2012/06/26/party/|archive-date=10 March 2017|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref> On 31 July, they filed a document to register an organising committee of a future party named "The People's Alliance".<ref>{{cite news|title=Команда Алексея Навального создает партию |trans-title=Alexei Navalny's team creates a party |url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2012/08/01/partiya_ashurkova|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105204634/http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2012/08/01/partiya_ashurkova|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|work=Vedomosti}}</ref> The party identified itself as [[centrism|centrist]]; one of the then-current leaders of the party, and Navalny's ally Vladimir Ashurkov, explained this was intended to help the party get a large share of voters. Navalny said the concept of political parties was "outdated", and added his participation would make maintaining the party more difficult. However, he "blessed" the party and discussed its maintenance with its leaders. They, in turn, stated they wanted to eventually see Navalny as a member of the party.<ref>{{cite news|title="Лента.ру" изучила устройство "партии Навального" |trans-title=Electronic party "Lenta.ru" studied the structure of "Navalny's party"|url=http://lenta.ru/articles/2012/08/06/electronicperformers/|publisher=Lenta.ru|access-date=27 December 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310084622/https://lenta.ru/articles/2012/08/06/electronicperformers/|archive-date=10 March 2017}}</ref> On 15 December 2012 Navalny expressed his support of the party, saying, "The People's Alliance is my party", but again refused to join it, citing the criminal cases against him.<ref>{{cite news|date=15 December 2012|title=Решение Навального не вступать в партию не было сюрпризом для его сторонников|trans-title=Navalny's decision not to join the party was not a surprise to his supporters|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2091888|access-date=20 October 2021|newspaper=[[Kommersant]]|language=ru|archive-date=20 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211020085812/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2091888|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 10 April 2013, the party filed documents for the official registration of the party.<ref name="bbcalliance">{{cite news |title=Регистрация партии соратников Навального приостановлена |trans-title=Registration of the party of Navalny's associates has been suspended |publisher=BBC Russian Service|url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2013/05/130506_peoples_alliance_registration|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822185752/https://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2013/05/130506_peoples_alliance_registration|archive-date=22 August 2020}}</ref> On 30 April, the registration of the party was suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=О приостановлении государственной регистрации партии&nbsp;– Новости. Народный альянс |trans-title=On the suspension of state registration of the party – News. People's Alliance |url=http://peoplesalliance.ru/press/news/o_priostanovlenii_gosudarstvennoj_registracii_partii/?Year=2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304175639/http://peoplesalliance.ru/press/news/o_priostanovlenii_gosudarstvennoj_registracii_partii?year=2013|archive-date=4 March 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Peoplesalliance.ru}}</ref> On 5 July 2013 the party was declined registration; according to ''[[Izvestia]]'', not all founders of the party were present during the congress, even though the papers contained their signatures.<ref>{{cite news|title=Минюст окончательно отказал в регистрации партии Навального|newspaper=Izvestia|url=http://izvestia.ru/news/553167|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105153600/http://izvestia.ru/news/553167|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> Navalny reacted to that with a tweet saying, "A salvo of all guns."<ref>{{cite news|title=Партии сторонников Навального отказали в регистрации: Политика: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/07/05/alliance/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://lenta.ru/news/2013/07/05/alliance/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref> Following the mayoral election, on 15 September 2013, Navalny declared he would join and, possibly, head the party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Алексей Навальный намерен вступить в незарегистрированную партию "Народный альянс" и, возможно, возглавить ее|url=http://echo.msk.ru/news/1157892-echo.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105125959/http://echo.msk.ru/news/1157892-echo.html|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=[[Echo of Moscow]]}}</ref> On 17 November 2013 Navalny was elected as the leader of the party.<ref>{{cite web|date=17 November 2013|title=Navalny becomes the People's Alliance party leader &#124; Russia Beyond the Headlines|url=http://rbth.com/news/2013/11/17/navalny_becomes_peoples_alliance_party_leader_31784.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://rbth.com/news/2013/11/17/navalny_becomes_peoples_alliance_party_leader_31784.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Rbth.com}}</ref>

On 8 January 2014, Navalny's party filed documents for registration for the second time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Алексей Навальный поборется за "Народный альянс"|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2380778|url-status=live|date=8 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2380778|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|newspaper=Kommersant}}</ref> On 20 January, registration of the party was suspended;<ref>{{cite web|title=Минюст приостановил регистрацию партии А.Навального :: Политика :: РосБизнесКонсалтинг|work=РБК |url=http://top.rbc.ru/politics/20/01/2014/900428.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713210714/http://top.rbc.ru/politics/20/01/2014/900428.shtml|archive-date=13 July 2015|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=[[RBK Group]]}}</ref> according to Russian laws, no two parties can share a name.<ref name="Bogdanov">{{cite news|date=28 November 2013|title=Навальный решил отсудить "Народный альянс" у Богданова: Политика: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/11/28/sue/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://lenta.ru/news/2013/11/28/sue/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref> On 8 February 2014, Navalny's party changed its name to "Progress Party".<ref>{{cite news|title=Партия Навального сменила название: Политика: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2014/02/08/party/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://lenta.ru/news/2014/02/08/party/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref> On 25 February 2014, the party was registered, and<ref>{{cite news|date=28 February 2014|title=Партия Навального получила регистрацию: Политика: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2014/02/28/progress/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://lenta.ru/news/2014/02/28/progress/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref> at this point, had six months to register regional branches in at least half of the [[federal subjects of Russia]].{{efn|Article 15, section 7: "Terms, as provided by sections 4 and 6 of the present article, are prolonged if a territorial body has passed a verdict of suspension of state registration of a regional branch of a political party, as provided by section 5.1 of the present article, or a verdict of denial of state registration of a regional branch of a political party has been challenged to a court and, as of the day of expiration of the said terms, has not gone into effect."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Федеральный закон от 11.07.2001 N 95-ФЗ (ред. от 23.05.2015) "О политических партиях" / КонсультантПлюс |url=http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_180106/?frame=2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703105335/http://www.consultant.ru/document/cons_doc_LAW_180106/?frame=2 |archive-date=3 July 2015 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Consultant.ru}}</ref> The following section is given as in force as on 2 April 2012 (the section had not changed by 1 May 2015).}} On 26 September 2014, the party declared it had registered 43 regional branches.<ref name="rbc progress party">{{Cite web |title=Навальный объявил о готовности подтвердить регистрацию партии :: Политика :: РосБизнесКонсалтинг |url=http://top.rbc.ru/politics/26/09/2014/951543.shtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713210707/http://top.rbc.ru/politics/26/09/2014/951543.shtml |archive-date=13 July 2015 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Top.rbc.ru}}</ref> An unnamed source of ''Izvestia'' in the ministry said registrations completed after the six-month term would not be taken into consideration, adding, "Yes, trials are taking place in some regions ... they cannot register new branches in other regions during the trials, because the main term is over". Navalny's blog countered, "Our answer is simple. A six-month term for registration has been legally prolonged ''ad interim'' prosecution of appeals of denials and registration suspensions".<ref name="rbc progress party" /> [[File:Electoral headquarters of Alexey Navalny 01.jpg|thumb|Navalny's election campaign in 2013]]

On 1 February 2015, the party held a convention, where Navalny stated the party was preparing for the 2016 elections, declaring the party would maintain its activity across Russia, saying, "We are unabashed to work in remote lands where the opposition does not work. We can even [work] in Crimea". The candidates the party would appoint were to be chosen via primary elections; however, he added, the party's candidates may be removed from elections.<ref>{{cite web|date=1 February 2015|title=Navalny's party to continue working for participation in elections &#124; Russia Beyond the Headlines|url=http://rbth.com/news/2015/02/01/navalnys_party_to_continue_working_for_participation_in_elections_43327.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://rbth.com/news/2015/02/01/navalnys_party_to_continue_working_for_participation_in_elections_43327.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Rbth.com}}</ref> On 17 April 2015, the party initiated a coalition of democratic parties.<ref name="elect">{{cite web|date=17 April 2015|title=Алексей Навальный&nbsp;– Объединение состоялось, у нас будет предвыборный список|url=https://navalny.com/p/4206/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/https://navalny.com/p/4206/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Navalny.com}}</ref> <!--According to a data array released in late March, which is claimed to be leaked correspondence of экс-замглавы Управления внутренней политики Администрации президента Алексея Анисимова, the registration of the party has been overviewed and controlled by the Kremlin.<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 March 2015 |title="Анонимный интернационал": процесс регистрации "Партии прогресса" курировался Кремлем |url=http://yodnews.ru/news/2015/03/26/ppprokopenko}}</ref>--> On 28 April 2015, the party was deprived of registration by the Ministry of Justice, which stated the party had not registered the required number of regional branches within six months after the official registration.<ref>{{cite news|title=Минюст отменил регистрацию "Партии прогресса", нарушившей закон при регистрации отделений|publisher=TASS|url=http://tass.ru/politika/1938519|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105180945/http://tass.ru/politika/1938519|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> Krainev claimed that the party could be eliminated only by the Supreme Court, and he added that not all trials of registration of regional branches were over, calling the verdict "illegal twice". He added that the party would appeal to the [[European Court of Human Rights]], and expressed confidence that the party would be restored and admitted to elections.<ref>{{cite news|title=Минюст отменил регистрацию "Партии прогресса", нарушившей закон при регистрации отделений|url=http://tass.ru/politika/1938519|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105180945/http://tass.ru/politika/1938519|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> The next day, the party officially challenged the verdict.<ref>{{cite web|date=16 April 2014|title="Партия прогресса" обжаловала решение Минюста о ликвидации|url=http://www.the-village.ru/village/situation/situation/213867-partiya-progressa|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105044727/http://www.the-village.ru/village/situation/situation/213867-partiya-progressa|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=The Village.ru}}</ref>

