[[File:Msk2013.Навальный.svg|thumb|upright=1.2|Percentages of Muscovites who voted for Navalny during the [[2013 Moscow mayoral election|election]]]]
[[File:Alexey Navalny's meeting at Bolotnaya Square 2013-09-09 5075.jpg|thumb|Navalny's meeting at [[Bolotnaya Square]] in Moscow, 9 September 2013]]

On 30 May 2013, [[Sergey Sobyanin]], the mayor of Moscow, argued an elected mayor is an advantage for the city compared to an appointed one,<ref>{{cite web|date=30 May 2013|title="Нужны и демократия, и власть" &#124; Городская власть &#124; Москва &#124; Московские новости|url=http://www.mn.ru/moscow_authority/20130530/347635870.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806052310/http://www.mn.ru/moscow_authority/20130530/347635870.html|archive-date=6 August 2015|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Mn.ru}}</ref> and on 4 June, he announced he would meet President Vladimir Putin and ask him for a snap election, mentioning the Muscovites would agree the governor elections should take place in the city of Moscow and the surrounding [[Moscow Oblast]] simultaneously.<ref>{{cite news|date=19 June 2013|title=Отставка Собянина и досрочные выборы мэра: причины и последствия &#124; РИА Новости|agency=RIA Novosti|url=http://ria.ru/politics/20130604/941316905.html|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105075428/http://ria.ru/politics/20130604/941316905.html|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> On 6 June, the request was granted,<ref>{{cite news|title=Собянин подписал указ о временном исполнении обязанностей мэра Москвы &#124; РИА Новости|agency=RIA Novosti|url=http://ria.ru/politics/20130606/941917281.html|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105103936/http://ria.ru/politics/20130606/941917281.html|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> and the next day, the [[Moscow City Duma]] appointed the [[2013 Moscow mayoral election|election]] on 8 September, the national voting day.<ref>{{cite news|date=7 June 2013|title=Досрочные выборы мэра Москвы назначены на 8 сентября|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2206494|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105123623/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2206494|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|newspaper=Kommersant}}</ref>

On 3 June, Navalny announced he would run for the post.<ref>{{cite web|title=Навальный заявил о намерении участвовать в выборах мэра Москвы: Политика|url=https://lenta.ru/news/2013/06/03/willing/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/https://lenta.ru/news/2013/06/03/willing/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref> To become an official candidate, he would need either seventy thousand signatures of Muscovites or to be pegged for the office by a registered party, and then to collect 110 signatures of municipal deputies from 110 different subdivisions (three-quarters of Moscow's 146). Navalny chose to be pegged by a party, [[People's Freedom Party (Russia)|RPR–PARNAS]].<ref>{{cite web|title="Это рейдерский захват партии". Почему Рыжков ушел из РПР-ПАРНАС|url=http://tvrain.ru/teleshow/here_and_now/eto_rejderskij_zahvat_partii_pochemu_ryzhkov_ushel_iz_rpr_parnas-362272/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/https://tvrain.ru/teleshow/here_and_now/eto_rejderskij_zahvat_partii_pochemu_ryzhkov_ushel_iz_rpr_parnas-362272/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Tvrain.ru|date=8 February 2014 }}</ref>

Among the six candidates who were officially registered as such, only two (Sobyanin and [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation|Communist]] Ivan Melnikov) were able to collect the required number of the signatures themselves, and the other four were given a number of signatures by the Council of Municipal Formations, following a recommendation by Sobyanin,<ref>{{cite web|date=17 July 2013|title=Навального зарегистрировали кандидатом в мэры Москвы: Политика: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/07/17/navalny/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/http://lenta.ru/news/2013/07/17/navalny/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref> to overcome the requirement (Navalny accepted 49 signatures, and other candidates accepted 70, 70, and 82).<ref>{{cite news|title=Совет муниципальных депутатов передал Навальному 49 подписей: Политика: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/07/09/signatures/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://lenta.ru/news/2013/07/09/signatures/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref>

On 17 July, Navalny was registered as one of the six candidates for the Moscow mayoral election.<ref>{{cite news|last=Smolchenko|first=Anna|date=17 July 2013|title=Navalny Moscow mayoral bid accepted ahead of verdict|publisher=[[Fox News]]|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/navalny-moscow-mayoral-bid-accepted-ahead-of-verdict/|url-status=live|access-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723000507/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/07/17/navalny-moscow-mayoral-bid-accepted-ahead-verdict/|archive-date=23 July 2013}}</ref> On 18 July, he was sentenced to a five-year prison term for the embezzlement and fraud charges that were declared in 2012. Several hours after his sentencing, he pulled out of the race and called for a boycott of the election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Navalny pulls out of Moscow poll, calls for boycott|agency=Agence France-Presse|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/afp/130718/navalny-pulls-out-moscow-poll-calls-boycott|url-status=live|access-date=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910050830/http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/afp/130718/navalny-pulls-out-moscow-poll-calls-boycott|archive-date=10 September 2013}}</ref> Later that day, the prosecution office requested that Navalny be freed on bail and released from travel restrictions, since the verdict had not yet taken legal effect, saying that he had previously followed the restrictions. Navalny was a mayoral candidate, and imprisonment would thus not comply with the rule for equal access to the electorate.<ref>{{cite news|date=19 July 2013|title=Прокуратура просит выпустить Навального и Офицерова под подписку &#124; РИА Новости|trans-title=The prosecutor's office asks to release Navalny and Ofitserov on bail|agency=RIA Novosti|url=http://ria.ru/incidents/20130719/950774598.html|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105102308/http://ria.ru/incidents/20130719/950774598.html|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> On his return to Moscow after being freed, pending an appeal, he vowed to stay in the race.<ref>{{cite news|title=Freed Kremlin critic arrives in Moscow|publisher=[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2013/07/201372063750946958.html|url-status=live|access-date=20 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720144824/http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2013/07/201372063750946958.html|archive-date=20 July 2013}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' has speculated that his release was ordered by the Kremlin in order to make the election and Sobyanin appear more legitimate.<ref name="kremlin critic">{{cite news|last=Englund|first=Will|date=9 September 2013|title=Kremlin critic Alexei Navalny has strong showing in Moscow mayoral race, despite loss|newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/kremlin-critic-alexei-navalny-has-strong-showing-in-moscow-mayoral-race-despite-loss/2013/09/09/dc9504e4-1924-11e3-a628-7e6dde8f889d_story.html|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|access-date=24 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028042215/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/kremlin-critic-alexei-navalny-has-strong-showing-in-moscow-mayoral-race-despite-loss/2013/09/09/dc9504e4-1924-11e3-a628-7e6dde8f889d_story.html|archive-date=28 October 2017}}</ref>

Navalny's campaign was successful in fundraising: out of 103.4&nbsp;million [[Russian ruble|ruble]]s (${{Formatprice|{{To USD|103400000|RUS|year=2013}}}} as of the election day{{refn|group=rates|According to the exchange rates set by the [[Central Bank of Russia]] for 8 September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=База данных по курсам валют &#124; Банк России|url=http://www.cbr.ru/currency_base/daily.aspx?date_req=08.09.2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518104222/http://www.cbr.ru/currency_base/daily.aspx?date_req=08.09.2013|url-status=dead|archive-date=18 May 2015|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Cbr.ru|url-access=limited}}</ref>}}), the total size of his electoral fund, 97.3&nbsp;million (${{Formatprice|{{To USD|97300000|RUS|year=2013}}|-2}}) were transferred by individuals throughout Russia;<ref>{{cite web|title=Алексей НАвАльНый, кандидат в мэры москвы 2013. отчет о предвыборной кампании.|trans-title=Alexei Navalny, candidate for mayor of Moscow 2013. Report on the election campaign.|url=http://report.navalny.ru/media/navalny_report.pdf|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304042249/http://report.navalny.ru/media/navalny_report.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Report.navalny.ru|language=ru}}</ref> such an amount is unprecedented in Russia.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ennis|first=Stephen|title=Alexei Navalny runs Western-style campaign in Moscow poll|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-23970618|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-23970618|archive-date=31 January 2016}}</ref> It achieved a high profile through an unprecedentedly large campaign organisation that involved around 20,000 volunteers who passed out leaflets and hung banners, in addition to conducting several campaign rallies a day around the city;<ref name="strong showing">{{cite news|author1=Laura Mills|author2=Lynn Berry|date=8 September 2013|title=Strong Showing for Navalny in Moscow Mayoral Race|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/moscow-votes-pivotal-mayoral-race-20193719?page=2|url-status=live|access-date=27 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130909115111/http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/moscow-votes-pivotal-mayoral-race-20193719?page=2|archive-date=9 September 2013}}</ref> they were the main driving force for the campaign.<ref name="ng">{{cite web|date=31 December 2013|title=Участие Навального в выборах мэра Москвы / Итоги года / Независимая газета|url=http://www.ng.ru/itog/2013-12-30/1_navalny.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105230052/http://www.ng.ru/itog/2013-12-30/1_navalny.html|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=[[Ng.ru]]}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' described the resulted campaign as "a miracle", along with Navalny's release on 19 July, the fundraising campaign, and the personality of Navalny himself.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lipman|first=Masha|date=6 September 2013|title=Alexey Navalny's Miraculous, Doomed Campaign|magazine=The New Yorker|url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/alexey-navalnys-miraculous-doomed-campaign|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160108065621/http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/alexey-navalnys-miraculous-doomed-campaign|archive-date=8 January 2016}}</ref> The campaign received very little television coverage and did not utilise billboards. Thanks to Navalny's strong campaign (and Sobyanin's weak one<ref name="strong showing"/>), his result grew over time, weakening Sobyanin's, and in the end of the campaign, he declared the [[runoff election]] (to be conducted if none of the candidates receives at least 50% of votes) was "a hair's breadth away".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://navalny.livejournal.com/848063.html |title=navalny: планирование, ребята, планирование |publisher=Navalny.livejournal.com |access-date=30 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315033124/http://navalny.livejournal.com/848063.html |archive-date=15 March 2014 }}</ref>

The largest sociological research organisations predicted that Sobyanin would win the election, scoring 58% to 64% of the vote; they expected Navalny to receive 15–20% of the vote, and the turnout was to be 45–52%. ([[Levada Center]] was the only one not to have made any predictions; the data it had on 28 August was similar to that of other organisations.)<ref name="elections sociology">{{cite news|date=16 November 2015|title=Почему социологические службы не смогли спрогнозировать результаты выборов московского мэра – Газета.Ru|newspaper=[[Gazeta.ru]]|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/2013/09/09_a_5645357.shtml|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/2013/09/09_a_5645357.shtml|archive-date=31 January 2016}}</ref> The final results of the voting showed Navalny received 27% of the vote, more than candidates appointed by the parties that received second, third, fourth, and fifth highest results during the 2011 parliamentary elections, altogether. Navalny fared better in the center and southwest of Moscow, which have higher income and education levels.<ref name="kremlin critic"/> Sobyanin received 51% of the vote, winning the election. The turnout was 32%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Сведения о проводящихся выборах и референдумах|url=http://www.moscow_city.vybory.izbirkom.ru/region/region/moscow_city?action=show&root=1&tvd=27720001368293&vrn=27720001368289&region=77&global=&sub_region=0&prver=0&pronetvd=null&vibid=27720001368293&type=222|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204412/http://www.moscow_city.vybory.izbirkom.ru/region/region/moscow_city?action=show&root=1&tvd=27720001368293&vrn=27720001368289&region=77&global=&sub_region=0&prver=0&pronetvd=null&vibid=27720001368293&type=222|archive-date=4 March 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Moscow_city.vybory.izbirkom.ru}}</ref> The organisations explained the differences were because Sobyanin's electorate did not vote, as they felt that their candidate was guaranteed to win. Navalny's campaign office predicted Sobyanin would score 49–51%, and Navalny would get 24–26% of votes.<ref name="elections sociology"/>

Many experts said the election had been fair, that the number of irregularities had been much lower than those of other elections held within the country, and that the irregularities had had little effect on the result.<ref name="election was fair">{{cite web|title=Выборы мэра превратились в "большую проблему"|url=http://www.utro.ru/articles/2013/09/09/1142783.shtml|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/http://www.utro.ru/articles/2013/09/09/1142783.shtml|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Utro.ru|date=9 September 2013 }}</ref><ref name="forbes moscow navalny"/> Dmitri Abyzalov, leading expert of Center of Political Conjuncture, added low turnout figures provide a further sign of fairness of the election, because that shows they were not overestimated.<ref name="election was fair"/> However, according to Andrei Buzin, co-chairman of the [[GOLOS Association]], State Departments of Social Security added people who did not originally want to vote to lists of those who would vote at home, with the number of such voters being 5% of those who voted, and added this did cause questions if Sobyanin would score 50% if this did not take place.<ref name="forbes moscow navalny">{{Cite news |title=Безусловный рефлекс: сколько сомнительных голосов на выборах мэра Москвы |work=Forbes.ru |url=http://www.forbes.ru/mneniya-column/vertikal/244554-bezuslovnyi-refleks-skolko-somnitelnykh-golosov-na-vyborakh-mera-mosk |url-status=live |access-date=27 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://www.forbes.ru/mneniya-column/vertikal/244554-bezuslovnyi-refleks-skolko-somnitelnykh-golosov-na-vyborakh-mera-mosk |archive-date=31 January 2016}}</ref> Dmitry Oreshkin, leader of the "People's election commission" project (who did a separate counting based on the data from election observers; their result for Sobyanin was 50%), said now that the runoff election was only 2% away, all details would be looked at very closely, and added it was impossible to prove "anything" juridically.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ru:Политолог Д.Орешкин: Выборы мэра Москвы были в 10 раз честнее думских :: Политика :: РосБизнесКонсалтинг|url=http://top.rbc.ru/politics/12/09/2013/876284.shtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003135130/http://top.rbc.ru/politics/12/09/2013/876284.shtml|archive-date=3 October 2013|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Top.rbc.ru}}</ref>

On 9 September, the day following the election, Navalny publicly denounced the tally, saying, "We do not recognise the results. They are fake". Sobyanin's office rejected an offer of a vote recount.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Анастасия Агамалова|author2=Наталья Райбман|author3=Алексей Никольский|script-title=ru:На Болотной площади прошел митинг в поддержку Навального|url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2013/09/09/na-bolotnoj-ploschadi-nachinaetsya-miting-v-podderzhku|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105232516/http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2013/09/09/na-bolotnoj-ploschadi-nachinaetsya-miting-v-podderzhku|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|work=Vedomosti|date=9 September 2013 }}</ref> On 12 September, Navalny addressed the [[Moscow City Court]] to overturn the result of the poll; the court rejected the assertion. Navalny then challenged the decision in the [[Supreme Court of Russia]], but the court ruled that the election results were legitimate.<ref>{{cite web|date=21 December 2015|script-title=ru:Верховный суд не согласился отменить итоги выборов мэра Москвы|url=http://www.vesti.ru/doc.html?id=1163249|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105143823/http://www.vesti.ru/doc.html?id=1163249|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Vesti.ru}}</ref>

=== RPR-PARNAS and democratic coalition ===
Following the mayoral election, Navalny was offered a position as the fourth co-chairman of [[People's Freedom Party (Russia)|RPR-PARNAS]].<ref>{{cite web|date=8 October 2013|script-title=ru:От Навального требуют конкретики/ Политика / Независимая газета|url=http://www.ng.ru/politics/2013-10-08/1_navalny.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://www.ng.ru/politics/2013-10-08/1_navalny.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Ng.ru}}</ref> On 14 November 2014, the two remaining RPR-PARNAS co-chairmen, [[Boris Nemtsov]] and former Prime Minister of Russia [[Mikhail Kasyanov]], declared it was the right moment to create a wide coalition of political forces, who favour the "European choice"; Navalny's [[Progress Party (Russia)|Progress Party]] was seen as one of the potential participants.<ref>{{cite news|date=14 November 2014|script-title=ru:Демократы улучили момент для объединения|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2609667|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208053502/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2609667|archive-date=8 December 2015|access-date=27 December 2015|newspaper=Kommersant}}</ref> However, on 27 February 2015, [[Assassination of Boris Nemtsov|Nemtsov was shot dead]]. Prior to his assassination, Nemtsov worked on a project of a coalition, in which Navalny and Khodorkovsky would become co-chairmen of RPR-PARNAS. Navalny declared merging parties would invoke bureaucratic difficulties and question the legitimacy of party's right to participate in federal elections without signatures collecting.<ref>{{cite news|date=18 April 2015|title=Михаил Касьянов и Алексей Навальный пошли на новое объединение|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2712281|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208062236/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2712281|archive-date=8 December 2015|access-date=27 December 2015|newspaper=Kommersant}}</ref> However, Nemtsov's murder accelerated the work, and on 17 April, Navalny declared a wide discussion had taken place among Progress Party, RPR-PARNAS, and other closely aligned parties, which resulted in an agreement of formation of a new [[Electoral alliance|electoral bloc]] between the two leaders.<ref name="elect"/> Soon thereafter, it was signed by four other parties and supported by Khodorkovsky's [[Open Russia]] foundation.<ref>{{cite web|date=20 April 2015|script-title=ru:Алексей Навальный – Демократическая коалиция. Уже шесть партий и конкретные планы|url=https://navalny.com/p/4207/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/https://navalny.com/p/4207/|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Navalny.com}}</ref> Electoral blocs are not present within the current{{when|date=August 2022}} law system of Russia, so it would be realised via means of a single party, RPR-PARNAS, which is not only eligible for participation in statewide elections, but is also currently{{when|date=August 2022}} not required to collect citizens' signatures for the right to participate in the State Duma elections scheduled for September 2016, due to the regional parliament mandate previously taken by Nemtsov. The candidates RPR-PARNAS would appoint were to be chosen via [[Partisan primary|primary election]]s.<ref>{{cite news|date=17 April 2015|script-title=ru:Алексей Навальный – Разворот|url=https://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/razvorot/1532392-echo/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419221215/https://www.echo.msk.ru/programs/razvorot/1532392-echo/|archive-date=19 April 2015|access-date=20 April 2015|publisher=Echo of Moscow|language=ru}}</ref>

On 5 July 2015, Kasyanov was elected as the only leader of RPR-PARNAS, and the party was renamed to just PARNAS. He added he would like to eventually re-establish the institution of co-chairmanship, adding, "Neither Alexei Navalny nor Mikhail Khodorkovsky will enter our party today and be elected as co-chairmen. But in the future, I think, such time will come".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2015/07/05/n_7349337.shtml|title=Касьянов: в будущем РПР-ПАРНАС могут возглавить Навальный и Ходорковский – Газета.Ru &#124; Новости|website=Газета.Ru|access-date=14 May 2022|archive-date=14 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220514053911/https://www.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2015/07/05/n_7349337.shtml|url-status=live}}</ref> On 7 July, in an interview released by [[TV Rain]], he specified Navalny could not leave a party of his, and this would need to be completed by PARNAS adsorbing members of the Progress Party and other parties of the coalition, and Navalny would be to come at some point when he "grows into this and feels this could be done" and join the party as well.<ref>{{Cite web |title="Режим рухнет неизбежно – он не может больше управлять ни экономикой, ни внутренней и внешней политикой" |date=7 July 2015 |url=http://tvrain.ru/teleshow/harddaysnight/rezhim_ruhnet_neizbezhno_on_ne_mozhet_bolshe_uprav-390615/ |publisher=TV Rain |access-date=20 July 2015 |archive-date=28 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728074446/http://tvrain.ru/teleshow/harddaysnight/rezhim_ruhnet_neizbezhno_on_ne_mozhet_bolshe_uprav-390615/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
[[File:Alexei Navalny marching in 2017.jpg|thumb|[[2017 Russian protests|Protesters]] marching along Moscow's [[Tverskaya Street]], 26 March 2017]]

The coalition claimed to have collected enough citizens' signatures for registration in the four regions it originally aimed for. However, in one region, the coalition would declare some signatures and personal data have been altered by malevolent collectors;<ref>{{Cite news |title=ПАРНАС отказалась от выборов в Калужской области |url=https://slon.ru/posts/54704 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105061445/https://slon.ru/posts/54704 |archive-date=5 January 2016 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Slon.ru}}</ref> signatures in the other regions have been rejected by regional election commissions.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shvets |first=Dmitry |date=27 July 2015 |title=Новосибирский облизбирком отказался регистрировать Демократическую коалицию |trans-title=Novosibirsk regional election commission refused to register the Democratic coalition |url=https://slon.ru/posts/54478 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105053437/https://slon.ru/posts/54478 |archive-date=5 January 2016 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Slon.ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=ПАРНАС сняли с выборов в Магадане |url=https://slon.ru/posts/54710 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105045827/https://slon.ru/posts/54710 |archive-date=5 January 2016 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Slon.ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=ПАРНАС сняли с выборов в Костромской области |url=https://slon.ru/posts/54956 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105045403/https://slon.ru/posts/54956 |archive-date=5 January 2016 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Slon.ru}}</ref> In [[Novosibirsk Oblast]], some election office staff went on a hunger strike, which was abandoned almost two weeks since its inception, when Khodorkovsky, Navalny, and Kasyanov publicly advised to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slon.ru/posts/54954|title=Активисты ПАРНАС прекратили голодовку в Новосибирске|website=slon.ru|access-date=9 August 2015|archive-date=20 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151020032339/https://slon.ru/posts/54954|url-status=live}}</ref> Сomplaints have been issued to the [[Central Election Commission of Russia]], after which the coalition has been registered as a participant in a regional election in one of the three contested regions, [[Kostroma Oblast]]. According to a source of ''[[Gazeta.ru]]'' "close to the Kremlin", the presidential administration saw coalition's chances as very low, yet was wary, but the restoration in one region occurred so PARNAS could "score a consolation goal".<ref>{{cite news|date=13 August 2015|title=ЦИК обязал избирком Костромской области рассмотреть вопрос о регистрации Демкоалиции|newspaper=Gazeta.ru|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/2015/08/13_a_7685512.shtml|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105133622/http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/2015/08/13_a_7685512.shtml|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> According to the official election results, the coalition scored 2% of votes, not enough to overcome the 5% threshold; the party admitted the election was lost.<ref>{{cite web|title=Озвучены окончательные результаты ПАРНАСа на выборах в Костромской области|url=http://www.vz.ru/news/2015/9/14/766862.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916231249/http://www.vz.ru/news/2015/9/14/766862.html|archive-date=16 September 2015|access-date=20 September 2015|website=vz.ru}}</ref>

=== 2018 presidential election ===
{{main|2018 Alexei Navalny presidential campaign}}

[[File:(Group 0)-20170916 190038 20170916 190056-8 images4d9.jpg|left|622x622px|thumb|Navalny meeting his followers in [[Yekaterinburg]] on 16 September 2017]]
With growing popular support Navalny announced his entry into the presidential race on 13 December 2016,<ref>{{cite news|last=Pertsev|first=Andrey|date=13 December 2016|title=Алексей Навальный намерен участвовать в президентских выборах|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3169689|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228103555/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3169689|archive-date=28 February 2017|access-date=11 February 2017|newspaper=Kommersant}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wkN8sSrUbdY|title=Пора выбирать: Алексей Навальный – кандидат в президенты России|date=13 December 2016|last=Alexei Navalny |access-date=11 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212071405/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wkN8sSrUbdY|archive-date=12 February 2017|url-status=live|via=YouTube}}</ref> however on 8 February 2017, the Leninsky district court of Kirov repeated its sentence of 2013 (after the case has been sent to a new trial with a different judge by the Supreme Court which annulled the initial sentence after the decision of [[European Court of Human Rights|ECHR]], which ruled that Russia had violated Navalny's right to a fair trial, in [[#Kirovles case|the Kirovles case]]) and re-sentenced him with a five-year suspended sentence.<ref name="VOA">{{cite news|last=Galperovich|first=Danila|date=8 February 2017|title=Navalny was re-sentenced to a suspended sentence in the 'Kirovles case'|publisher=RFE/RL|website=[[Voice of America]]|url=https://www.golos-ameriki.ru/a/dg-navalny-decision/3714420.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211083556/http://www.golos-ameriki.ru/a/dg-navalny-decision/3714420.html|archive-date=11 February 2017}}</ref> This sentence, if it came into force and remained valid, might prohibit the future official registration of Navalny as a candidate. Navalny announced that he would pursue the annulment of the sentence that clearly contradicts the decision of ECHR. Moreover, Navalny announced that his presidential campaign would proceed independently of court decisions. He referred to the Russian Constitution (Article 32), which deprives only two groups of citizens of the right to be elected: those recognised by the court as legally unfit and those kept in places of confinement by a court sentence. According to [[Freedom House]] and ''[[The Economist]]'', Navalny was the most viable contender to Vladimir Putin in the 2018 election.<ref name="disqualify">{{cite web|date=29 January 2019|title=Russia|url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2019/russia|archive-url=https://archive.today/20191116225413/https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2019/russia|archive-date=16 November 2019|access-date=16 November 2019|publisher=[[Freedom House]]|quote=His most potent rival, Aleksey Navalny, had been disqualified before the campaign began due to a politically motivated criminal conviction, creating what the Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) called "a lack of genuine competition."}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=16 June 2017|title=Aleksei Navalny's protesters are a force to be reckoned with|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21723439-anti-corruption-activist-chief-threat-vladimir-putin-next-years-election-aleksei|url-status=live|access-date=16 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616005722/https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21723439-anti-corruption-activist-chief-threat-vladimir-putin-next-years-election-aleksei|archive-date=16 June 2017}}</ref> Navalny organised a series of anti-corruption rallies in different cities across Russia in March. This appeal was responded to by the representatives of 95 Russian cities, and four cities abroad: London, Prague, Basel and Bonn.<ref>{{cite news|date=23 March 2017|title=Мы ждем перемен?|trans-title=We are waiting for changes?|publisher=[[:ru:Росбалт|Rosbalt]]|url=http://www.rosbalt.ru/russia/2017/03/23/1601435.html|url-status=live|access-date=7 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170619160806/http://www.rosbalt.ru/russia/2017/03/23/1601435.html|archive-date=19 June 2017}}</ref>

[[File:Alexey Navalny and people of Yekaterinburg (24705173428).jpg|thumb|Navalny's campaign rally in Yekaterinburg, 16 September 2017]]
Navalny was attacked by unknown assailants outside his office in the Anti-Corruption Foundation on 27 April 2017. They sprayed [[Brilliant green (dye)|brilliant green dye]], possibly mixed with other components, into his face in a [[Zelyonka attack]] that can damage eyes of the victim. He had been attacked before, earlier in the spring. In the second attack, the green-colored [[Brilliant green (dye)|disinfectant]] had evidently been mixed with a caustic chemical, resulting in a [[chemical burn]] to his right eye.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=2 May 2017|title=Kremlin Critic Aleksei Navalny Says Attack Left Him Mostly Blind in an Eye (Published 2017)|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/02/world/europe/russia-aleksei-navalny-opposition.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210130214549/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/02/world/europe/russia-aleksei-navalny-opposition.html|archive-date=30 January 2021|access-date=8 February 2021|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He reportedly lost 80 percent of the sight in his right eye.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/a/russia-navalny-files-complaint-police-failure-investigate-attack/28464133.html|title=Navalny Accuses Police Of Failing To Investigate Attack|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502194653/http://www.rferl.org/a/russia-navalny-files-complaint-police-failure-investigate-attack/28464133.html|archive-date=2 May 2017|publisher=RFE/RL}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/what-is-zelyonka/28463920.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502210837/http://www.rferl.org/a/what-is-zelyonka/28463920.html|title=Zelyonka: The Green 'Weapon Of Choice'|archive-date=2 May 2017|publisher=RFE/RL}}</ref> Navalny accused the Kremlin of orchestrating the attack.<ref>{{cite news|date=2 May 2017|title=Navalny Sues Police, Loses Vision in One Eye, and Launches New Manhunt|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://themoscowtimes.com/news/following-attack-navalny-sues-police-loses-80-percent-of-his-vision-in-one-eye-and-launches-new-manhunt-57882|url-status=live|access-date=4 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502233013/https://themoscowtimes.com/news/following-attack-navalny-sues-police-loses-80-percent-of-his-vision-in-one-eye-and-launches-new-manhunt-57882|archive-date=2 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2 May 2017|title=Alexei Navalny, Putin foe, claims vision loss after chemical attack; blames Kremlin|newspaper=The Washington Post|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/may/2/alexei-navalny-putin-foe-claims-vision-loss-after-/|url-status=live|access-date=4 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504132246/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/may/2/alexei-navalny-putin-foe-claims-vision-loss-after-/|archive-date=4 May 2017}}</ref>

Navalny was released from jail on 27 July 2017 after spending 25 days of imprisonment. Before that, he was arrested in Moscow for participating in protests and was sentenced to 30 days in jail for organising illegal protests.<ref>{{cite news|date=7 July 2017|title=Russian opposition leader Navalny released from prison|publisher=Politico|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/alexei-navalny-released-from-prison-russia/|url-status=live|access-date=7 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818174432/http://www.politico.eu/article/alexei-navalny-released-from-prison-russia/|archive-date=18 August 2017}}</ref>

In September 2017, [[Human Rights Watch]] accused Russian police of systematic interference with Navalny's presidential campaign. "The pattern of harassment and intimidation against Navalny's campaign is undeniable," said Hugh Williamson, Europe, and Central Asia director at Human Rights Watch. "Russian authorities should let Navalny's campaigners work without undue interference and properly investigate attacks against them by ultra-nationalists and pro-government groups."<ref>{{cite news|date=6 September 2017|title=Russia: Nationwide Assaults on Political Opposition Campaign|work=Human Rights Watch|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/09/06/russia-nationwide-assaults-political-opposition-campaign|url-status=live|access-date=14 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019180405/https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/09/06/russia-nationwide-assaults-political-opposition-campaign|archive-date=19 October 2017}}</ref> On 21 September, the [[Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe]] invited Russian authorities, in connection with the [[#Kirovles case|Kirovles case]], "to use urgently further avenues to erase the prohibition on Mr. Navalny's standing for election".<ref>{{cite web|date=21 September 2017|title=H46-25 Navalnyy and Ofitserov v. Russian Federation (Application No. 46632/13)|url=https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectID=090000168074a249|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923002911/https://search.coe.int/cm/Pages/result_details.aspx?ObjectID=090000168074a249|archive-date=23 September 2017|publisher=[[Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe]]}}</ref>

Navalny was sentenced to 20 days in jail on 2 October 2017 for calls to participate in protests without approval from state authorities.<ref>{{cite web|date=2 October 2017|script-title=ru:Алексей Навальный арестован на 20 суток|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3427702|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003075038/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3427702|archive-date=3 October 2017|access-date=2 October 2017|newspaper=Kommersant|language=ru}}</ref>

[[File:Алексей Навальный и Иван Жданов на заседании Центральной избирательной комиссии, 25 декабря 2017 года.jpg|thumb|[[Roman Rubanov]], Navalny and [[Ivan Zhdanov]] at a meeting of the [[Central Election Commission (Russia)|Central Election Commission]] in December 2017]]
In December 2017, Russia's Central Electoral Commission barred Navalny from running for president in 2018, citing Navalny's corruption conviction. The European Union said Navalny's removal cast "serious doubt" on the election. Navalny called for a boycott of the 2018 presidential election, stating his removal meant that millions of Russians were being denied their vote.<ref name="bbc boycott">{{cite news|date=26 December 2017|title=Kremlin queries legality of boycott call|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42486355|url-status=live|access-date=26 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226145814/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42486355|archive-date=26 December 2017}}</ref> Navalny filed an appeal against the Russian Supreme Court's ruling on 3 January,<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ru:Навальный обжаловал решение Верховного суда о недопуске на выборы|url=https://www.rbc.ru/politics/03/01/2018/5a4ccb199a79474c39099792|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105122358/https://www.rbc.ru/politics/03/01/2018/5a4ccb199a79474c39099792|archive-date=5 January 2018|access-date=6 January 2018|website=РБК|date=3 January 2018 }}</ref> however a few days later on 6 January, the [[Supreme Court of Russia]] rejected his appeal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Supreme Court Rejects Navalny Appeal On Presidential Election Ban|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-supreme-court-rejects-navalny-appeal/28959277.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106140427/https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-supreme-court-rejects-navalny-appeal/28959277.html|archive-date=6 January 2018|access-date=6 January 2018|publisher=RFE/RL}}</ref>

Navalny led protests on 28 January 2018 to urge a boycott of the presidential election. Navalny was arrested on the day of the protest and then released the same day, pending trial. OVD-Info reported that 257 people were arrested throughout the country. According to Russian news reports, police stated Navalny was likely to be charged with calling for unauthorised demonstrations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Heintz|first=Jim|date=28 January 2018|title=Russian opposition leader arrested amid election protests|newspaper=The Washington Post|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/russian-opposition-leader-arrested-amid-election-protests/2018/01/28/481754a0-049a-11e8-aa61-f3391373867e_story.html|access-date=29 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129045830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/russian-opposition-leader-arrested-amid-election-protests/2018/01/28/481754a0-049a-11e8-aa61-f3391373867e_story.html|archive-date=29 January 2018}}</ref> Two of Navalny's associates were given brief jail terms for urging people to attend unsanctioned opposition rallies. Navalny stated on 5 February 2018 the government was accusing Navalny of assaulting an officer during the protests.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bennetts|first=Marc|date=5 February 2018|title=Russian police accuse Navalny of assaulting officer during protest|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/05/russia-police-accuse-navalny-of-assaulting-officer-during-protest|url-status=live|access-date=8 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208023539/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/05/russia-police-accuse-navalny-of-assaulting-officer-during-protest|archive-date=8 February 2018}}</ref> Navalny was among 1600 people detained during 5 May protests prior to Putin's inauguration; Navalny was charged with disobeying police.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bennetts|first=Marc|date=5 May 2018|title=Russia's Alexei Navalny arrested as 1,600 detained nationwide|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/05/russian-police-arrest-more-than-200-anti-putin-protesters-siberia|url-status=live|access-date=7 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180507014302/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/05/russian-police-arrest-more-than-200-anti-putin-protesters-siberia|archive-date=7 May 2018}}</ref> On 15 May, he was sentenced to 30 days in jail.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ivanova|first=Polina|date=15 May 2018|title=Russian opposition leader Navalny jailed for 30 days over protest|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-navalny/russian-opposition-leader-navalny-jailed-for-30-days-over-protest-idUSKCN1IG26F|url-status=live|access-date=24 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517152608/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-navalny/russian-opposition-leader-navalny-jailed-for-30-days-over-protest-idUSKCN1IG26F|archive-date=17 May 2018}}</ref> Immediately after his release on 25 September 2018, he was arrested and convicted for organising illegal demonstrations and sentenced to another 20 days in jail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSKCN1M42GB/|title=Russian court sentences opposition leader Navalny to 20 days in jail|website=[[Reuters]] }}</ref>

=== 2019 Moscow City Duma elections ===
{{See also|2019 Moscow City Duma election|2019 Moscow protests}}
[[File:Rally for right to vote in Moscow (2019-08-10) 144559.jpg|left|thumb|Rally for right to vote in Moscow (10 August 2019)]]
During the [[2019 Moscow City Duma election]] Navalny supported independent candidates, most of whom were not allowed to participate in the elections, which led to mass street protests. In July 2019, Navalny was arrested, first for ten days, and then, almost immediately, for 30 days. On the evening of 28 July, he was hospitalised with severe damage to his eyes and skin. At the hospital, he was diagnosed with an "allergy," although this diagnosis was disputed by [[Anastasia Vasilyeva]], an ophthalmologist who previously treated Navalny after a chemical attack by an alleged protester in 2017.<ref name="guardian-29-jul">{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Shaun|date=29 July 2019|title=Alexei Navalny discharged from hospital against wishes of doctor|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/29/russian-opposition-leader-alexei-navalny-may-have-been-poisoned-says-doctor|url-status=live|access-date=29 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729105636/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/29/russian-opposition-leader-alexei-navalny-may-have-been-poisoned-says-doctor|archive-date=29 July 2019}}</ref> Vasilyeva questioned the diagnosis and suggested the possibility that Navalny's condition was the result of "the damaging effects of undetermined chemicals".<ref name="meduza-29-jul">{{cite news |last=Kovalev |first=Alexey |author-link=Alexey Kovalev (journalist) |date=29 July 2019 |title=Discharge, itching, and lesions: Doctors disagree about why Russia's jailed opposition leader needed to be hospitalised |website=[[Meduza]] |url=https://meduza.io/en/feature/2019/07/29/discharge-itching-and-lesions |url-status=live |access-date=29 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729075020/https://meduza.io/en/feature/2019/07/29/discharge-itching-and-lesions |archive-date=29 July 2019}}</ref> On 29 July 2019, Navalny was discharged from hospital and taken back to prison, despite the objections of his personal physician who questioned the hospital's motives.<ref name="guardian-29-jul"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Pleitgen|first1=Fred|last2=Ilyushina|first2=Mary|last3=Hodge|first3=Nathan|last4=Shukla|first4=Sebastian|title=Kremlin critic Alexei Navalny is hospitalized after being detained|publisher=[[CNN]]|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/28/europe/alexei-navalny-hospitalized-intl/index.html|url-status=live|access-date=30 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729073932/https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/28/europe/alexei-navalny-hospitalized-intl/index.html|archive-date=29 July 2019}}</ref> Supporters of Navalny and journalists near the hospital were attacked by the police and many were detained.<ref name="meduza-29-jul"/> In response, he initiated the [[Smart Voting]] project.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/09/13/europe/russia-regional-elections-intl/index.html |title=Russia's regional elections pose serious test for pro-Kremlin party |website=[[CNN]] |date=13 September 2020 |access-date=7 February 2021 |archive-date=27 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200927225132/https://www.cnn.com/2020/09/13/europe/russia-regional-elections-intl/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== 2020 constitutional referendum ===
{{See also|2020 Russian constitutional referendum}}
Navalny campaigned against the [[2020 Russian constitutional referendum|vote on constitutional amendments]] that took place on 1 July, calling it a "coup" and a "violation of the constitution".<ref name="bbc-2020">{{cite news|date=20 August 2020|title=Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny 'poisoned'|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53844958|url-status=live|access-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200820094717/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53844958|archive-date=20 August 2020}}</ref> He also said that the changes would allow President Putin to become "[[president for life]]".<ref>{{cite news|date=25 June 2020|title=Russians vote on Putin's reforms to constitution|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53176061|url-status=live|access-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200711031411/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53176061|archive-date=11 July 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gershkovich|first=Evan|date=10 March 2020|title='President for Life': Putin Opens Door to Extending Rule until 2036|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/10/president-for-life-putin-opens-door-to-extending-rule-until-2036-a69576|url-status=live|access-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200608173921/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/03/10/president-for-life-putin-opens-door-to-extending-rule-until-2036-a69576|archive-date=8 June 2020}}</ref> After the results were announced, he called them a "big lie" that did not reflect public opinion.<ref>{{cite news|date=2 July 2020|title=Putin strongly backed in controversial Russian reform vote|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53255964|url-status=live|access-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200713115630/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53255964|archive-date=13 July 2020}}</ref> The reforms include an amendment allowing Putin to serve another two terms in office (until 2036), after his [[Vladimir Putin#2018–present: Fourth presidential term|fourth presidential term]] ends.<ref name="bbc-2020"/>

==Anti-corruption investigations==
{{See also|Anti-Corruption Foundation}}
In 2008, Navalny sought to become an [[activist shareholder]] in five Russian oil and gas companies ([[Rosneft]], [[Gazprom]], [[Gazprom Neft]], [[Lukoil]], and [[Surgutneftegas]]), investing 300,000 rubles with the ultimate goal of increasing the transparency of their financial assets.<ref name="vedomosti">{{Cite news |last1=Mokrousova |first1=Irina |last2=Reznik |first2=Irina |date=13 February 2012 |title=Чем зарабатывает на жизнь Алексей Навальный |trans-title=How does Alexei Navalny make a living |url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/library/articles/2012/02/13/pesnya_o_blogere |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124004326/http://www.vedomosti.ru/library/articles/2012/02/13/pesnya_o_blogere |archive-date=24 November 2015 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=[[Vedomosti]]}}</ref> Such transparency is required by law, but there are allegations that high-level managers of these companies are involved in theft and resisting transparency.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vasilyeva|first=Nataliya|date=1 April 2010|title=Activist presses Russian corporations for openness|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|agency=Associated Press|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2011498772_apeurussiacorporategadfly.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814214542/http://old.seattletimes.com/html/businesstechnology/2011498772_apeurussiacorporategadfly.html|archive-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>

In November 2010, Navalny published<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ru:Как пилят в Транснефти|url=http://navalny.livejournal.com/526563.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131232434/http://navalny.livejournal.com/526563.html|archive-date=31 January 2011|access-date=9 February 2011|publisher=[[LiveJournal]]|language=ru}}</ref> confidential documents about [[Transneft]]'s auditing. According to Navalny's blog, about US$4&nbsp;billion were stolen by Transneft's leaders during the construction of the [[Eastern Siberia–Pacific Ocean oil pipeline]].<ref>{{cite news|date=17 November 2010|title=Russia checks claims of $4bn oil pipeline scam|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-11779154|url-status=live|access-date=9 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125061750/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-11779154|archive-date=25 November 2010}}</ref><ref name="reuters140111">{{cite news|last=Soldatkin|first=Vladimir|date=14 January 2011|title=Russia's Transneft denies $4 bln theft|publisher=Reuters|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/transneft-shareholder-idUKLDE70C1PF20110114|url-status=dead|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20121208195249/http://uk.reuters.com/article/2011/01/14/transneft-shareholder-idUKLDE70C1PF20110114|archive-date=8 December 2012}}</ref> In December, Navalny announced the launch of the {{Interlanguage link|RosPil|ru|РосПил}} project, which seeks to bring to light corrupt practices in the government procurement process.<ref>{{cite web|last=Navalny|first=Alexei|date=29 December 2010|title=RosPil|url=http://navalny.livejournal.com/541417.html?thread=56716521|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217145517/http://navalny.livejournal.com/541417.html?thread=56716521|archive-date=17 February 2012|access-date=26 June 2012|website=Navalny Live Journal Blog|language=ru}}</ref> The project takes advantage of existing procurement regulation that requires all government requests for tender to be posted online. Information about winning bids must be posted online as well. The name RosPil is a pun on the slang term "[[wikt:распил|распил]]" (literally "sawing"),<ref>{{cite news|last=Parfitt|first=Tom|date=21 August 2020|title=Alexei Navalny profile: Scourge of Kremlin cronies has long list of powerful enemies|newspaper=[[The Times]]|publication-place=Moscow|url=https://www.thetimes.com/uk/politics/article/alexei-navalny-profile-scourge-of-the-powerful-is-never-short-of-enemies-gwbkftl9c|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|access-date=11 February 2021|archive-url=https://archive.today/20210211224227/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/alexei-navalny-profile-scourge-of-the-powerful-is-never-short-of-enemies-gwbkftl9c|archive-date=11 February 2021|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> implying the embezzlement of state funds.<ref>{{Cite news |date=16 February 2024 |title=Alexei Navalny, Russian opposition leader who galvanised huge protests against Putin – obituary |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2024/02/16/alexei-navalny-putin-opposition-russia-poison/ |access-date=16 February 2024 |work=The Telegraph |language=en-GB |issn=0307-1235 |quote=Navalny then formalised this project under the name RosPil, a pun on the Russian word for sawdust, or money illegally appropriated. |archive-date=17 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240217044919/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2024/02/16/alexei-navalny-putin-opposition-russia-poison/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2011, Navalny launched RosYama (literally "Russian Hole"), a project that allowed individuals to report potholes and track government responses to complaints.<ref>{{cite web|last=Navalny|first=Alexei|date=30 May 2011|title=RosYama|url=http://navalny.livejournal.com/589343.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215185059/http://navalny.livejournal.com/589343.html|archive-date=15 February 2012|access-date=22 June 2012|language=ru}}</ref> In August, Navalny published papers related to a scandalous real estate deal<ref>{{cite news|last=Ablonczy|first=Bálint|date=23 July 2012|title=It's ugly, but it was ours|publisher=Hetivalasz|url=http://hetivalasz.hu/english_world_affairs/its-ugly-but-it-was-ours-25964|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711034903/http://hetivalasz.hu/english_world_affairs/its-ugly-but-it-was-ours-25964|archive-date=11 July 2012}}</ref> between the Hungarian and Russian governments.<ref>{{cite web|date=3 August 2011|script-title=ru:Инновационные технологии: как это работает на самом деле|url=http://navalny.livejournal.com/609880.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625133702/http://navalny.livejournal.com/609880.html|archive-date=25 June 2012|access-date=31 July 2012|publisher=Navalny Live Journal|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Potts|first=Andy|date=21 February 2011|title=Vekselberg faces questions over Hungarian property fraud|work=The Moscow News |url=http://themoscownews.com/business/20110221/188433935.html|url-status=live|access-date=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731103323/http://themoscownews.com/business/20110221/188433935.html|archive-date=31 July 2012}}</ref> According to the papers, Hungary sold a former embassy building in Moscow for US$21&nbsp;million to an offshore company of [[Viktor Vekselberg]], who immediately resold it to the Russian government for US$116&nbsp;million. The property's real value was estimated at US$52&nbsp;million. Irregularities in the paper trail implied collusion. Three Hungarian officials responsible for the deal were detained in February 2011.<ref>{{cite web|date=16 February 2011|title=Hungary: detentions linked to the sale of property in Moscow|url=https://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/analyses/2011-02-16/hungary-detentions-linked-to-sale-property-moscow |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601080940/http://www.osw.waw.pl/en/publikacje/ceweekly/2011-02-16/hungary-detentions-linked-to-sale-property-moscow|archive-date=1 June 2013|access-date=19 July 2013|publisher=OSW}}</ref>

Navalny was founder of the [[Anti-Corruption Foundation]] (FBK).<ref name="Foy">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/82ff1707-fd44-43e8-887d-85d02a656e6b|title=Russia outlaws Alexei Navalny's organisations as 'extremist'|website=Financial Times|author1=Henry Foy|author2=Aime Williams|date=10 June 2021|access-date=21 February 2024|archive-date=10 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210610000646/https://www.ft.com/content/82ff1707-fd44-43e8-887d-85d02a656e6b|url-status=live}}</ref>

In February 2012, Navalny concluded that Russian federal money going to [[Ramzan Kadyrov]]'s [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Chechnya)|Chechen Interior Ministry]] was being spent "in a totally shadowy and fraudulent way."<ref>{{cite journal|date=10 February 2012|title=Anti-Corruption Blogger Navalny Takes On Chechnya's Kadyrov|journal=North Caucasus Weekly|volume=13|issue=4|url=https://jamestown.org/program/anti-corruption-blogger-navalny-takes-on-chechnyas-kadyrov/|access-date=4 September 2020|archive-date=4 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200804100129/https://jamestown.org/program/anti-corruption-blogger-navalny-takes-on-chechnyas-kadyrov/|url-status=live}}</ref> In May, Navalny accused Deputy Prime Minister [[Igor Shuvalov]] of corruption, stating that companies owned by [[Roman Abramovich]] and [[Alisher Usmanov]] had transferred tens of millions of dollars to Shuvalov's company, allowing Shuvalov to share in the profit from Usmanov's purchase of the British steel company [[Tata Steel Europe|Corus]]. Navalny posted scans of documents to his blog showing the money transfers.<ref>{{cite news|date=30 March 2012|title=Russian whistleblower accuses Putin's investment czar of multimillion dollar corruption|newspaper=The Washington Post|agency=Associated Press|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/whistleblower-accuses-putins-ally-corruption-095920861.html|url-status=live|access-date=30 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413150123/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/whistleblower-accuses-putins-ally-corruption-095920861.html|archive-date=13 April 2014}}</ref> Usmanov and Shuvalov stated the documents Navalny had posted were legitimate, but that the transaction had not violated Russian law. "I unswervingly followed the rules and principles of conflict of interest," said Shuvalov. "For a lawyer, this is sacred".<ref name="nyt-30-mar">{{cite news|author=Andrew E. Kramer|date=30 March 2012|title=Activist Presses for Inquiry into Senior Putin Deputy|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/31/world/europe/navalny-presses-for-inquiry-into-putin-deputy.html|url-status=live|access-date=29 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508203527/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/31/world/europe/navalny-presses-for-inquiry-into-putin-deputy.html|archive-date=8 May 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In July, Navalny posted documents on his blog allegedly showing that [[Alexander Bastrykin]], head of the [[Investigative Committee of Russia]], owned an undeclared business in the [[Czech Republic]]. The posting was described by the ''[[Financial Times]]'' as Navalny's "answering shot" for having had his emails leaked during his arrest in the previous month.<ref name="data release">{{cite news|last=Clover|first=Charles|date=26 July 2012|title=Blogger strikes at Putin with data release|newspaper=[[Financial Times]]|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/70820f30-d736-11e1-a378-00144feabdc0.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814214540/https://www.ft.com/content/70820f30-d736-11e1-a378-00144feabdc0|archive-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>

[[File:Anti-Corruption Rally in Saint Petersburg (2017-06-12) 69.jpg|thumb|The [[Levada Center]] survey showed that 58% of surveyed Russians supported the [[2017–2018 Russian protests|2017 Russian protests]] against government corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.levada.ru/2017/06/13/aktsii-protesta-12-iyunya/|title=Акции протеста 12 июня|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218004201/http://www.levada.ru/2017/06/13/aktsii-protesta-12-iyunya/|archive-date=18 February 2020|language=ru|website=[[Levada Centre]]|date=13 June 2017}}</ref>]]

In August 2018, Navalny alleged that [[Viktor Zolotov]] stole at least US$29&nbsp;million from procurement contracts for the [[National Guard of Russia]]. Shortly after his allegations against Zolotov, Navalny was imprisoned for staging protests in January 2018. Subsequently, Viktor Zolotov published a video message on 11 September challenging Navalny to a duel and promising to make "good, juicy mincemeat" of him.<ref>{{cite news|date=11 September 2018|title=The director of Russia's National Guard challenges Alexey Navalny to a fistfight|website=Meduza|url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2018/09/11/the-director-of-russia-s-national-guard-challenges-alexey-navalny-to-a-fist-fight|access-date=11 September 2018|archive-date=11 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911191245/https://meduza.io/en/news/2018/09/11/the-director-of-russia-s-national-guard-challenges-alexey-navalny-to-a-fist-fight|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Russian opposition leader injured following detention|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/25/russian-opposition-leader-injured-detention-alexei-navalny-broken-finger|access-date=11 September 2018|archive-date=11 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911091953/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/25/russian-opposition-leader-injured-detention-alexei-navalny-broken-finger|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Medvedev===
{{main|He Is Not Dimon to You}}

In March 2017, Navalny published the investigation ''[[He Is Not Dimon to You]]'', accusing Prime Minister [[Dmitry Medvedev]] of corruption. The authorities either ignored the accusation or argued that it was made by a "convicted criminal" and not worth comment. On 26 March, Navalny organised a series of [[2017–2018 Russian protests|anti-corruption rallies]] in cities across Russia. In some cities, the rallies were sanctioned by authorities, but in others, including Moscow and Saint Petersburg, they were not allowed. The Moscow police said that 500 people had been detained, but according to the human-rights group OVD-Info, 1,030 people were detained in Moscow alone, including Navalny himself.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mortensen|first1=Antonia|last2=Pleitgen|first2=Fred|last3=Rehbein|first3=Matt|date=25 March 2017|title=Kremlin critic detained in tense anti-corruption protests|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/03/26/world/russia-corruption-protests/index.html|url-status=live|access-date=26 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326202546/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/03/26/world/russia-corruption-protests/index.html|archive-date=26 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Walker|first=Shaun|date=27 March 2017|title=Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny jailed after protests|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/27/russian-opposition-leader-alexei-navalny-at-court-following-arrest|url-status=live|access-date=27 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327205156/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/mar/27/russian-opposition-leader-alexei-navalny-at-court-following-arrest|archive-date=27 March 2017}}</ref> On 27 March, he was fined 20,000 rubles minimum for organising an illegal protest, and jailed for 15 days for resisting arrest.<ref>{{cite news|date=27 March 2017|title=Russia jails protests leader Alexei Navalny for 15 days|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-39404985|url-status=live|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721174757/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-39404985|archive-date=21 July 2018}}</ref>

===Putin===
{{main|Putin's Palace (film)}}

[[File:Alexey Navalny at Pushkinskaya Square, May 5th, 2018.jpg|thumb|Navalny and his team organised around 90 "He's Not Our [[Tsar]]" protests across Russia in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=From Kids to Leaders, Russia Cracks Down on Protesters |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2018/05/23/kids-leaders-russia-cracks-down-protesters |work=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=23 May 2018 |access-date=16 February 2024 |archive-date=16 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230916145720/https://www.hrw.org/news/2018/05/23/kids-leaders-russia-cracks-down-protesters |url-status=live }}</ref>]]
On 19 January 2021, two days after he was detained by Russian authorities upon his return to Russia, an investigation by Navalny and the FBK was published accusing President [[Vladimir Putin]] of using fraudulently obtained funds to build a [[Putin's Palace|massive estate]] for himself near the town of [[Gelendzhik]] in [[Krasnodar Krai]], in what he called "the world's biggest bribe". The estate was first reported on in 2010 after the businessman [[Sergei Kolesnikov (whistleblower)|Sergei Kolesnikov]], who was involved in the project, gave details about it. According to Navalny, the estate is 39 times the size of [[Monaco]], with the [[Federal Security Service]] (FSB) owning 70 square kilometers of land around the palace, and the estate cost over 100&nbsp;billion rubles ($1.35&nbsp;billion) to construct.<ref>{{cite web|date=20 January 2021|title=Navalny video: Putin palace claims reach millions for jailed critic|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55732296|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2022|archive-date=21 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210121191936/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55732296|url-status=live}}</ref> It also showed aerial footage of the estate via a drone, and a detailed floor plan of the palace that Navalny and the FBK said was given by a contractor, which was compared to photographs from inside the palace that were leaked onto the Internet in 2011. Using the floorplan, computer-generated visualisations of the palace interior were also shown.<ref name="tmt-putin"/>

{{Blockquote
|text=There are impregnable fences, its own port, its own security, a church, its own permit system, a no-fly zone, and even its own border checkpoint. It is absolutely a separate state within Russia.<ref name="tmt-putin"/>
|author=Alexei Anatolievich Navalny
}}

This investigation also detailed an elaborate corruption scheme allegedly involving Putin's inner circle that allowed Putin to hide billions of dollars to build the estate. Navalny's team also said that it managed to confirm reporting about Putin's alleged lovers Svetlana Krivonogikh and [[Alina Kabaeva]].<ref name="tmt-putin">{{cite web|date=19 January 2021|title=Navalny Targets 'Billion-Dollar Putin Palace' in New Investigation|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/19/navalny-targets-billion-dollar-putin-palace-in-investigation-released-after-jailing-a72661|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=19 January 2021|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119160300/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/19/navalny-targets-billion-dollar-putin-palace-in-investigation-released-after-jailing-a72661|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=19 January 2021|title=ФБК опубликовал огромное расследование о "дворце Путина" в Геленджике. Вот главное из двухчасового фильма о строительстве ценой в 100 миллиардов|trans-title=FBK has published a huge investigation about the "Putin's palace" in Gelendzhik. Here are the highlights from a two-hour movie about a 100-billion-ruble construction|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2021/01/19/fbk-opublikoval-ogromnoe-rassledovanie-o-dvortse-putina-v-gelendzhike-vot-glavnoe-iz-dvuhchasovogo-filma-o-stroitelstve-tsenoy-v-100-milliardov|access-date=19 January 2021|website=Meduza|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119162405/https://meduza.io/feature/2021/01/19/fbk-opublikoval-ogromnoe-rassledovanie-o-dvortse-putina-v-gelendzhike-vot-glavnoe-iz-dvuhchasovogo-filma-o-stroitelstve-tsenoy-v-100-milliardov|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=19 January 2021|title=ФБК опубликовал расследование о "дворце Путина" размером с 39 княжеств Монако|trans-title=FBK has published an investigation about "Putin's palace" the size of 39 principalities of Monaco|url=https://tvrain.ru/news/fbk_opublikoval_rassledovanie_o_dvortse_putina_razmerom_s_39_knjazhestv_monako-522873/|access-date=19 January 2021|publisher=[[TV Rain]]|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119222256/https://tvrain.ru/news/fbk_opublikoval_rassledovanie_o_dvortse_putina_razmerom_s_39_knjazhestv_monako-522873/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=20 January 2021|title=Following the money|url=https://meduza.io/en/feature/2021/01/20/following-the-money|website=Meduza|access-date=20 January 2021|archive-date=20 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120095719/https://meduza.io/en/feature/2021/01/20/following-the-money|url-status=live}}</ref> Navalny's video on YouTube garnered over 20 million views in less than a day, and over 92&nbsp;million after a week. Kremlin spokesman [[Dmitry Peskov]] in a press conference called the investigation a "scam" and said that citizens should "think before transferring money to such crooks".<ref>{{cite web|date=20 January 2021|title="Подумайте перед тем, как переводить деньги таким жуликам". Песков – о расследовании ФБК про "дворец Путина"|url=https://meduza.io/news/2021/01/20/podumayte-pered-tem-kak-perevodit-dengi-takim-zhulikam-peskov-o-rassledovanii-fbk-pro-dvorets-putina|website=Meduza|access-date=20 January 2021|archive-date=20 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120100635/https://meduza.io/news/2021/01/20/podumayte-pered-tem-kak-perevodit-dengi-takim-zhulikam-peskov-o-rassledovanii-fbk-pro-dvorets-putina|url-status=live}}</ref>

Putin denied ownership of the palace and the oligarch [[Arkady Rotenberg]], Putin's childhood friend and judo partner, claimed ownership.<ref>{{cite web|date=30 January 2021|title=Putin's former judo partner says he owns palace linked to Russian leader|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jan/30/vladimir-putin-former-judo-partner-says-he-owns-palace-linked-to-russian-leader|access-date=30 January 2021|newspaper=The Guardian|archive-date=30 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210130165914/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jan/30/vladimir-putin-former-judo-partner-says-he-owns-palace-linked-to-russian-leader|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=30 January 2021|title=Russian billionaire Arkady Rotenberg says 'Putin Palace' is his|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55872249|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2022|archive-date=7 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211207113307/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55872249|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Criminal cases ==
=== Kirovles case ===

==== Case ====
[[File:Алексей Навальный в зале Ленинского суда Кирова.JPG|thumb|left|Navalny in court as part of the Kirovles trial, 2013]]
On 30 July 2012, the [[Investigative Committee of Russia|Investigative Committee]] charged Navalny with embezzlement. The committee stated that he had conspired to steal timber from Kirovles, a state-owned company in [[Kirov Oblast]], in 2009, while acting as an adviser to Kirov's governor [[Nikita Belykh]].<ref name="nyt-30-mar"/><ref name="BBC317">{{cite news|date=31 July 2012|title=Russian blogger Navalny charged with embezzlement|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-19060444|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731184600/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-19060444|archive-date=31 July 2012}}</ref> Investigators had closed a previous probe into the claims for lack of evidence.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexey Navalny: An archenemy Putin wouldn't name and Kremlin couldn't scare |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2024/2/16/obit-navalny-putins-archenemy-and-anti-corruption-champion |website=aljazeera.com |publisher=Aljazeera |access-date=16 February 2024 |archive-date=16 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240216142028/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2024/2/16/obit-navalny-putins-archenemy-and-anti-corruption-champion |url-status=live }}</ref> Navalny was released on his own recognisance but instructed not to leave Moscow.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barry|first=Ellen|date=31 July 2012|title=Russian Prosecutors Charge Protest Movement Leader|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/01/world/europe/aleksei-navalny-charged-with-embezzlement.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731152240/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/01/world/europe/aleksei-navalny-charged-with-embezzlement.html|archive-date=31 July 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

Navalny described the charges as "weird" and unfounded.<ref>{{cite news|date=31 July 2012|title=Putin critic Navalny charged with theft|publisher=Al Jazeera|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2012/07/201273115211951682.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801095056/http://www.aljazeera.com//news/europe/2012/07/201273115211951682.html|archive-date=1 August 2012}}</ref> He stated that authorities "are doing it to watch the reaction of the protest movement and of Western public opinion ... So far they consider both of these things acceptable and so they are continuing along this line".<ref name="nyt-30-mar"/> His supporters protested before the Investigative Committee offices.<ref name="BBC317"/>

Despite the mounting legal pressure, which Navalny described as 'political revenge for his investigations and work at the Anti-Corruption Foundation, as well as revenge for the campaign during the election period', he remained actively engaged in opposition activities.<ref>Гарькавая, Татьяна (25 April 2013). "[Судом Навального отвлекают от борьбы]" [Garkavaya Tatyana. Navalny Distracted from His Activism by the Courts]. Respublika (in Russian). Archived from the original on 25 April 2015. Retrieved 31 May 2025. https://web.archive.org/web/20150425162502/http://www.respublika-kz.info/news/politics/30092/</ref> He took part in an antigovernmental protest in Moscow, undeterred by the ongoing proceedings against him. During this time, he also met with Kazakh theatre director and opposition figure [[Bolat Atabaev]], who was visiting Moscow. The two discussed their respective political experiences and shared strategies for confronting corruption in authoritarian systems.<ref>Гарькавая, Татьяна (8 October 2012). "[Москва, Абай, Атабаев, Навальный]" [Garkavaya Tatyana. Moscow, Abai, Atabaev, Navalny]. Respublika (in Russian). Archived from the original on 26 April 2015. Retrieved 31 May 2025. https://web.archive.org/web/20150426111642/http://www.respublika-kz.info/news/society/25825/</ref>

In April 2013, Loeb & Loeb LLP{{Efn|[https://www.loeb.com/en Loeb & Loeb LLP], founded by [[Joseph P. Loeb]] ''et al.''. LLP stands for [[Limited liability partnership]].}} issued "An Analysis of the Russian Federation's prosecutions of Alexei Navalny", a paper detailing Investigative Committee accusations. The paper concludes that "the Kremlin has reverted to misuse of the Russian legal system to harass, isolate and attempt to silence political opponents".<ref>{{cite web|title=An Analysis of the Russian Federation's prosecutions of Alexei Navalny|url=https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B_VQeHLcziV_Vkk0dlBSRTQ2Yjg/view?sle=true|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422143244/https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B_VQeHLcziV_Vkk0dlBSRTQ2Yjg/view?sle=true|archive-date=22 April 2016|access-date=19 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2013|title=Sergei Guriev says climate of oppression deepening in Russia|newspaper=Financial Times|url=https://www.ft.com/content/3b10f6b6-ce90-11e2-8e16-00144feab7de|url-status=live|access-date=17 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517153221/https://www.ft.com/content/3b10f6b6-ce90-11e2-8e16-00144feab7de|archive-date=17 May 2018|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

==== Conviction and release ====
The Kirovles trial commenced in the city of [[Kirov, Kirov Oblast|Kirov]] on 17 April 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sandford|first=Daniel|date=17 April 2013|title=Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny goes on trial|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-22172224|url-status=live|access-date=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130617073213/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-22172224|archive-date=17 June 2013}}</ref> On 18 July, Navalny was sentenced to five years in jail for embezzlement.<ref name="Brumfield">{{cite news|last1=Brumfield|first1=Ben|last2=Black|first2=Phil|last3=Smith-Spark|first3=Laura|date=19 July 2013|title=Outspoken Putin critic Alexei Navalny hit with prison sentence|publisher=[[CNN]]|url=https://www.cnn.com/2013/07/18/world/europe/russia-navalny-case/|url-status=live|access-date=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016111550/http://edition.cnn.com/2013/07/18/world/europe/russia-navalny-case/index.html|archive-date=16 October 2013}}</ref> He was found guilty of misappropriating about 16&nbsp;million rubles<ref>{{cite news|last=Elder|first=Miriam|date=18 July 2013|title=Russia: Alexei Navalny found guilty of embezzlement|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/18/alexei-navalny-found-guilty-embezzlement|url-status=live|access-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828151757/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/18/alexei-navalny-found-guilty-embezzlement|archive-date=28 August 2013}}</ref> ($500,000) worth of lumber from a state-owned company.<ref>{{cite news|date=18 July 2013|title=Outspoken Putin critic Alexei Navalny hit with prison sentence|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2013/07/18/world/europe/russia-navalny-case/index.html|url-status=live|access-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016111550/http://edition.cnn.com/2013/07/18/world/europe/russia-navalny-case/index.html|archive-date=16 October 2013}}</ref> The sentence read by the judge Sergey Blinov was textually the same as the request of the prosecutor, with the only exception that Navalny was given five years, and the prosecution requested six years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Voronin |first=Nikolai |date=18 July 2013|script-title=ru:Как судили Навального: репортаж из зала суда|language=ru|publisher=BBC Russian Service|url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2013/07/130718_navalny_kirov_sentence.shtml|url-status=live|access-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720073547/http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2013/07/130718_navalny_kirov_sentence.shtml|archive-date=20 July 2013}}</ref>
[[File:Girls (9319552964).jpg|thumb|"Enough of fake cases". The protest against the verdict in Moscow, 18 July 2013]]

Later that evening, the Prosecutor's Office appealed Navalny and Ofitserov jail sentences, arguing that until the higher court affirmed the sentence, the sentence was invalid. The next morning, the appeal was granted. Navalny and Ofitserov were released on 19 July, awaiting the hearings of the higher court.<ref>{{cite news|date=19 July 2013|title=Alexei Navalny freed following anti-Putin protests in Moscow – video|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2013/jul/19/alexei-navalny-freed-putin-protests-moscow-video|url-status=live|access-date=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828150151/http://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2013/jul/19/alexei-navalny-freed-putin-protests-moscow-video|archive-date=28 August 2013}}</ref> The prosecutor's requested decision was described as "unprecedented" by experts.{{who|date=June 2015}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Alpert|first=Lukas I.|date=19 July 2013|title=Alexei Navalny Freed Pending Appeal|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323309404578615110654425662|url-status=live|access-date=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518225313/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323309404578615110654425662|archive-date=18 May 2015}}</ref>

==== Probation ====
The prison sentence was suspended by a court in Kirov on 16 October 2013, still being a burden for his political future.<ref name="SparedJail">{{cite news|author=Andrew E. Kramer|date=16 October 2013|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/17/world/europe/russian-opposition-leader-is-spared-jail.html|title=Navalny Is Spared Prison Term in Russia|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301180638/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/17/world/europe/russian-opposition-leader-is-spared-jail.html|archive-date=1 March 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

==== Review of the sentence ====
On 23 February 2016, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] ruled that Russia had violated Navalny's right to a fair trial, and ordered the government to pay him 56,000 euros in legal costs and damages.<ref>{{cite news|date=23 February 2016|title=European Court: Trial Against Putin Foe Navalny Was Unfair|publisher=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]]|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/european-court-trial-putin-foe-navalny-unfair-37129162|url-status=live|access-date=23 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224091255/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/european-court-trial-putin-foe-navalny-unfair-37129162|archive-date=24 February 2016}}</ref>

On 16 November 2016, Russia's [[Supreme Court of Russia|Supreme Court]] overturned the 2013 sentence, sending the verdict back to the Leninsky District Court in Kirov for review.<ref>{{cite news|date=16 November 2016|title=Верховный суд отменил приговор Навальному по делу "Кировлеса"|agency=ТАСС Информационное Агентство России|url=http://tass.ru/proisshestviya/3787991|url-status=live|access-date=16 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116164226/http://tass.ru/proisshestviya/3787991|archive-date=16 November 2016}}</ref>

On 8 February 2017, the Leninsky district court of Kirov repeated its sentence of 2013 and charged Navalny with a five-year suspended sentence.<ref name="VOA"/> Navalny announced that he would pursue the annulment of the sentence that clearly contradicts the decision of ECHR.<ref>{{cite web|date=22 November 2017|title=Навальный обжаловал в ЕСПЧ повторный приговор по делу "Кировлеса"|trans-title=Navalny appealed to the ECHR against the repeated sentence in the Kirovles case|url=https://meduza.io/news/2017/11/22/navalnyy-obzhaloval-v-espch-povtornyy-prigovor-po-delu-kirovlesa|access-date=21 October 2020|website=Meduza|archive-date=1 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034031/https://meduza.io/news/2017/11/22/navalnyy-obzhaloval-v-espch-povtornyy-prigovor-po-delu-kirovlesa|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Baranovskaya|first=Marina|date=22 November 2017|title=ЕСПЧ принял к рассмотрению жалобу Навального|trans-title=ECHR accepted Navalny's complaint for consideration|url=https://www.dw.com/ru/%D0%95%D0%A1%D0%9F%D0%A7-%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%BD%D1%8F%D0%BB-%D0%BA-%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BC%D0%BE%D1%82%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8E-%D0%B6%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B1%D1%83-%D0%9D%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE/a-41490191|access-date=21 October 2020|publisher=Deutsche Welle|language=ru|archive-date=17 February 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240217045054/https://www.dw.com/ru/%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%BF%D1%87-%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B8%D0%BD%D1%8F%D0%BB-%D0%BA-%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BC%D0%BE%D1%82%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%8E-%D0%B6%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%B1%D1%83-%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B0%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B3%D0%BE/a-41490191|url-status=live}}</ref>
<!--

== October 2012 arrest ==
Following the alleged kidnapping and torture of opposition activist [[Leonid Razvozzhayev]] from [[Kyiv]], Ukraine, Navalny was arrested along with Sergei Udaltsov and [[Ilya Yashin]] while attempting to join a Moscow protest on Razvozzhayev's behalf on 27 October 2012. The three were charged with violating public order, for which they could be fined up to 30,000 rubles ($900) or given 50 hours of community service.<ref>{{Cite news |author1=Maria Tsvetkova |author2=Gleb Bryanski |date=27 October 2012 |title=Russia activists detained after opposition council meets |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-opposition-idUSBRE89Q0AV20121027 |access-date=27 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027200800/http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/10/27/us-russia-opposition-idUSBRE89Q0AV20121027 |url-status=live |archive-date=27 October 2012}}</ref>-->

=== Yves Rocher case and house arrest ===
<!-- Since June 2012, Navalny had been subject to travel restrictions because of the Kirovles trial, and since December 2012, he was subject to another restriction, coming from the Yves Rocher trial. Unlike the former restriction, which allowed him to move across Moscow and the surrounding Moscow Oblast, the latter limited his movements to Moscow alone.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Навальный дал вторую подписку о невыезде |url=http://lenta.ru/news/2012/12/17/navalny/}}</ref> On 10 January 2014, however, he was found in Moscow Oblast, and the investigators announced the restrictions were broken.<ref>{{Cite web |title=СК: Навальный нарушил подписку о невыезде |url=http://www.vz.ru/news/2014/1/13/667664.html}}</ref> Navalny declared he had been given the right to visit the territory of the Oblast some time after the December 2012 restriction was signed, and published a corresponding document.<ref name="brokenrestrictionbbc">{{Cite news |title=Навальный заявляет, что не нарушал подписку о невыезде |url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2014/01/140113_navalny_travel_restrictions}}</ref> His press secretary Anna Veduta declared, "the Investigating Committee is arranging propaganda soil to put Alexey under a house arrest".<ref name="brokenrestrictionbbc" />
-->
{{See also|Yves Rocher (company)#Controversy}}

==== Case ====
In 2008, Oleg Navalny made an offer to Yves Rocher Vostok, the Eastern European subsidiary of [[Yves Rocher (company)|Yves Rocher]] between 2008 and 2012, to accredit Glavpodpiska, which was created by Navalny, with delivering duties. On 5 August, the parties signed a contract. To fulfill the obligations under the agreement, Glavpodpiska outsourced the task to sub-suppliers, AvtoSAGA and Multiprofile Processing Company (MPC). In November and December 2012, the Investigating Committee interrogated and questioned Yves Rocher Vostok. On 10 December, Bruno Leproux, general director of Yves Rocher Vostok, filed to the Investigative Committee, asking to investigate if the Glavpodpiska subscription company had damaged Yves Rocher Vostok, and the Investigative Committee initiated a case.<ref name="bbcyvesrocher">{{cite news|title=Суть "дела Ив Роше" и братьев Навальных|publisher=BBC Russian Service|url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2014/12/141229_navalny_yves_rocher_background|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102135735/http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2014/12/141229_navalny_yves_rocher_background|archive-date=2 January 2015}}</ref>

The prosecution claimed Glavpodpiska embezzled money by taking duties and then redistributing them to other companies for lesser amounts of money, and collecting the surplus: 26.7&nbsp;million rubles ($540,000) from Yves Rocher Vostok, and 4.4&nbsp;million rubles from the MPC. The funds were claimed to be subsequently legalised by transferring them on fictitious grounds from a fly-by-night company to Kobyakovskaya Fabrika Po Lozopleteniyu, a willow weaving company founded by Navalny and operated by his parents.<ref>{{cite web|date=29 December 2014|title=Details Of Yves Rocher Case :: Politics :: Society & Politics :: Russia-InfoCentre|url=http://www.russia-ic.com/society_politics/politics/2605/#.VKbt-CvF-_Q|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105061741/http://www.russia-ic.com/society_politics/politics/2605/#.VKbt-CvF-_Q|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Russia-ic.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=30 December 2014|title=Opposition activist Navalny gets suspended sentence in Yves Rocher case &#124; Russia Beyond the Headlines|url=http://rbth.co.uk/news/2014/12/30/russian_opposition_activist_navalny_gets_suspended_sentence_in_yves_roch_42658.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822185810/https://www.rbth.com/news/2014/12/30/russian_opposition_activist_navalny_gets_suspended_sentence_in_yves_roch_42658.html|archive-date=22 August 2020|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Rbth.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=15 November 2013|title=Navalny brothers Yves Rocher embezzlement case investigation completed |work=RAPSI|url=http://rapsinews.com/judicial_news/20131115/269672881.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208105133/http://rapsinews.com/judicial_news/20131115/269672881.html|archive-date=8 December 2015|access-date=27 December 2015}}</ref> The Navalnys denied the charges. The Navalny brothers' lawyers claimed the investigators "added phrases like 'bearing criminal intentions' to a description of regular entrepreneurial activity". According to Oleg Navalny's lawyer, Glavpodpiska did not just collect money, it controlled provision of means of transport, execution of orders, collected and expedited production to the carriers, and was responsible before clients for terms and quality of executing orders.<ref name="bbcyvesrocher"/>

None of the witnesses confirmed that there were any losses, except MPC CEO Sergei Shustov who said he had learned about his losses from an investigator and believed him without making audits. Both brothers and their lawyers claimed Alexei Navalny did not participate in the Glavpodpiska operations, and witnesses all stated they had never encountered Alexei Navalny in person before the trial.<ref name="bbcyvesrocher" />

==== House arrest and limitations ====
Following the imputed violation of travel restrictions, Navalny was placed under [[house arrest]] and prohibited from communicating with anyone other than his family, lawyers, and investigators on 28 February 2014.<ref name="vasilyeva2014">{{cite news|last=Vasilyeva|first=Nataliya|date=30 December 2014|title=Conviction of Putin foe sets off protest in Moscow|agency=Associated Press|url=https://news.yahoo.com/putin-foe-arrives-court-hear-verdict-061609972.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231033820/http://news.yahoo.com/putin-foe-arrives-court-hear-verdict-061609972.html|archive-date=31 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=28 February 2014|title=Court puts Russian opposition leader under house arrest|publisher=Moscow News.Net|url=http://www.moscownews.net/news/220274120/court-puts-russian-opposition-leader-under-house-arrest|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204205357/http://www.moscownews.net/news/220274120/court-puts-russian-opposition-leader-under-house-arrest|archive-date=4 February 2017}}</ref> Navalny claimed the arrest was politically motivated, and he filed a complaint to the European Court of Human Rights. On 7 July, he declared the complaint had been accepted and given priority; the court compelled the [[Government of Russia]] to provide answers to a questionnaire.<ref>{{Citation |last=Navalny |first=Alexei |title=ЕСПЧ принял жалобу на домашний арест и дал ей приоритет |work=navalny.[[livejournal]].com |trans-title=The ECHR accepted the complaint against house arrest and gave it priority |url=https://navalny.livejournal.com/943758.html |access-date=17 February 2024 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150517233357/http://navalny.livejournal.com/943758.html |archive-date=17 May 2015 |language=ru}}</ref>

The house arrest, in particular, prohibited usage of the internet; however, new posts were released under his social media accounts after the arrest was announced. A 5 March post claimed the accounts were controlled by his Anti-Corruption Foundation teammates and his wife [[Yulia Navalnaya|Yulia]]. On 13 March, his LiveJournal blog was blocked in Russia, because, according to the [[Federal Service for Supervision of Communications, Information Technology and Mass Media|Federal Service for Supervision of Communications, Information Technology, and Mass Media]] (Roskomnadzor), "functioning of the given web page breaks the regulation of the juridical decision of the bail hearing of a citizen against whom a criminal case has been initiated".<ref>{{Cite news |title=Роскомнадзор заблокировал блог Навального – Газета.Ru &#124; Новости |work=Gazeta.ru |url=http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2014/03/13/n_6010813.shtml |url-status=live |access-date=27 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235353/http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2014/03/13/n_6010813.shtml |archive-date=31 January 2016}}</ref> <!--Navalny filed a complaint, but the court rejected it on 11 April.<ref>[http://www.cityboom.ru/news/2014/04/11/navalny City Boom] 11 April 2014</ref>-->

The house arrest was eased a number of times: On 21 August, Navalny was allowed to communicate with his co-defendants;<ref>{{Cite web |title="Триумф российского правосудия": суд смягчил условия ареста Алексея Навального |date=21 August 2014 |url=http://www.mk.ru/politics/2014/08/21/triumf-rossiyskogo-pravosudiya-sud-smyagchil-usloviya-aresta-alekseya-navalnogo.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326000444/http://www.mk.ru/politics/2014/08/21/triumf-rossiyskogo-pravosudiya-sud-smyagchil-usloviya-aresta-alekseya-navalnogo.html |archive-date=26 March 2015 |access-date=10 May 2015}}</ref> a journalist present in the courthouse at the moment confirmed Navalny was allowed to communicate with "anyone but the Yves Rocher case witnesses".<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 August 2014 |title=Суд спустя полгода снял с Навального "обет молчания", разрешив отвечать на накопившиеся к нему претензии |url=http://newsru.com/russia/21aug2014/navalobet.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518083311/http://newsru.com/russia/21aug2014/navalobet.html |archive-date=18 May 2015 |access-date=10 May 2015 |publisher=newsru.com}}</ref> On 10 October, his right to communicate with the press was confirmed by another court, and he was allowed to make comments on the case in media (Navalny's plea not to prolong the arrest was, however, rejected).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Суд разрешил Алексею Навальному комментировать дело "Ив Роше" |url=http://www.bfm.ru/news/275454 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/http://www.bfm.ru/news/275454 |archive-date=31 January 2016 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Bfm.ru}}</ref> On 19 December, he was allowed to mail correspondence to authorities and international courts. Navalny again pleaded not to prolong the arrest, but the plea was rejected again.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Суд смягчил условия домашнего ареста Навального :: Общество :: РБК |url=http://top.rbc.ru/society/19/12/2014/5493f2879a794787f8a18ffa |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822185752/https://www.rbc.ru/society/19/12/2014/5493f2879a794787f8a18ffa |archive-date=22 August 2020 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Top.rbc.ru|date=19 December 2014 }}</ref>

==== Conviction ====
The verdict was announced on 30 December 2014. Both brothers were found guilty of fraud against Multiprofile Processing Company (MPC) and [[Yves Rocher (company)|Yves Rocher Vostok]] and money laundering, and were convicted under Articles 159.4 §§ 2 and 3 and 174.1 § 2 (a) and (b) of the Criminal Code.<ref>[https://hudoc.echr.coe.int/eng?i=001-161861 Third Section] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230826163053/https://hudoc.echr.coe.int/eng?i=001-161861 |date=26 August 2023 }} European Court of Human Rights. 8 March 2016</ref> Alexei Navalny was given 3{{frac|1|2}} years of suspended sentence, and Oleg Navalny was sentenced to 3{{frac|1|2}} years in prison and was arrested after the verdict was announced;<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith-Spark|first1=Laura|last2=Chance|first2=Matthew|last3=Eshchenko|first3=Alla|date=30 December 2014|title=Kremlin critic Alexei Navalny gets 3.5-year suspended sentence|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2014/12/30/world/europe/russia-alexei-navalny-case/index.html?hpt=hp_t3|url-status=live|access-date=30 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230102634/http://edition.cnn.com/2014/12/30/world/europe/russia-alexei-navalny-case/index.html?hpt=hp_t3|archive-date=30 December 2014}}</ref> both had to pay a fine of 500,000 rubles and a compensation to the MPC of over 4&nbsp;million rubles.<ref name="verdict">{{cite news|last=Mogilevskaya|first=Anna|date=17 February 2015|script-title=ru:Приговор Алексею и Олегу Навальным вступил в силу|trans-title=The verdict to Alexey and Oleg Navalny entered into force|newspaper=Kommersant|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2669921|url-status=live|access-date=10 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512033551/http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2669921|archive-date=12 May 2015}}</ref> In the evening, several thousand protesters gathered in the center of Moscow. Navalny broke his house arrest to attend the rally and was immediately apprehended by the police and brought back home.<ref name="alexander" />

Both brothers filed complaints to the [[European Court of Human Rights]]: Oleg's was communicated and given priority; Alexei's was reviewed in the context of the previous complaint related to this case and the Government of Russia had been "invited to submit further observations"<!-- by 13 February 2015-->.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Алексей Навальный – Некоторые юридические новости |url=https://navalny.com/p/4057/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105062026/https://navalny.com/p/4057/ |archive-date=5 January 2016 |access-date=27 December 2015 |publisher=Navalny.com}}</ref> The second instance within the country confirmed the verdict, only releasing Alexei from the responsibility to pay his fine. Both prosecutors and defendants were not satisfied with this decision.<ref name="verdict" />

==== ECHR ====
On 17 October 2017, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] ruled that Navalny's conviction for fraud and money laundering "was based on an unforeseeable application of criminal law and that the proceedings were arbitrary and unfair". The Court found that the domestic court's decisions had been arbitrary and manifestly unreasonable. ECHR found the Russian courts' decisions violated articles 6 and 7 of the [[European Convention on Human Rights]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 October 2017 |title=Human rights court: Kremlin critic's conviction 'arbitrary and unfair' |work=Politico |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/human-rights-court-kremlin-critics-conviction-arbitrary-and-unfair/ |url-status=live |access-date=17 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017180800/http://www.politico.eu/article/human-rights-court-kremlin-critics-conviction-arbitrary-and-unfair/ |archive-date=17 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=HUDOC – European Court of Human Rights |url=https://hudoc.echr.coe.int/eng#%7B%22documentcollectionid2%22:%5B%22GRANDCHAMBER%22,%22CHAMBER%22%5D,%22itemid%22:%5B%22001-177665%22%5D%7D |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107024019/http://hudoc.echr.coe.int/eng#%7B%22documentcollectionid2%22:%5B%22GRANDCHAMBER%22,%22CHAMBER%22%5D,%22itemid%22:%5B%22001-177665%22%5D%7D |archive-date=7 November 2015 |access-date=17 October 2017 |website=hudoc.echr.coe.int}}</ref> On 15 November 2018, the Grand Chamber upheld the decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.questionegiustizia.it/articolo/la-tutela-del-dibattito-politico-al-di-la-delle-immunita_20-02-2019.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220063129/http://questionegiustizia.it/articolo/la-tutela-del-dibattito-politico-al-di-la-delle-immunita_20-02-2019.php|title=La tutela del dibattito politico al di là delle immunità|archive-date=20 February 2019|website=www.questionegiustizia.it}}</ref>

=== Indemnification ===
After the Yves Rocher case, Navalny had to pay a compensation of 4.4&nbsp;million rubles. He declared the case was "a frame up", but he added he would pay the sum as this could affect granting his brother's parole.<ref>{{cite web|title=Суд предоставил Навальному отсрочку для оплаты долга по "делу "Ив Роше"|url=http://www.rosbalt.ru/moscow/2015/10/14/1451017.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016011443/http://www.rosbalt.ru/moscow/2015/10/14/1451017.html|archive-date=16 October 2015|access-date=26 October 2015|website=Rosbalt}}</ref> On 7 October 2015, Alexei's lawyer announced the defendant willingly paid 2.9&nbsp;million and requested an installment plan for the rest of the sum.<ref>{{cite news|date=10 July 2015|title=Алексей Навальный в рамках дела "Ив Роше" выплатил 3 млн рублей|newspaper=Kommersant|url=http://kommersant.ru/doc/2826609|url-status=live|access-date=15 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015073158/http://www.kommersant.ru/Doc/2826609|archive-date=15 October 2015}}</ref> The request was granted, except the term was contracted from the requested five months to two,<ref>{{cite news|last=Shur|first=Artem|date=14 October 2015|title=Алексей Навальный получил два месяца отсрочки выплаты по делу "Ив Роше"|trans-title=Alexey Navalny received a two-month grace period in the Yves Rocher case|newspaper=Kommersant|url=http://kommersant.ru/doc/2832268|url-status=live|access-date=15 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015121158/http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2832268|archive-date=15 October 2015}}</ref> and a part of the sum declared paid (900,000 rubles; arrested from Navalny's banking account) was not yet received by the police; the prosecutors declared that may happen because of inter-process delays.<ref>{{cite news|title=Алексей Навальный получил два месяца отсрочки выплаты по делу "Ив Роше"|newspaper=Kommersant|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/Doc/2832268|url-status=live|access-date=26 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822185748/https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/2832268|archive-date=22 August 2020}}</ref>

Later that month, Kirovles sued Navalny for the 16.1&nbsp;million rubles declared pecuniary injury; Navalny declared he had not expected the suit, as Kirovles did not initiate it during the 2012–2013 trial. On 23 October, a court resolved the said sum should be paid by the three defendants.<ref name="pay"/> The court denied the defendants' motion 14.7&nbsp;million had already been paid by that point; the verdict and the payment sum were justified by a ruling by a Plenum of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Навальному грозит банкротство после решения суда о выплате "Кировлесу" 16 миллионов|url=http://www.mk.ru/politics/2015/10/23/navalnomu-grozit-bankrotstvo-posle-resheniya-suda-o-vyplate-kirovlesu-16-millionov.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025205424/http://www.mk.ru/politics/2015/10/23/navalnomu-grozit-bankrotstvo-posle-resheniya-suda-o-vyplate-kirovlesu-16-millionov.html|archive-date=25 October 2015|access-date=26 October 2015|website=mk.ru|date=23 October 2015 }}</ref> Navalny declared he could not cover the requested sum; he called the suit a "drain-dry strategy" by authorities.<ref name="pay">{{cite news|title=Алексей Навальный должен оплатить ущерб по делу "Кировлеса"|url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2015/10/23/614132-navalnii-dolzhen |url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151026035813/http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2015/10/23/614132-navalnii-dolzhen|archive-date=26 October 2015|access-date=26 October 2015|work=Vedomosti}}</ref>

=== Other cases ===

In late December 2012, the [[Investigative Committee of Russia]] asserted that Allekt, an advertising company headed by Navalny, defrauded the [[Union of Right Forces]] (SPS) political party in 2007 by taking 100&nbsp;million rubles ($3.2&nbsp;million) payment for advertising and failing to honor its contract. If charged and convicted, Navalny could be jailed for up to 10 years. Leonid Gozman, a former SPS official, was quoted as saying: "Nothing of the sort happened—he committed no robbery". Earlier in December, as reported by the [[BBC]], "the Investigative Committee charged [...] Navalny and his brother Oleg with embezzling 55 million rubles ($1.76&nbsp;million) in 2008–2011 while working in a postal business". Navalny, who denied the allegations in the two previous cases, sought to laugh off news of the third inquiry with a tweet stating "Fiddlesticks".<ref name="BBC01">{{cite news|date=24 December 2012|title=Russian opposition leader Navalny faces third inquiry|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-20836116|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121225183605/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-20836116|archive-date=25 December 2012}}</ref> In April 2020, [[Yandex Search|Yandex]] search engine started artificially placing negative commentary about Navalny on the top positions in its search results for his name.<ref>{{cite web|date=28 April 2020|title=Yandex says its experimental search results trashing Alexey Navalny were 'a mistake'|website=Meduza|url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2020/04/28/yandex-says-its-experimental-search-results-trashing-alexey-navalny-were-a-mistake|url-status=live|access-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200429150839/https://meduza.io/en/news/2020/04/28/yandex-says-its-experimental-search-results-trashing-alexey-navalny-were-a-mistake|archive-date=29 April 2020}}</ref> Yandex declared this was part of an "experiment" and returned to presenting organic search results.<ref>{{cite web|date=28 April 2020|title="Яндекс" выделял в результатах поиска негативные материалы о Навальном. Компания назвала это экспериментом|url=https://tvrain.ru/news/jandeks-507766/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200428122823/https://tvrain.ru/news/jandeks-507766/|archive-date=28 April 2020|access-date=27 April 2020|website=tvrain.ru|publisher=TV Rain}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=27 April 2020|title="Яндекс" выделял в выдаче негативные материалы по запросу "Навальный". Компания назвала это экспериментом|language=ru|website=Meduza|url=https://meduza.io/news/2020/04/28/yandeks-vydelyal-v-vydache-negativnye-materialy-po-zaprosu-navalnyy-kompaniya-nazvala-eto-eksperimentom|url-status=live|access-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200602051032/https://meduza.io/news/2020/04/28/yandeks-vydelyal-v-vydache-negativnye-materialy-po-zaprosu-navalnyy-kompaniya-nazvala-eto-eksperimentom|archive-date=2 June 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Вкладка с обсуждаемым контентом: разбор полётов – Блог Яндекса|url=https://yandex.ru/blog/company/vkladka-s-obsuzhdaemym-kontentom-razbor-poletov|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200504044905/https://yandex.ru/blog/company/vkladka-s-obsuzhdaemym-kontentom-razbor-poletov|archive-date=4 May 2020|access-date=29 April 2020|website=yandex.ru}}</ref>

Navalny alleged that Russian billionaire and businessman [[Yevgeny Prigozhin]] was linked to a company called Moskovsky Shkolnik (Moscow schoolboy) that had supplied poor quality food to schools which had caused a [[dysentery]] outbreak.<ref name="Navalny-Prigozhin"/><ref>{{cite news|date=14 May 2019|title=Parents sue tycoon's firm over dysentery outbreak in Moscow|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|url=https://financialpost.com/pmn/business-pmn/parents-sue-tycoons-firm-over-dysentery-outbreak-in-moscow|access-date=4 September 2020|archive-date=29 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129222018/https://financialpost.com/pmn/business-pmn/parents-sue-tycoons-firm-over-dysentery-outbreak-in-moscow|url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2019, Moskovsky Shkolnik filed a lawsuit against Navalny. In October 2019, the Moscow Arbitration Court ordered Navalny to pay 29.2&nbsp;million rubles. Navalny said that "Cases of dysentery were proven using documents. But it's us that has to pay."<ref>{{cite news|date=28 October 2019|title=Kremlin Critic Navalny and Allies Hit With $1.4M Lawsuit Payout|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/10/28/kremlin-critic-navalny-and-allies-hit-with-14m-lawsuit-payout-a67942|access-date=4 September 2020|archive-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200820111938/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/10/28/kremlin-critic-navalny-and-allies-hit-with-14m-lawsuit-payout-a67942|url-status=live}}</ref> By April 2019, Navalny had won six complaints against Russian authorities in the ECHR for a total of €225,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Safronov|first=Evgeniy|date=9 April 2019|title=Навальный получил от ЕСПЧ больше 200 тыс. евро за пять лет|trans-title=Navalny received from the ECHR more than 200 thousand euros in five years|url=https://openmedia.io/news/navalnyj-poluchil-ot-espch-bolshe-200-tys-evro-za-pyat-let/|access-date=20 October 2020|website=Open Media.io|language=ru|archive-date=23 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191023200433/https://openmedia.io/news/navalnyj-poluchil-ot-espch-bolshe-200-tys-evro-za-pyat-let/|url-status=live}}</ref> Prigozhin was quoted by the press service of his catering company [[Concord Management and Consulting]] on 25 August 2020 as saying that he intended to enforce a court decision that required Navalny, his associate [[Lyubov Sobol]] and his Anti-Corruption Foundation to pay 88 million rubles in damages to the Moskovsky Shkolnik company over a video investigation.<ref>{{cite news|date=26 August 2020|title='Putin's chef' promises to ruin comatose Navalny with $1.2m bill|publisher=Al Jazeera|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/08/chef-promises-ruin-comatose-navalny-12m-bill-200826084533241.html|access-date=4 September 2020|archive-date=2 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200902181118/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/08/chef-promises-ruin-comatose-navalny-12m-bill-200826084533241.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Poisoning and recovery==
{{main|Poisoning of Alexei Navalny}}

On 20 August 2020, Navalny fell ill during a flight from [[Tomsk]] to Moscow and was hospitalised in the Emergency City Clinical Hospital No. 1 in [[Omsk]] ({{lang|ru|Городская клиническая больница скорой медицинской помощи №1}}), where the plane had made an [[emergency landing]]. The change in his condition on the plane was sudden and violent, and video footage showed crewmembers on the flight scurrying towards him as he screamed loudly.<ref name="harding-2020">{{cite news|last1=Harding|first1=Luke|last2=Roth|first2=Andrew|date=20 August 2020|title=A cup of tea, then screams of agony: how Alexei Navalny was left fighting for his life|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/aug/20/a-cup-of-tea-then-screams-of-agony-how-alexei-navalny-was-left-fighting-for-his-life|url-status=live|access-date=20 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200820173012/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/aug/20/a-cup-of-tea-then-screams-of-agony-how-alexei-navalny-was-left-fighting-for-his-life|archive-date=20 August 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Later, he said that he was not screaming from pain, but from the knowledge that he was dying.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Bidder|first1=Benjamin|last2=Esch|first2=Christian|date=1 October 2020|title=Russian Opposition Leader Alexei Navalny on His Poisoning|magazine=[[Der Spiegel]]|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/world/alexei-navalny-on-his-poisoning-i-assert-that-putin-was-behind-the-crime-a-ae5923d5-20f3-4117-80bd-39a99b5b86f4|url-status=live|access-date=22 November 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201120165902/https://www.spiegel.de/international/world/alexei-navalny-on-his-poisoning-i-assert-that-putin-was-behind-the-crime-a-ae5923d5-20f3-4117-80bd-39a99b5b86f4|archive-date=20 November 2020}}</ref>

Navalny's spokeswoman, [[Kira Yarmysh]], later said that he was in a coma and on a ventilator in the Omsk hospital. She also said that since he arose that morning, Navalny had consumed nothing but a cup of tea, acquired at the airport. It was initially suspected that something was mixed into his drink, and physicians stated that a "toxin mixed into a hot drink would be rapidly absorbed". The hospital said that he was in a stable but serious condition. Although staff initially acknowledged that Navalny had probably been poisoned, after numerous police personnel appeared outside Navalny's room, the medical staff was less forthcoming. The Omsk hospital's deputy chief physician later told reporters that poisoning was "one scenario among many" being considered.<ref name="harding-2020"/>

A plane was sent from Germany to evacuate Navalny from Russia for treatment at the [[Charité]] Hospital in Berlin. Although the doctors treating him in Omsk initially declared he was too sick to be transported,<ref>{{cite news|date=21 August 2020|title=Alexei Navalny doctors refuse to let Putin critic leave Russia – aide|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/aug/21/alexei-navalny-plane-leaves-germany-to-transport-putin-critic-after-suspected-poisoning|url-status=live|access-date=21 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200821060411/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/aug/21/alexei-navalny-plane-leaves-germany-to-transport-putin-critic-after-suspected-poisoning|archive-date=21 August 2020}}</ref> they later released him.<ref>{{cite news|date=21 August 2020|title=Alexei Navalny: Russian doctors agree to let Putin critic go to Germany|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53865811|url-status=live|access-date=21 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200821182838/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53865811|archive-date=21 August 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=22 August 2020|title=Alexei Navalny arrives in Germany for treatment|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53871617|url-status=live|access-date=22 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822030125/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-53871617|archive-date=22 August 2020}}</ref> On 24 August, the doctors in Germany made an announcement, confirming that Navalny had been poisoned with a [[cholinesterase inhibitor]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Osborne|first=Samuel|date=24 August 2020|title=Alexei Navalny: Russian opposition leader was poisoned, German hospital suggests|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/alexei-navalny-poisoned-russia-putin-berlin-hospital-test-kremlin-a9685821.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200824150451/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/alexei-navalny-poisoned-russia-putin-berlin-hospital-test-kremlin-a9685821.html |archive-date=24 August 2020 |url-access=limited |url-status=live|access-date=24 August 2020}}</ref>

Ivan Zhdanov, chief of Navalny's [[Anti-Corruption Foundation]], said that Navalny could have been poisoned because of one of the foundation's investigations.<ref name="Navalny-Prigozhin">{{cite news|date=26 August 2020|title=Kremlin-Linked Businessman Prigozhin Vows to Ruin Navalny|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/08/26/kremlin-linked-businessman-prigozhin-vows-to-ruin-navalny-a71246|access-date=4 September 2020|archive-date=5 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200905025211/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2020/08/26/kremlin-linked-businessman-prigozhin-vows-to-ruin-navalny-a71246|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 September, the German government announced that Navalny was poisoned with a [[Novichok agent|Novichok]] nerve agent, from the same family of nerve agents that was used to poison [[Sergei Skripal]] and his daughter. International officials said that they had obtained "unequivocal proof" from toxicology tests, and have called on the Russian government for an explanation.<ref name="poisoning">{{cite news|last=Rainsford|first=Sarah|date=2 September 2020|title=Russia's Navalny poisoned with Novichok – German government|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54002880|access-date=2 September 2020|archive-date=20 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120203525/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54002880|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Halasz|first1=Stephania|last2=Jones|first2=Bryony|last3=Mezzofiore|first3=Gianluca|date=2 September 2020|title=Novichok nerve agent used in Alexey Navalny poisoning, says German government|publisher=CNN|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/09/02/europe/alexey-navalny-novichok-intl/index.html|access-date=2 September 2020|archive-date=2 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200902170748/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/09/02/europe/alexey-navalny-novichok-intl/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Schwirtz|first1=Michael|last2=Eddy|first2=Melissa|date=2 September 2020|title=Aleksei Navalny Was Poisoned With Novichok, Germany Says|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/09/02/world/europe/navalny-poison-novichok.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200902141131/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/09/02/world/europe/navalny-poison-novichok.html|archive-date=2 September 2020|url-status=live|access-date=2 September 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 7 September, German doctors announced that he was out of the coma.<ref>{{cite news|date=7 September 2020|title=Russia's Navalny out of coma after poisoning|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54061370|access-date=7 September 2020|archive-date=7 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200907192655/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54061370|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 September, Navalny's spokeswoman said that Navalny would return to Russia.<ref>{{cite news|date=15 September 2020|title=Alexei Navalny: Poisoned Putin critic 'will return to Russia'|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54163389|access-date=15 March 2022|archive-date=15 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220315063717/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54163389|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 17 September, Navalny's team said that traces of the nerve agent used to poison Navalny was detected on an empty water bottle from his hotel room in Tomsk, suggesting that he was possibly poisoned before leaving the hotel.<ref>{{cite news|date=17 September 2020|title=Navalny team says nerve agent found on Russian hotel room water bottle|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny/navalny-team-says-nerve-agent-was-found-on-hotel-room-water-bottle-idUSKBN2680X0|access-date=17 September 2020|archive-date=18 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200918004319/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny/navalny-team-says-nerve-agent-was-found-on-hotel-room-water-bottle-idUSKBN2680X0|url-status=live}}</ref> On 23 September, Navalny was discharged from hospital after his condition had sufficiently improved.<ref>{{cite news|date=23 September 2020|title=Alexei Navalny: Russian activist discharged from Berlin hospital|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54262279|access-date=23 September 2020|archive-date=31 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201231021045/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54262279|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 October, [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons|OPCW]] confirmed presence of cholinesterase inhibitor from the Novichok group in Navalny's blood and urine samples.<ref>{{cite news|title=OPCW: Novichok found on Alexei Navalny samples|url=https://www.dw.com/en/opcw-novichok-found-on-alexei-navalny-samples/a-55176999|access-date=6 October 2020|publisher=Deutsche Welle|archive-date=14 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214061834/https://www.dw.com/en/opcw-novichok-found-on-alexei-navalny-samples/a-55176999|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Schwirtz|first=Michael|date=14 October 2020|title=Nerve Agent Was Used to Poison Navalny, Chemical Weapons Body Confirms|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/10/06/world/europe/navalny-opcw-russia-novichok.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201006160603/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/10/06/world/europe/navalny-opcw-russia-novichok.html|archive-date=6 October 2020|url-status=live|access-date=20 October 2020|issn=0362-4331|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Deutsch|first=Anthony|date=6 October 2020|title=Chemical weapons body confirms nerve agent Novichok in Navalny's blood|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny-chemicalweapo-idUSKBN26R2GQ|access-date=20 October 2020|archive-date=19 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201019004118/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny-chemicalweapo-idUSKBN26R2GQ|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 14 December, a joint investigation by ''[[The Insider (website)|The Insider]]'' and [[Bellingcat]] in co-operation with [[CNN]] and ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' was published, which implicated agents from Russia's [[Federal Security Service]] (FSB) in Navalny's poisoning.<ref>{{cite web|date=14 December 2020|title=Alexei Navalny: Report names 'Russian agents' in poisoning case|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55303703|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214211536/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55303703|archive-date=14 December 2020|access-date=15 December 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Troianovski|first=Anton|author-link=Anton Troianovski|date=21 December 2020|title=Navalny Says Russian Agent Confessed to Plot to Poison Him|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/21/world/europe/russia-navalny-poisoning-putin.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201221210341/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/12/21/world/europe/russia-navalny-poisoning-putin.html|archive-date=21 December 2020|url-status=live|access-date=25 January 2021|quote=The call Mr. Navalny released Monday added to the trove of evidence suggesting that the agency had organised – and botched – an assassination attempt against [him]|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Rainsford|first=Sarah|date=1 October 2020|title=Alexei Navalny blames Vladimir Putin for poisoning him|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54369664|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201003164809/https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/world-europe-54369664|archive-date=3 October 2020|access-date=2 October 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> The investigation detailed a special unit of the FSB, which specialises in chemical substances, and the investigators then tracked members of the unit, using telecom and travel data. According to the investigation, Navalny was under surveillance by a group of operatives from the unit for 3 years and there may have been earlier attempts to poison Navalny.<ref>{{cite web|date=14 December 2020|title=Alexei Navalny: Report names 'Russian agents' in poisoning case|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55303703|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2022|archive-date=14 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214211536/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55303703|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lister|first1=Tim|last2=Ward|first2=Clarissa|last3=Shukla|first3=Sebastian|date=14 December 2020|title=CNN-Bellingcat investigation identifies Russian specialists who trailed Putin's nemesis Alexey Navalny before he was poisoned|publisher=[[CNN International]]|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/12/14/europe/russia-navalny-agents-bellingcat-ward/index.html|access-date=14 December 2020|archive-date=14 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214200625/https://www.cnn.com/2020/12/14/europe/russia-navalny-agents-bellingcat-ward/index.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=14 December 2020|title=FSB Team of Chemical Weapon Experts Implicated in Alexey Navalny Novichok Poisoning|work=[[Bellingcat]]|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2020/12/14/fsb-team-of-chemical-weapon-experts-implicated-in-alexey-navalny-novichok-poisoning/|access-date=14 December 2020|archive-date=14 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201214180522/https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2020/12/14/fsb-team-of-chemical-weapon-experts-implicated-in-alexey-navalny-novichok-poisoning/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Дело раскрыто. Я знаю всех, кто пытался меня убить|trans-title=The case is open. I know everyone who tried to kill me|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=smhi6jts97I|archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/smhi6jts97I|archive-date=21 December 2021|url-status=live|access-date=18 December 2020|website=www.youtube.com|date=14 December 2020 }}{{cbignore}}</ref> In an interview with Spanish newspaper ''[[El País]]'', Navalny said that "It is difficult for me to understand exactly what is going on in [Putin's] mind. ... 20 years of power would spoil anyone and make them crazy. He thinks he can do whatever he wants."<ref>{{cite news|date=14 December 2020|title=Alexey Navalny: 'I have no doubt that Putin gave the order to poison me'|newspaper=[[El País]]|url=https://english.elpais.com/international/2020-12-14/alexei-navalny-i-have-no-doubt-that-putin-gave-the-order-to-poison-me.html|access-date=18 December 2020|archive-date=16 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201216045153/https://english.elpais.com/international/2020-12-14/alexei-navalny-i-have-no-doubt-that-putin-gave-the-order-to-poison-me.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 21 December 2020, Navalny released a video showing him impersonating a Russian security official and speaking over the phone with a man identified by some investigative news media as a chemical weapons expert named Konstantin Kudryavtsev. During the call, he revealed that the poison had been placed on Navalny's clothing, particularly in his underwear, and that Navalny would have died if not for the plane's emergency landing and quick response from an ambulance crew on the runway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/article/alexei-navalny-poisoning-underpants-202f470c2d1c19151b9deb564d94e8f9|title=Navalny releases recording of call to his alleged poisoner|date=20 April 2021|website=AP NEWS|first=Daria|last=Litvinova|access-date=26 January 2021|archive-date=23 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201223025405/http://apnews.com/article/alexei-navalny-poisoning-underpants-202f470c2d1c19151b9deb564d94e8f9|url-status=live}}</ref>

In January 2021, ''Bellingcat'', ''The Insider'' and ''Der Spiegel'' linked the unit that tracked Navalny to other deaths, including activists [[Timur Kuashev]] in 2014 and [[Ruslan Magomedragimov]] in 2015, and politician [[Nikita Isaev|Nikita Isayev]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|date=27 January 2021|title=Navalny's Alleged FSB Poisoners Linked to Deaths of Journalists, Activists – Investigation|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/27/navalnys-alleged-fsb-poisoners-linked-to-deaths-of-journalists-activists-investigation-a72757|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=12 February 2021|archive-date=6 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210206182611/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/27/navalnys-alleged-fsb-poisoners-linked-to-deaths-of-journalists-activists-investigation-a72757|url-status=live}}</ref> In February, another joint investigation found that Russian opposition politician [[Vladimir Vladimirovich Kara-Murza|Vladimir Kara-Murza]] was followed by the same unit before his suspected poisonings.<ref>{{cite news|date=11 February 2021|title=Navalny, Kara-Murza Tailed by Same FSB Squad Before Alleged Poisonings – Investigation|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/11/navalny-kara-murza-tailed-by-same-fsb-squad-before-alleged-poisonings-investigation-a72911|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=12 February 2021|archive-date=12 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210212043033/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/11/navalny-kara-murza-tailed-by-same-fsb-squad-before-alleged-poisonings-investigation-a72911|url-status=live}}</ref>

The European Union, United Kingdom and United States responded to the poisoning by imposing sanctions on senior Russian officials.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chappell|first=Bill|date=15 October 2020|title=EU Sanctions Russian Officials Over Navalny Poisoning, Citing Chemical Weapons Use|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/10/15/923982672/eu-sanctions-russian-officials-over-navalny-poisoning-citing-chemical-weapons-us|access-date=20 October 2020|website=NPR.org|archive-date=20 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201020054826/https://www.npr.org/2020/10/15/923982672/eu-sanctions-russian-officials-over-navalny-poisoning-citing-chemical-weapons-us|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=15 October 2020|title=Navalny Novichok poisoning: EU sanctions hit top Russians|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54552480|access-date=20 October 2020|archive-date=20 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201020110438/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-54552480|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Emmott|first1=Robin|last2=Young|first2=Sarah|last3=Falconbridge|first3=Guy|last4=Marrow|first4=Alexander|last5=Antonov|first5=Dmitry |editor=Andrew Cawthorne |editor2=Giles Elgood |editor3=William Maclean |date=15 October 2020|title=EU, Britain sanction Russian officials over Navalny poisoning|publisher=[[Reuters]]|publication-place=Brussels|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny-eu-idUSKBN2701DT|access-date=25 January 2021|archive-date=15 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230815145232/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny-eu-idUSKBN2701DT|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="tmt-2-mar">{{cite web|date=2 March 2021|title=U.S., EU Sanction Russia Over Navalny Poisoning|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/03/02/us-eu-sanction-russia-over-navalny-poisoning-a73119|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=2 March 2021|archive-date=2 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210302233528/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/03/02/us-eu-sanction-russia-over-navalny-poisoning-a73119|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Imprisonment==
{{See also|2021 Russian protests}}

===Yves Rocher case===
<mapframe width=300 height=200 zoom=3 latitude=54.3 longitude=25.3 text="Approximate aircraft route of flight DP936 taken by Alexei Navalny, on 17 January 2021, showing its deviation">
{
  "type": "ExternalData",
  "service": "page",
  "title": "Flight DP936 2021-01-17.map"
}
</mapframe>

On 17 January 2021, Navalny [[Poisoning of Alexei Navalny#Return and imprisonment|flew from Germany to Russia]] on [[Pobeda (airline)|Pobeda]] airlines flight DP936. The flight was scheduled to land at Moscow's [[Vnukovo Airport]], but was diverted mid-flight to [[Sheremetyevo International Airport]]. At passport control, he was detained. The [[Federal Penitentiary Service]] (FSIN) confirmed his detention and said that he would remain in custody until the court hearing.<ref>{{cite news|date=17 January 2021|title=Navalny Returns to Russia|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/17/navalny-returns-to-russia-a72635|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=17 January 2021|archive-date=18 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210118002330/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/17/navalny-returns-to-russia-a72635|url-status=live}}</ref> Prior to his return, the FSIN had said that Navalny might face jail time upon his arrival in Moscow for violating the terms of his probation by leaving Russia, saying it would be "obliged" to detain him once he returned;<ref name="tmt-14-jan">{{cite news|date=14 January 2021|title=Russia Warns 'Obliged' to Detain Kremlin Critic Navalny on Return|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/14/russia-says-obliged-to-detain-navalny-upon-return-a72611|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=19 January 2021|archive-date=17 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117224440/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/14/russia-says-obliged-to-detain-navalny-upon-return-a72611|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2014, Navalny received a suspended sentence in the ''[[#Yves Rocher case and house arrest|Yves Rocher case]]'', which he called politically motivated and in 2017, the [[European Court of Human Rights]] ruled that Navalny was unfairly convicted.<ref>{{cite news|date=17 October 2017|title=Human Rights Court Says Navalny Unfairly Convicted In 'Yves Rocher Case'|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/aleksei-oleg-navalny-yves-rocher-case-echr-unfairly-convicted/28799784.html|publisher=RFE/RL|access-date=19 January 2021|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119172627/https://www.rferl.org/a/aleksei-oleg-navalny-yves-rocher-case-echr-unfairly-convicted/28799784.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=18 January 2021|title=Alexey Navalny remanded in custody for 30 days pending trial|url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2021/01/18/alexey-navalny-remanded-in-custody-for-30-days-pending-trial|website=Meduza|access-date=19 January 2021|archive-date=18 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210118175448/https://meduza.io/en/news/2021/01/18/alexey-navalny-remanded-in-custody-for-30-days-pending-trial|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] declared Navalny to be a [[prisoner of conscience]] and called on the Russian authorities to release him.<ref>{{cite web|date=17 January 2021|title=Russia: Aleksei Navalny becomes prisoner of conscience after arrest on arrival in Moscow|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2021/01/russia-aleksei-navalny-becomes-prisoner-of-conscience-after-arrest-on-arrival-in-moscow/|website=[[Amnesty International]]|access-date=17 January 2021|archive-date=17 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117190312/https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2021/01/russia-aleksei-navalny-becomes-prisoner-of-conscience-after-arrest-on-arrival-in-moscow/|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2021, Amnesty briefly revoked the designation after it said it was being "bombarded" with complaints about xenophobic comments made by Navalny in the past;<ref name="BBC2021-Rainsford">{{cite web | last=Rainsford | first=Sarah | title=Amnesty strips Alexei Navalny of 'prisoner of conscience' status | website=BBC Home | date=2021-02-24 | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56181084 | access-date=2024-03-13 | archive-date=25 February 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240225093635/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56181084 | url-status=live }}</ref> however, they reversed this decision in May of the same year, with a statement that noted that designation of "an individual as Prisoner of Conscience [...] in no way involves or implies the endorsement of their views" and that the primary purpose of such a designation was to "highlight [...] the urgent need for his rights [...] to be recognised and acted upon by the Russian authorities".<ref name="amnesty_title"/>

A court decision on 18 January 2021 ordered the detention of Navalny until 15 February for violating his parole.<ref>{{cite web|date=17 January 2021|title=Russia Navalny: Poisoned opposition leader held after flying home|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55694598|access-date=17 January 2021|publisher=BBC News|language=en|archive-date=21 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210121202407/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55694598|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=14 January 2021|title=Alexei Navalny ordered to be detained on return to Russia, say officials|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jan/14/alexei-navalny-will-be-detained-on-return-to-russia-says-prison-service|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=23 March 2021|archive-date=18 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210418173930/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jan/14/alexei-navalny-will-be-detained-on-return-to-russia-says-prison-service|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="tmt-14-jan"/> A makeshift court was set up in the police station where Navalny was being held. Another hearing would later be held to determine whether his suspended sentence should be replaced with a jail term.<ref>{{cite web|date=18 January 2021|title=Alexei Navalny: Poisoned Putin critic Navalny jailed for 30 days|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55700312|publisher=BBC News|access-date=18 January 2021|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119011318/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55700312|url-status=live}}</ref> Navalny described the procedure as "ultimate lawlessness" and called on his supporters to take to the streets.<ref>{{cite news|date=18 January 2021|title=Navalny Urges Russians To 'Take to the Streets' Over Jailing|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/18/navalny-urges-russians-to-take-to-the-streets-over-jailing-a72646|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=19 January 2021|archive-date=18 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210118153907/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/01/18/navalny-urges-russians-to-take-to-the-streets-over-jailing-a72646|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, while in jail, [[A Palace for Putin. The Story of the Biggest Bribe|an investigation]] by Navalny and the FBK was published accusing President [[Vladimir Putin]] of corruption.<ref>{{cite web|date=19 January 2021|title=ФБК опубликовал огромное расследование о "дворце Путина" в Геленджике. Вот главное из двухчасового фильма о строительстве ценой в 100 миллиардов|trans-title=FBK has published a huge investigation about the "Putin's palace" in Gelendzhik. Here's the highlight of a two-hour movie about a $100&nbsp;billion construction|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2021/01/19/fbk-opublikoval-ogromnoe-rassledovanie-o-dvortse-putina-v-gelendzhike-vot-glavnoe-iz-dvuhchasovogo-filma-o-stroitelstve-tsenoy-v-100-milliardov|access-date=19 January 2021|website=Meduza|archive-date=19 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119162405/https://meduza.io/feature/2021/01/19/fbk-opublikoval-ogromnoe-rassledovanie-o-dvortse-putina-v-gelendzhike-vot-glavnoe-iz-dvuhchasovogo-filma-o-stroitelstve-tsenoy-v-100-milliardov|url-status=live}}</ref> The investigation and his arrest led to [[2021 Russian protests|mass protests across Russia]] beginning on 23 January 2021.<ref>{{cite news|date=23 January 2021|title=Detentions and warnings over Navalny protests|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55765895|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2022|archive-date=15 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220315065253/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55765895|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=28 January 2021|title=Russian Court Orders Navalny to Remain in Jail Ahead of Trial|language=en|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|first=Jake|last=Rudnitsky|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-01-28/russian-police-detain-navalny-allies-ahead-of-sunday-s-protest|access-date=29 January 2021|url-access=subscription|archive-date=29 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210129081056/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-01-28/russian-police-detain-navalny-allies-ahead-of-sunday-s-protest|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[File:Митинг 23 января 2021 года в Санкт-Петербурге.jpg|thumb|Protest in support of Navalny in St. Petersburg, 23 January 2021]]
A Moscow court on 2 February 2021 replaced Navalny's three-and-a-half-year suspended sentence with a prison sentence, minus the amount of time he spent under house arrest, meaning he would spend over {{frac|2|1|2}} years in a [[corrective labour colony]].<ref>{{cite web|date=2 February 2021|title=In Responding to Navalny's Prison Sentence, the West Has Limited Options|url=https://worldview.stratfor.com/article/responding-navalny-s-prison-sentence-west-has-limited-options|url-access=subscription|access-date=11 February 2021|website=[[Stratfor]]|archive-date=5 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210205180541/https://worldview.stratfor.com/article/responding-navalny-s-prison-sentence-west-has-limited-options|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Palasciano|first=Andrea|date=2 February 2021|title=As It's Happening: Navalny Sentenced to 2.5 Years in Penal Colony|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/02/as-its-happening-navalny-in-court-a72803|access-date=2 February 2021|newspaper=The Moscow Times|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202072555/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/02/as-its-happening-navalny-in-court-a72803|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="BBC 2021-02-02">{{cite news|date=2 February 2021|title=Putin critic Navalny jailed in Russia despite protests|language=en|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55910974|access-date=2 February 2021|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202174655/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-55910974|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=2 February 2021|title=Суд отправил Алексея Навального в колонию|url=https://meduza.io/news/2021/02/02/sud-otpravil-alekseya-navalnogo-v-koloniyu|website=Meduza|access-date=2 February 2021|archive-date=11 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210511045234/https://meduza.io/news/2021/02/02/sud-otpravil-alekseya-navalnogo-v-koloniyu|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alexei Navalny sentenced to prison term for violating probation as protesters detained|publisher=CBC|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/russia-navalny-court-1.5897347|access-date=2 February 2021|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202153948/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/russia-navalny-court-1.5897347|url-status=live}}</ref>{{excessive citations inline|date=February 2024}} The verdict was condemned by the governments of the United States, United Kingdom, Germany, France and others as well as the EU.<ref name="BBC 2021-02-02"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Russia: UK responds to Navalny sentencing|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/russia-uk-responds-to-navalny-sentencing|access-date=2 February 2021|publisher=[[Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office]]|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202174035/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/russia-uk-responds-to-navalny-sentencing|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Blinken|first=Antony|title=The United States is deeply concerned by Russia's actions toward Aleksey Navalny|url=https://twitter.com/SecBlinken/status/1356665053492219904|access-date=2 February 2021|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202180542/https://twitter.com/SecBlinken/status/1356665053492219904|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2 February 2021|title=Germany's Merkel condemns Navalny sentence, demands halt to violence|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny-merkel/germanys-merkel-condemns-navalny-sentence-demands-halt-to-violence-idUSKBN2A22SC|access-date=2 February 2021|publisher=Reuters|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202205624/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-politics-navalny-merkel/germanys-merkel-condemns-navalny-sentence-demands-halt-to-violence-idUSKBN2A22SC|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Macron|first=Emmanuel|title=La condamnation d'Alexeï @Navalny est inacceptable|url=https://twitter.com/EmmanuelMacron/status/1356676542257102853|access-date=2 February 2021|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202185125/https://twitter.com/EmmanuelMacron/status/1356676542257102853|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Borrell|first=Josep|title=The sentencing of Alexey @navalny runs counter Russia's international commitments on rule of law & fundamental freedoms|url=https://twitter.com/JosepBorrellF/status/1356680080332840962|access-date=2 February 2021|archive-date=2 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202190537/https://twitter.com/JosepBorrellF/status/1356680080332840962|url-status=live}}</ref>{{excessive citations inline|date=February 2024}} Immediately after the verdict was announced, protests in a number of Russian cities were held and met with a harsh police crackdown.<ref>{{cite web|date=2 February 2021|title=Вечер после приговора Алексею Навальному. Полиция задерживает людей на Манежной площади|url=https://meduza.io/live/2021/02/02/vecher-posle-prigovora-alekseyu-navalnomu-politsiya-zaderzhivaet-lyudey-na-manezhnoy-ploschadi|website=Meduza|access-date=15 February 2021|archive-date=11 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210511045312/https://meduza.io/live/2021/02/02/vecher-posle-prigovora-alekseyu-navalnomu-politsiya-zaderzhivaet-lyudey-na-manezhnoy-ploschadi|url-status=live}}</ref> Navalny later returned to court for a trial on slander charges, where he was accused of defaming a [[World War II]] veteran who took part in a promotional video backing the [[2020 amendments to the Constitution of Russia|constitutional amendments]] last year. The case was launched in June 2020 after Navalny called those who took part in the video "corrupt lackeys" and "traitors". Navalny called the case politically motivated and accused authorities of using the case to smear his reputation. Although the charge is punishable by up to two years in prison if proven, his lawyer said that Navalny cannot face a custodial sentence because the law was changed to make it a jailable offence after the alleged crime had taken place.<ref>{{cite web|date=12 February 2021|title=Kremlin critic Navalny back in Moscow court for slander trial|url=https://www.france24.com/en/europe/20210212-kremlin-critic-navalny-back-in-moscow-court-for-slander-trial|publisher=France24|access-date=15 February 2021|archive-date=15 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210215131715/https://www.france24.com/en/europe/20210212-kremlin-critic-navalny-back-in-moscow-court-for-slander-trial|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=4 February 2021|title=Alexey Navalny to appear in court on Friday for war veteran defamation hearing|url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2021/02/04/alexey-navalny-to-appear-in-court-on-friday-for-war-veteran-defamation-hearing|website=Meduza|access-date=15 February 2021|archive-date=12 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210212230129/https://meduza.io/en/news/2021/02/04/alexey-navalny-to-appear-in-court-on-friday-for-war-veteran-defamation-hearing|url-status=live}}</ref>

The [[European Court of Human Rights]] ruled on 16 February 2021 that the Russian government should release Navalny immediately, with the court saying that the resolution was made in "regard to the nature and extent of risk to the applicant's life". Navalny's lawyers had applied to the court for an "interim measure" for his release on 20 January 2021 after his detention. However Russian officials indicated that they would not comply with the decision. Justice Minister [[Konstantin Chuychenko]] called the measure a "flagrant intervention in the operation of a judicial system of a sovereign state" as well as "unreasonable and unlawful", claiming that it did not "contain any reference to any fact or any norm of the law, which would have allowed the court to take this decision". In December 2020, a series of laws were also passed and signed that gave the constitution precedence over rulings made by international bodies as well international treaties.<ref>{{cite news|date=17 February 2021|title=European Rights Court Demands Navalny's 'Immediate' Release|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/17/european-rights-court-demands-navalnys-immediate-release-a72996|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=18 February 2021|archive-date=17 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217152040/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/17/european-rights-court-demands-navalnys-immediate-release-a72996|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=17 February 2021|title=European Rights Court Rules Russia Should 'Immediately' Release Navalny|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/european-rights-court-navalny/31107805.html|publisher=RFE/RL|access-date=18 February 2021|archive-date=18 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210218123024/https://www.rferl.org/a/european-rights-court-navalny/31107805.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=17 February 2021|title=Navalny must be freed, European rights court tells Russia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56102257|publisher=BBC News|access-date=15 March 2022|archive-date=15 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220315063713/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56102257|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=17 February 2021|title=Глава Минюста счел неисполнимым требование ЕСПЧ освободить Навального|trans-title=The head of the Ministry of Justice considered unrealistic the demand of the ECtHR to release Navalny|url=https://www.interfax.ru/russia/751442|website=[[Interfax]]|access-date=18 February 2021|archive-date=18 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210218202132/https://www.interfax.ru/russia/751442|url-status=live}}</ref> A few days later, a Moscow court rejected Navalny's appeal and upheld his prison sentence; however, it reduced his sentence by six weeks after deciding to count his time under house arrest as part of his time served. Another court convicted Navalny on slander charges against the World War II veteran, fining him 850,000 rubles (${{Formatprice|{{To USD|850000|RUS|year=2021}}|-2}}).<ref>{{cite news|date=20 February 2021|title=Moscow Court Upholds Prison Term for Kremlin Critic Navalny|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/20/moscow-court-upholds-prison-term-for-kremlin-critic-navalny-a73022|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=21 February 2021|archive-date=20 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210220223836/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/20/moscow-court-upholds-prison-term-for-kremlin-critic-navalny-a73022|url-status=live}}</ref>
[[File:Protests on Tverskaya Street.jpg|thumb|Protest in support of Navalny in Moscow, 21 April 2021]]

A resolution by the ECHR called for his release.<ref>{{cite news|date=17 February 2021|title='Release' Alexei Navalny, European Court of Human Rights tells Russia|language=en|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/release-alexei-navalny-european-court-of-human-rights-tells-russia/a-56600777|access-date=17 February 2021|archive-date=17 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217144332/https://www.dw.com/en/release-alexei-navalny-european-court-of-human-rights-tells-russia/a-56600777|url-status=live}}</ref>

Navalny was reported on 28 February 2021 to have recently arrived at the [[Corrective colony No. 2, Vladimir Oblast|Pokrov correctional colony]] in [[Vladimir Oblast]], a prison where [[Dmitry Demushkin]] and [[Konstantin Kotov (activist)|Konstantin Kotov]] were also jailed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sauer|first=Pjotr|date=28 February 2021|title='They Will Break You': Inside Navalny's Notorious New Prison Home|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/28/they-will-break-you-inside-navalnys-notorious-new-prison-home-a73099|access-date=1 March 2021|newspaper=The Moscow Times|language=en|archive-date=28 February 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210228215124/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/02/28/they-will-break-you-inside-navalnys-notorious-new-prison-home-a73099|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=28 February 2021|title=Navalny arrives at Russian penal colony|url=https://thewest.com.au/news/conflict/navalny-arrives-at-russian-penal-colony-ng-s-2051463|access-date=1 March 2021|newspaper=[[The West Australian]]|language=en|archive-date=2 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210302153924/https://thewest.com.au/news/conflict/navalny-arrives-at-russian-penal-colony-ng-s-2051463|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Navalny arrives in penal colony in Russia's Vladimir region – human rights activist|url=https://tass.com/russia/1261143|access-date=1 March 2021|publisher=[[TASS]]|archive-date=1 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210301054558/https://tass.com/russia/1261143|url-status=live}}</ref> In early March 2021, the European Union and United States imposed sanctions on senior Russian officials in response to Navalny's poisoning and imprisonment.<ref name="tmt-2-mar"/>

In March 2021, Navalny in a formal complaint accused authorities of torture by [[Sleep deprivation#Uses|depriving him of sleep]], where authorities consider him a flight risk. Navalny told lawyers that guards wake him up eight times a night announcing to a camera that he was in his prison cell. A lawyer of Navalny said that he was suffering from health problems, including [[Hypoesthesia|a loss of sensation]] in his [[Vertebral column|spine]] and legs, and that prison authorities denied Navalny's requests for a civilian physician, claiming his health was "satisfactory".<ref name="tmt-25-mar">{{cite news|date=25 March 2021|title=Navalny in 'Strong' Pain, Team Fears for His Life: Lawyer|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/03/25/navalny-in-strong-pain-team-fears-for-his-life-lawyer-a73370|newspaper=The Moscow Times|access-date=27 March 2021|archive-date=26 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210326075739/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/03/25/navalny-in-strong-pain-team-fears-for-his-life-lawyer-a73370|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=25 March 2021|title=Alexei Navalny says he is being 'tortured' in prison|url=https://www.dw.com/en/alexei-navalny-says-he-is-being-tortured-in-prison/a-56995363|publisher=Deutsche Welle|access-date=27 March 2021|archive-date=27 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210327002917/https://www.dw.com/en/alexei-navalny-says-he-is-being-tortured-in-prison/a-56995363|url-status=live}}</ref> On 31 March 2021, Navalny announced a [[hunger strike]] to demand proper medical treatment.<ref>{{cite news|date=31 March 2021|title=Putin critic Navalny on hunger strike over Russian prison treatment|language=en|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56595560|access-date=31 March 2021|archive-date=31 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210331170207/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56595560|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 April 2021, six doctors, including Navalny's personal physician, Anastasia Vasilyeva, and two CNN correspondents, were arrested outside the prison when they attempted to visit Navalny whose health significantly deteriorated.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brennan|first=David|date=6 April 2021|title=Alexei Navalny's Doctor Arrested as Vladimir Putin Critic Holds Prison Hunger Strike|work=[[Newsweek]]|url=https://www.newsweek.com/alexei-navalny-doctor-arrested-vladimir-putin-critic-holds-prison-hunger-strike-1581274|access-date=6 April 2021|archive-date=6 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210406133632/https://www.newsweek.com/alexei-navalny-doctor-arrested-vladimir-putin-critic-holds-prison-hunger-strike-1581274|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=6 April 2021|title=Six doctors, CNN correspondents detained outside Alexei Navalny's prison|publisher=[[ABC Australia]]|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-04-07/alexei-navalny-doctor-detained-prison-russia/100052100|access-date=6 April 2021|archive-date=6 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210406142544/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2021-04-07/alexei-navalny-doctor-detained-prison-russia/100052100|url-status=live}}</ref> On 7 April 2021, Navalny's attorneys claimed he had suffered two [[spinal disc herniation]]s and had lost feeling in his hands, prompting criticism from the U.S. government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Khurshudyan|first=Isabelle|date=7 April 2021|title=Jailed Kremlin critic Navalny has two herniated disks, loss of feeling in his hands, lawyers say|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/navalny-health-prison-russia-putin/2021/04/07/7e00d192-97b1-11eb-8f0a-3384cf4fb399_story.html|access-date=7 April 2021|newspaper=The Washington Post|archive-date=7 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210407144859/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/navalny-health-prison-russia-putin/2021/04/07/7e00d192-97b1-11eb-8f0a-3384cf4fb399_story.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Macias|first=Amanda|date=7 April 2021|title=U.S. disturbed over imprisoned Kremlin critic Navalny's deteriorating health|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/04/07/us-disturbed-over-kremlin-critic-navalnys-deteriorating-health.html|access-date=7 April 2021|publisher=[[CNBC]]|archive-date=7 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210407181920/https://www.cnbc.com/2021/04/07/us-disturbed-over-kremlin-critic-navalnys-deteriorating-health.html|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Agnès Callamard]], Secretary General of Amnesty International accused Vladimir Putin of slowly killing Alexei Navalny through torture and inhumane treatment in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jurist.org/news/2021/04/amnesty-russia-slowly-killing-navalny-through-inhumane-detention-conditions/|title=Amnesty: Russia 'slowly killing' Navalny through inhumane detention conditions|author=Zoe Gujral|publisher=[[University of Pittsburgh School of Law]]|date=7 April 2021|access-date=11 April 2021|archive-date=11 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210411014914/https://www.jurist.org/news/2021/04/amnesty-russia-slowly-killing-navalny-through-inhumane-detention-conditions/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="reuters-7-apr">{{cite news|date=7 April 2021|title=Amnesty International says Russia may be slowly killing Navalny|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-rights-amnesty-idUSKBN2BT31F|publisher=Reuters|access-date=7 April 2021|archive-date=7 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210407023454/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-rights-amnesty-idUSKBN2BT31F|url-status=live}}</ref> He also complained that he was not allowed to read newspapers or have any books including a copy of the [[Quran]] that he planned to study.<ref>{{cite news|last=Demidova|first=Olga|date=13 April 2021|title=Навальный подаст в суд на колонию из-за отказа дать ему привезенный Коран|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/ru/navalnyj-podast-v-sud-na-koloniju-iz-za-otkaza-dat-emu-privezennyj-koran/a-57184862|access-date=1 July 2021|archive-date=24 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624010310/https://www.dw.com/ru/navalnyj-podast-v-sud-na-koloniju-iz-za-otkaza-dat-emu-privezennyj-koran/a-57184862|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 17 April 2021, it was reported that Navalny was in immediate need of medical attention. Navalny's personal doctor Anastasia Vasilyeva and three other doctors, including cardiologist Yaroslav Ashikhmin, asked prison officials to grant them immediate access, stating on social media that "our patient can die any minute", due to an increased risk of a fatal cardiac arrest or kidney failure "at any moment".<ref>{{cite web|date=17 April 2021|title=Jailed Putin critic Alexei Navalny could die at any minute, doctors warn|url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/apr/18/jailed-putin-critic-alexei-navalny-could-die-at-any-minute-doctors-warn|access-date=18 April 2021|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en|archive-date=17 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210417235556/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/apr/18/jailed-putin-critic-alexei-navalny-could-die-at-any-minute-doctors-warn|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=17 April 2021|title=Health of Kremlin critic Alexei Navalny worsening amid prison hunger strike, doctor says|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/alexei-navalny-health-doctor-prison-hunger-strike-1.5992142}}</ref> Test results obtained by Navalny's lawyers showed heightened levels of [[potassium]] in the blood, which can bring on cardiac arrest, and sharply elevated [[creatinine]] levels, indicating impaired kidneys. Navalny's results showed blood potassium levels of 7.1&nbsp;mmol ([[millimole]]s) per liter; blood potassium levels higher than 6.0&nbsp;mmol per liter usually require immediate treatment.<ref>{{cite news|date=17 April 2021|title=Putin critic Navalny could 'die within days', say doctors|language=en|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56786266|access-date=18 April 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dixon|first=Robyn|author-link=Robyn Dixon (journalist)|date=18 April 2021|title=Navalny's daughter pleads for medical care for the imprisoned Kremlin critic amid mounting health concerns|language=en|newspaper=The Washington Post|location=Moscow|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/russia-navalny-health-putin/2021/04/18/6eb7a96a-9fc5-11eb-b2f5-7d2f0182750d_story.html|url-access=limited|access-date=21 April 2021|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Later that night, an open letter, addressed to Putin and open for Russian citizens to sign, was signed and published by 11 politicians representing several regional parliaments, demanding an independent doctor be allowed to visit Navalny, and for a review and cancellation of all of his criminal cases. "We regard what is happening in relation to Navalny as an attempt on the life of a politician, committed out of personal and political hatred," said the letter, "You, the President of the Russian Federation, personally bear responsibility for the life of Alexey Navalny on the territory of the Russian Federation, including in prison facilities – [you bear this responsibility] to Navalny himself, to his relatives, and to the whole world."<ref>{{cite news|author1=Anna Chernova |author2=Arnaud Siad|title=Navalny's life is Putin's 'personal' responsibility, say Russian politicians|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/04/18/europe/navalny-vladimir-putin-letter-intl/index.html|access-date=18 April 2021|publisher=CNN}}</ref> Among the signatories were chairman of the [[Pskov Oblast]] branch of the [[Yabloko]] party, the deputy of the regional assembly [[Lev Schlossberg]], the deputy from [[Karelia]], the ex-chairman of Yabloko [[Emilia Slabunova]], and the deputy of the Moscow City Duma Yevgeny Stupin.<ref>{{cite news|title=Шлосберг и другие депутаты обратились к Путину по ситуации с Навальным|trans-title=Schlosberg and other deputies appealed to Putin on the situation with Navalny|url=https://www.dw.com/ru/shlosberg-i-drugie-deputaty-obratilis-k-putinu-po-situacii-s-navalnym/a-57242635|access-date=18 April 2021|publisher=Deutsche Welle|language=ru}}</ref>

The following day, his daughter called on Russian prison authorities to let her father be checked by doctors in a tweet<ref>{{cite web|last=Navalny|first=Dasha|date=17 April 2021|title=Status 6:46&nbsp;pm|url=https://twitter.com/Dasha_Navalnaya/status/1383597776232009730|website=Twitter|quote=Allow a doctor to see my dad.}}</ref> written from [[Stanford University]], where she is a student. Prominent celebrities such as [[J.K. Rowling]] and [[Jude Law]] also addressed a letter<ref>{{cite news|date=16 April 2021|title=An open letter to Vladimir Putin On Alexei Navalny's detention|newspaper=The Economist|url=https://www.economist.com/letters/2021/04/16/on-alexei-navalnys-detention|quote=The president must ensure that the jailed Russian opposition leader has access to the medical care he needs}}</ref> to Russian authorities asking to provide Navalny with proper medical treatment.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tétrault-farber|first=Gabrielle|date=18 April 2021|title=Daughter of jailed Kremlin critic Alexei Navalny says he needs a doctor|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/daughter-jailed-kremlin-critic-alexei-navalny-says-he-needs-doctor-2021-04-18/|access-date=18 April 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=17 April 2021|title=Aleksei Navalny Needs His Doctors|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/17/opinion/navalny-poisoning-prison-doctors.html|archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/17/opinion/navalny-poisoning-prison-doctors.html|archive-date=28 December 2021|newspaper=The New York Times|url-access=subscription}}{{cbignore}}</ref> U.S. president [[Joe Biden]] called his treatment "totally unfair" and National Security Advisor [[Jake Sullivan]] said that the Kremlin had been warned "that there will be consequences if Mr. Navalny dies."<ref>{{cite news|date=18 April 2021|title=U.S. Warns of 'Consequences' if Navalny Dies as Russia Protests Called|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/04/18/mass-protests-called-across-russia-to-save-navalnys-life-a73637|newspaper=The Moscow Times}}</ref> The European Union's head diplomat [[Josep Borrell]] stated that the organisation held the Russian government accountable for Navalny's health conditions. The president of the [[European Commission]], [[Ursula von der Leyen]], also expressed her concern for his health.<ref name="Al J">{{cite news|title=As Western powers raise alarm, Navalny transferred to hospital|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/4/19/jailed-kremlin-critic-navalny-transferred-to-hospital|date=19 April 2021|publisher=Al Jazeera|language=en}}</ref> However, Russian authorities rebuked such concerns by foreign countries. Kremlin spokesperson [[Dmitry Peskov]] said that Russian prison officials are monitoring Navalny's health, not the president.<ref name="tmt-19-apr">{{cite news|date=19 April 2021|title=Kremlin Rejects Western Concerns Over Hunger-Striking Navalny's Health|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/04/19/kremlin-rejects-western-concerns-over-hunger-striking-navalnys-health-a73653|access-date=19 April 2021|newspaper=The Moscow Times|language=en}}</ref>

On 19 April 2021, Navalny was moved from prison to a hospital for convicts, according to the Russian prison service,<ref>{{cite news|date=19 April 2021|title=Russian prison service transfers Alexei Navalny to hospital|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/russian-prison-service-transfers-alexei-navalny-to-hospital/a-57248156|access-date=19 April 2021}}</ref><ref name="Al J"/> for "vitamin therapy".<ref name="tmt-19-apr"/> On 23 April 2021, Navalny announced that he was ending his hunger strike on advice of his doctors and as he felt his demands had been partially met.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kramer|first=Andrew E.|date=23 April 2021|title=Navalny, Putin's Nemesis, Ends Hunger Strike in Russia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/23/world/europe/russia-navalny-putin-hunger-strike.html|archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20211228/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/04/23/world/europe/russia-navalny-putin-hunger-strike.html|archive-date=28 December 2021|access-date=23 April 2021|website=The New York Times|url-access=subscription}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Navalny ends hunger strike after being seen by civilian doctors|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/4/23/navalny-ends-hunger-strike-after-being-seen-by-civilian-doctors|access-date=24 April 2021|publisher=Al Jazeera|language=en}}</ref> {{As of| June 2021}}, his newspapers were still being censored as articles were cut out.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zverev|first1=Anton|last2=Marrow|first2=Alexander|date=2 June 2021|title=Kremlin critic Navalny loses bid to end sleep deprivation 'torture'|publisher=The Globe and Mail Inc|agency=Reuters|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-kremlin-critic-navalny-loses-bid-to-end-sleep-deprivation-torture/}}</ref>

===Designation as extremist===

On 16 April 2021, the Moscow prosecutor office requested the [[Moscow City Court]] to designate organisations linked to Navalny including the Anti-Corruption Foundation and his headquarters as extremist organisations, claiming: "Under the disguise of liberal slogans, these organisations are engaged in creating conditions for the destabilisation of the social and socio-political situation."<ref>{{cite web|date=16 April 2021|title=Прокуратура потребовала признать ФБК экстремистской организацией|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2021/04/16/prokuratura-potrebovala-priznat-fbk-ekstremistskoy-organizatsiey|website=Meduza}}</ref> In response, Navalny aide [[Leonid Volkov (politician)|Leonid Volkov]] stated: "Putin has just announced full-scale mass political repression in Russia."<ref>{{cite news|date=16 April 2021|title=Russian Prosecutors Seek to Label Navalny Groups as 'Extremist'|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/04/16/russian-prosecutors-seek-to-label-navalny-groups-as-extremist-a73631|newspaper=The Moscow Times}}</ref>

On 26 April 2021, Moscow's prosecutor office ordered Navalny's network of regional offices, including those of the FBK, to cease its activities, pending a court ruling on whether to designate them as extremist organisations. Volkov explained that it will limit many of the group's activities as prosecutors seek to label the Foundation as "extremists".<ref>{{cite news|date=26 April 2021|title=Russia suspends activities of Alexei Navalny's campaign groups|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/russia-suspends-activities-of-alexei-navalnys-campaign-groups/a-57335053|access-date=26 April 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=26 April 2021|title=Navalny support network ordered to stop Russia-wide activities|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-56888845|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> The move was condemned by Germany as well as [[Amnesty International]], which, in a statement, said: "The objective is clear: to raze Alexei Navalny's movement to the ground while he languishes in prison."<ref>{{cite news|date=26 April 2021|title=Russia Orders Navalny Group to Suspend Activities|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/04/26/russia-orders-navalny-group-to-suspend-activities-a73734|newspaper=The Moscow Times}}</ref>

On 29 April 2021, Navalny's team announced that the political network would be dissolved, in advance of a court ruling in May expected to designate it as extremist.<ref>{{cite news|date=29 April 2021|title=Navalny Dissolves Political Network Ahead of Expected 'Extremist' Ruling|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/04/29/navalny-dissolves-political-network-ahead-of-expected-extremist-ruling-a73774|newspaper=The Moscow Times}}</ref> According to Volkov, the headquarters would be transformed into independent political organisations "which will deal with investigations and elections, public campaigns and rallies".<ref>{{cite web|date=29 April 2021|title=Леонид Волков объявил о закрытии сети штабов Навального|trans-title=Leonid Volkov announced the closure of Navalny's network of headquarters|language=ru|url=https://meduza.io/news/2021/04/29/leonid-volkov-ob-yavil-o-zakrytii-seti-shtabov-navalnogo|website=Meduza}}</ref> On the same day, his allies said that a new criminal case had been opened against Navalny, for allegedly setting up a non-profit organisation that infringed on the rights of citizens.<ref>{{cite news|date=29 April 2021|title=Russia opens new criminal case against Navalny – allies|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russia-opens-new-criminal-case-against-navalny-allies-2021-04-29/|access-date=29 April 2021}}</ref> The next day, the leader of [[Team 29]], [[Ivan Pavlov (lawyer)|Ivan Pavlov]], who also represents Navalny's team in the extremism case, was detained in Moscow.<ref>{{cite web|date=30 April 2021|title=В Москве задержали главу "Команды 29" – адвоката Ивана Павлова, защищающего ФБК и Ивана Сафронова.|trans-title=In Moscow, the head of "Team 29", lawyer Ivan Pavlov, who defends the FBK, and Ivan Safronov, were detained.|language=ru|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2021/04/30/v-moskve-zaderzhali-glavu-komandy-29-advokata-ivana-pavlova-zaschischayuschego-fbk-i-ivana-safronova-glavnoe|website=Meduza}}</ref>

On 30 April, the financial monitoring agency added Navalny's regional campaign offices to a list of "terrorists and extremists."<ref>{{cite news|date=30 April 2021|title=Russia adds Navalny's regional campaign offices to 'extremism' list|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/russia-adds-navalnys-regional-campaign-offices-extremism-list-2021-04-30/|access-date=30 April 2021}}</ref> On 20 May, the head of the Russian prison system and Navalny's ally [[Ivan Zhdanov]] reported that Navalny had "more or less" recovered and that his health was generally satisfactory.<ref>{{cite news|date=20 May 2021|title=Russia: Navalny 'recovered' after hunger strike, says prison authority|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/russia-navalny-recovered-after-hunger-strike-says-prison-authority/a-57593621|access-date=20 May 2021}}</ref> On 7 June, Navalny was returned to prison after fully recovering from the effects of the hunger strike.<ref>{{cite news|date=7 June 2021|title=Alexei Navalny returns to prison after hunger strike|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/alexei-navalny-returns-to-prison-after-hunger-strike/a-57799841|access-date=7 June 2021}}</ref>

On 9 June 2021, Navalny's political network, including his headquarters and the FBK, were designated as extremist organisations and liquidated by the Moscow City Court.<ref>{{cite news|date=9 June 2021|title=Russia Blacklists Navalny's Political and Activist Movements as 'Extremist'|language=en|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/06/09/russia-blacklists-navalnys-political-and-activist-movements-as-extremist-a74159|newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=9 June 2021|title=Мосгорсуд признал ФБК экстремистской организацией|language=ru|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|url=https://www.dw.com/ru/mosgorsud-priznal-fbk-jekstremistskoj-organizaciej/a-57825179}}</ref> Vyacheslav Polyga, judge of Moscow City Court, upheld the administrative claim of the prosecutor of Moscow city Denis Popov and, rejecting all the petitions of the defense, decided<ref>{{cite web|title=Решение Московского городского суда от 09.06.2021 года по делу №3а-1573/2021|language=ru|trans-title=Moscow City Court decision of 9 June 2021 in the case No.3а-1573/2021|url=https://team29.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Reshenie_FBK.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210629180921/https://team29.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/Reshenie_FBK.pdf|archive-date=29 June 2021|publisher=Team29.org}}</ref> to recognise Anti-Corruption Foundation as extremist organisation, to liquidate it and to confiscate its assets; similar decision had been taken against the Citizens' Rights Protection Foundation; the activity of the Alexei Navalny staff was prohibited (case No.3а-1573/2021).<ref>{{cite news|date=9 June 2021|title=Мосгорсуд признал ФБК и штабы Навального экстремистскими организациями|language=ru|trans-title=The Moscow City Court recognised the FBK and Navalny's headquarters as extremist organisations|publisher=[[Mediazona]]|url=https://zona.media/news/2021/06/09/fbk|access-date=10 June 2021}}</ref>

Case hearing was held [[in camera]] because, as indicated by advocate [[Ilia Novikov]], the case file including the text of the administrative claim was [[Classified information|classified]] as state secret.<ref>{{cite news|title="ФБК – это самая важная организация в России. Прокуроры нас убеждали в том же самом" Интервью адвоката Ильи Новикова – об итогах суда над структурами Навального|language=ru|date=11 June 2021|publisher=[[Meduza]]|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2021/06/10/fbk-eto-samaya-vazhnaya-organizatsiya-v-rossii-prokurory-nas-ubezhdali-v-tom-zhe-samom}}</ref> According to advocate [[Ivan Pavlov (lawyer)|Ivan Pavlov]], Navalny was not a party to the proceedings and the judge refused to grant him that status; at the hearing, the prosecutor stated that defendants are extremist organisations because they want a change of power in Russia and have promised to assist protest participants by paying administrative and criminal fines, as well as filing complaints with the European Court of Human Rights.<ref>{{cite news|title=Суд признал ФБК и Штабы Навального экстремистскими и запретил их|language=ru|trans-title=The court recognised the FBK and Navalny's Headquarters as extremist and banned them|date=9 June 2021|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|Radio Liberty]]|url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/mosgorsud-priznal-fbk-i-shtaby-navaljnogo-ekstremistskimi-i-zapretil/31299399.html}}</ref> On 4 August 2021, First Court of Appeal of General Jurisdiction in Moscow upheld the decision of the court of first instance (case No.66а-3553/2021) and this decision entered into force that day.<ref>{{cite web|date=4 August 2021|title=ФБК не прошел апелляцию|trans-title=FBK did not pass the appeal|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4928980|access-date=25 August 2021|newspaper=[[Kommersant]]|language=ru}}</ref>

On 28 December 2021, it was reported that the [[Anti-Corruption Foundation]], the Citizens' Rights Protection Foundation and 18 individuals, including Alexei Navalny, filed a cassational appeal with the Second Court of Cassation of General Jurisdiction.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kropman|first=Vitaliy|title=Признание ФБК "экстремистской организацией" обжаловано в суде|language=ru|date=28 December 2021|magazine=[[Deutsche Welle]]|url=https://www.dw.com/ru/priznanie-fbk-jekstremistskoj-organizaciej-obzhalovali-v-sude/a-60277415}}</ref> On 25 March 2022, the Second Court of Cassation rejected all the appeals and upheld the judgements of the lower courts (case No.8а-5101/2022).<ref>{{cite news|title=Кассационный суд отклонил жалобы на признание ФБК экстремистской организацией|language=ru|date=25 March 2022|publisher=[[Russian Agency of Legal and Judicial Information]]|url=http://rapsinews.ru/judicial_news/20220325/307827684.html}}</ref>

In October 2021, Navalny said that the Russian prison commission designated him as a "terrorist" and "extremist", but that he was no longer regarded as a flight risk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/10/11/kremlin-critic-navalny-says-he-is-now-designated-a-terrorist|title=Kremlin critic Navalny says he is now designated a 'terrorist'|publisher=[[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]}}</ref> In January 2022, Russia added him and his aides to the "terrorists and extremists" list.<ref>{{cite news|date=25 January 2022|title=Russia Adds Navalny To 'Terrorists' List As Civil-Society Crackdown Continues|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-navalny-terrorists-extremists/31670205.html|access-date=25 January 2022|publisher=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|Radio Liberty]]|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=25 January 2022|title=Russia Adds Navalny, Top Aides To 'Terrorists and Extremists' Register|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/01/25/russia-adds-navalny-top-aides-to-terrorists-and-extremists-register-a76144|access-date=25 January 2022|publisher=[[The Moscow Times]]|language=en}}</ref> On 28 June 2022, Navalny lost his appeal on being designated as "extremist" and "terrorist".<ref>{{cite news|date=28 June 2022|title=Navalny loses appeal over being labelled an extremist and a terrorist|url=https://www.euronews.com/2022/06/08/navalny-loses-appeal-over-being-labelled-an-extremist-and-a-terrorist|access-date=29 June 2022|agency=[[Euronews]]}}</ref>

[[File:Navalny;Cellule d'isolement Shizo; Genève.jpg|thumb|Interior of the replica solitary confinement cell for Navalny, called shizo in [[Geneva]], June 2023]]

===Later charges===
In February 2022, Alexei Navalny faced an additional 10 to 15 years in prison in a new trial on fraud and contempt of court charges.<ref>{{cite news|date=15 February 2022|title=Alexei Navalny faces additional 10-year jail sentence on fraud charges|url=https://www.euronews.com/2022/02/15/alexei-navalny-kremlin-critic-faces-additional-10-year-jail-sentence-on-fraud-charges|access-date=22 February 2022|publisher=[[Euronews]]|language=en}}</ref><ref name="trial"/> The charges alleged that he stole $4.7m (£3.5m) of donations given to his political organisations and insulted a judge.<ref>{{cite news|date=16 February 2022|title=Putin critic Navalny put on trial again in Russia|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-60387695|access-date=19 February 2022}}</ref><ref name="trial">{{cite news|date=15 February 2022|title=Alexei Navalny faces new trial inside Russian prison|url=https://www.dw.com/en/alexei-navalny-faces-new-trial-inside-russian-prison/a-60787817|publisher=Deutsche Welle|access-date=19 February 2022}}</ref> He was tried in a makeshift courtroom in the [[Corrective colony No. 2, Vladimir Oblast|corrective colony]] at which he was imprisoned.<ref name="2022_domicile">{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|date=15 February 2022|title=Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny faces a new trial, this time in prison|language=en|work=NPR|url=https://www.npr.org/2022/02/15/1081009674/russia-opposition-leader-alexei-navalny-new-trial-prison-putin|access-date=22 February 2022}}</ref> Amnesty International independently analysed the trial materials calling the charges "arbitrary" and "politically motivated".<ref name="amnesty-review-2022">{{cite web |title=Russia: Fraud charges against Aleksei Navalny are arbitrary and politically motivated |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/EUR4653292022ENGLISH.pdf |website=Amnesty International |access-date=22 March 2022}}</ref>

On 21 February 2022, prosecution witness Fyodor Gorozhanko refused to testify against Navalny in the trial, stating that investigators had "pressured" him to testify to the information they wanted and that he did not believe Navalny had committed any crimes.<ref>{{cite news|title=На суде над Навальным свидетель обвинения отказался от показаний|trans-title=At the trial of Navalny, the witness for the prosecution refused to testify|url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/na-sude-nad-navaljnym-svidetelj-obvineniya-otkazalsya-davatj-pokazaniya/31714818.html|access-date=22 February 2022|publisher=RFE/RL|language=ru}}</ref> On 24 February, during his trial, Navalny condemned the [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|Russian invasion of Ukraine]] that began that day and asked the court to include his statement to the trial's protocol. He said that it would "lead to a huge number of victims, destroyed futures, and the continuation of this line of impoverishment of the citizens of Russia." He called the war a distraction to the population to "divert their attention from problems that exist inside the country".<ref>{{cite news|title=Jailed Russian Opposition Politician Navalny Condemns Russia's Attack On Ukraine At Trial|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/navalny-condemns-russia-attack-ukraine/31720484.html|publisher=RFE/RL|date=24 February 2022}}</ref>

On 22 March 2022, Navalny was found guilty of contempt of court and embezzlement and given a 9-year sentence in a maximum-security prison; he was also ordered to pay a fine of 1.2&nbsp;million rubles (approx. $13,000).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/03/22/navalny-sentenced-to-9-more-years-in-prison-a77027|title=Navalny Sentenced to 9 More Years in Prison|website=The Moscow Times|date=23 March 2022}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]] described the trial as a "sham".<ref name="2022-conviction-bbc">{{cite web |title=Russia Navalny: Putin critic jailed for nine more years in trial branded 'sham' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-60832310 |website=BBC News |access-date=22 March 2022 |date=22 March 2022}}</ref>

On 17 May 2022, Navalny opened an appeal process against the sentence; the court said the process would resume on 24 May after Navalny requested to postpone the hearing to have a family meeting before being transferred.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/05/17/kremlin-critic-navalny-appeals-jail-sentence-a77703|title=Kremlin Critic Navalny Appeals Jail Sentence|website=[[The Moscow Times]]|date=17 May 2022}}</ref> On 24 May, the Moscow City Court upheld the judgement of the court of first instance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Навальный. Апелляция на приговор по делу о мошенничестве, день второй|language=ru|date=24 May 2022|magazine=[[Mediazona]]|url=https://zona.media/online/2022/05/24/naval-2}}</ref>

On 31 May 2022, Navalny said that he was officially notified about new charges of extremism brought against him, in which he was facing up to an additional 15 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/05/31/kremlin-foe-navalny-says-facing-15-more-years-in-prison-a77852|title=Kremlin Foe Navalny Says Facing 15 More Years in Prison|website=[[The Moscow Times]]|date=31 May 2022}}</ref>

In mid-June 2022, Navalny was transferred to the maximum security prison [[IK-6 Penal Colony|IK-6]] in [[Melekhovo, Vladimir Oblast|Melekhovo]], [[Vladimir Oblast]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Muniz |first1=Liliana |title=Alexei Navalny moved to infamous maximum security prison, says aide |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/alexei-navalny-opposition-leader-move-maximum-security-prison/ |agency=[[Politico Europe]] |date=15 June 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://meduza.io/feature/2022/06/15/alekseya-navalnogo-otpravili-v-pytochnuyu-koloniyu-6-vo-vladimirskoy-oblasti|title=Алексея Навального отправили в "пыточную" колонию № 6 во Владимирской области|website=[[Meduza]]|date=15 June 2022}}</ref>

On 11 July 2022, Navalny announced the relaunch of his [[Anti-Corruption Foundation]] as an international organisation with an advisory board including his wife [[Yulia Navalnaya]], [[Guy Verhofstadt]], [[Anne Applebaum]], and [[Francis Fukuyama]]; Navalny also stated that the first contribution to Anti-Corruption Foundation International would be the [[Sakharov Prize]] ($50,000) that was awarded to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russias-navalny-launches-international-anti-corruption-fund-2022-07-11/|title=Russia's Navalny launches international anti-corruption fund|website=[[Reuters]]|date=11 July 2022}}</ref>

On 7 September 2022, Navalny said that he had been placed in solitary confinement for the fourth time in just over a month, immediately following his release. He attributed this treatment to his attempts to establish a labour union in his penal colony and his "6000" list of individuals he has called to be sanctioned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/09/07/navalny-put-in-solitary-confinement-for-fourth-time-in-month-a78737|title=Navalny Put in Solitary Confinement for Fourth Time in Month|website=[[The Moscow Times]]|date=8 September 2022}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2024|reason=Source does not mention the 6000 List}} The next day, he said that his attorney-client privilege was revoked with prison authorities accusing him of continuing to commit crimes from prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/navalny-attorney-client-privilege-revoked/32024731.html|title=Navalny Says Russian Prison Authorities Revoked His Attorney-Client Privilege|website=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|date=8 September 2022}}</ref>
[[File:Berlin FreeNavalny Birthday rally asv2023-06 img12.jpg|thumb|FreeNavalny rally in [[Berlin]] on Navalny's 47th birthday, 4 June 2023. Some protesters have a [[White-blue-white flag]].]]
On 4 October 2022, allies of Navalny said they were relaunching his regional political network to fight the [[2022 Russian mobilization|mobilization]] and war.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/10/04/team-navalny-says-relaunching-regional-network-to-resist-war-mobilization-a78975|title=Team Navalny Says Relaunching Regional Network to Resist War, Mobilization|website=The Moscow Times|date=4 October 2022}}</ref>

On 17 November 2022, Navalny stated that he was now in permanent solitary confinement. Infractions besides the attempt to start a labour union among the prisoners were that he did not button his collar, did not clean the prison yard well enough, and that he addressed a prison official by his military rank rather than his [[patronymic]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=17 November 2022 |title=Navalny says he is now in permanent solitary confinement. |work=NYT |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/11/17/world/europe/russia-alexei-navalny-solitary-confinement.html}}</ref>

On 10 January 2023, over 400 doctors in Russia signed an open letter to president Putin demanding that prison authorities "stop abusing" Navalny, after it became known that he fell ill with flu in solitary confinement and his lawyers were not allowed to give him basic medication.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/news-64239241|title=Навальный заболел в ШИЗО. Что говорят врачи, потребовавшие от Путина "прекратить издевательства" над политиком|website=BBC News Russian|date=11 January 2022}}</ref> Less than a month later, Navalny was transferred to an isolated punishment cell, a stricter form of imprisonment reserved for those who violate prison rules, for the maximum term of six months.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Алексею Навальному ужесточили режим заключения |url=https://www.rbc.ru/politics/01/02/2023/63da60ae9a7947f48aa3c8f1 |access-date=1 February 2023 |website=РБК |date=February 2023 |language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Berkhead |first=Samantha |date=1 February 2023 |title=Ailing Navalny Ordered to 6 Months in Punishment Cell |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2023/02/01/ailing-navalny-ordered-to-6-months-in-punishment-cell-a80114 |access-date=1 February 2023 |website=The Moscow Times |language=en}}</ref>

On 4 August 2023, Navalny was sentenced to an additional 19 years in a "special regime" colony on charges including publicly inciting extremist activity, financing extremist activity, and "rehabilitating Nazi ideology"; the Moscow City Court found him guilty on all charges in a closed-doors trial.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://meduza.io/feature/2023/08/04/alekseya-navalnogo-prigovorili-k-19-godam-kolonii-po-delu-ob-ekstremizme |title=Алексея Навального приговорили к 19 годам колонии "особого режима" по делу об "экстремизме" |trans-title= |website=[[Meduza]] |date=4 August 2023}}</ref> In a social media post published the previous day, Navalny stated that he had expected to be given a "Stalinist" sentence and called on supporters to fight against corruption.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2023/08/04/russia-sentences-navalny-to-19-years-behind-bars-in-extremism-trial-a82056 |title=Russia Sentences Navalny to 19 Years Behind Bars in 'Extremism' Trial |website=[[The Moscow Times]] |access-date=15 October 2023 |date=4 August 2023}}</ref> According to his lawyers, following this latest sentencing, Navalny would have been released in December 2038.<ref name="gazette">{{Cite web |date=4 December 2023 |title=Суд утвердил приговор Навальному. Он останется в колонии до 2038 года |url=https://www.gazeta.ru/social/2023/09/26/17647123.shtml |access-date=4 December 2023 |website=Газета.Ru |language=ru |archive-date=4 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231204061907/https://www.gazeta.ru/social/2023/09/26/17647123.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 13 October 2023, three of his lawyers, Vadim Kobzev, Igor Sergunin and Alexei Liptser, were detained on charges about participating in an "extremist group". Navalny commented that "Just like in Soviet times, not only political activists are being prosecuted and turned into political prisoners, but their lawyers, too".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/russian-authorities-raid-homes-lawyers-imprisoned-opposition-leader-103951431 |title=Russia raids the homes of lawyers for imprisoned opposition leader Alexei Navalny | website=ABC News |date=13 October 2023 |access-date=15 October 2023}}</ref>

===In IK-3 "special regime" colony===
{{main|Polar Wolf}}

[[File:Kharp panorama.jpg|thumb|Kharp and IK-3]]
On 11 December 2023, Navalny's aides revealed that they had not had any contact with Navalny for six days. According to their statements, he was removed from the penal colony where he had been imprisoned and his current whereabouts are not known. The disappearance came after Navalny was sentenced to an additional 19 years in August and the beginning of campaigning for the [[2024 Russian presidential election]], which Putin recently announced his candidacy for. Navalny's aides had been preparing for his transfer to a "special regime" colony (the harshest grade in Russia's prison system).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russias-navalny-removed-prison-colony-whereabouts-unclear-supporters-2023-12-11/|title=Navalny aides says he has disappeared within Russia's prison system|first1=Mark|last1=Trevelyan|date=11 December 2023|website=Reuters}}</ref> His last known whereabouts was the [[Corrective colony No. 6, Vladimir Oblast|IK-6]] prison camp in [[Vladimir Oblast]], where on 15 December staff commented that Navalny had left the facility and was being moved to a different prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/whereabouts-russias-navalny-still-unknown-ally-2023-12-15/|title=Alexei Navalny is being moved to a new Russian prison – authorities|website=[[Reuters]] |access-date=16 February 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=15 December 2023 |title=ФСИН сообщила об убытии Навального "за пределы" Владимирской области |url=https://www.rbc.ru/politics/15/12/2023/657c063e9a7947716c8d6656 |access-date=16 December 2023 |website=РБК |language=ru}}</ref> On 25 December 2023 he was discovered to be in the [[FKU IK-3, Kharp|IK-3]] "special regime" colony, known as "Polar Wolf", in [[Kharp]] in the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug.<ref name="disappear" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Sauer |first=Pjotr |date=25 December 2023 |title=Alexei Navalny discovered in remote Arctic penal colony |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/dec/25/alexei-navalny-discovered-in-remote-arctic-penal-colony |access-date=25 December 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=25 December 2023 |title=Kremlin critic Navalny moved to Arctic penal colony: ally |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20231225-kremlin-critic-navalny-moved-to-arctic-penal-colony-ally |access-date=25 December 2023 |website=France 24 |language=en}}</ref> He remained there until his death on 16 February 2024.<ref name="skyd">{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/russian-opposition-politician-and-putin-critic-alexei-navalny-has-died-13072837|title=Alexei Navalny: Putin critic dies after 'losing consciousness' at maximum security prison|website=Sky News|access-date=16 February 2024}}</ref><ref name="bbcd">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-68315943|title=Russian opposition leader Navalny has died, prison service says|date=16 February 2024|access-date=16 February 2024|website=BBC News}}</ref>

===Political prisoner status===

Human Rights Centre [[Memorial (society)|Memorial]] recognised Navalny as a [[political prisoner]] in 2021.<ref>{{cite web|date=18 January 2021|title=Задержание Навального – политически мотивированный произвол и расправа|trans-title=The detention of Navalny is politically motivated arbitrariness and reprisal|url=https://memohrc.org/ru/news_old/zaderzhanie-navalnogo-politicheski-motivirovannyy-proizvol-i-rasprava|access-date=4 February 2021|website=memohrc.org|publisher=[[Memorial (society)]]|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=18 January 2021|title=HRC "Memorial" recognises Alexei Navalny as a political prisoner|url=https://www.eng.kavkaz-uzel.eu/articles/53414/|access-date=4 February 2021|website=[[Caucasian Knot]]}}</ref> [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe|PACE]] also considered Navalny a political prisoner.<ref>{{cite web |title=PACE's General Rapporteur for political prisoners strongly condemns Alexei Navalny's recent sentencing |url=https://www.coe.int/bs/web/portal/-/pace-s-general-rapporteur-for-political-prisoners-strongly-condemns-alexei-navalny-s-recent-sentencing |website=Council of Europe |access-date=26 December 2023}}</ref>

On 24 May 2024, ''[[DW News]]'' broadcast a piece which related that Navalny and [[Evan Gershkovich]] had in early 2024 almost been exchanged for [[Vadim Krasikov]], who in August 2019 in Berlin's [[Tiergarten Park]] assassinated [[Zelimkhan Khangoshvili]], a Georgian national and ethnic [[Chechens|Chechen]] who opposed with violence Putin's regime.<ref name="dwn1">{{cite news |title='A killer in the service of the Kremlin' Will Russia's assassin be exchanged? |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V3J2QB7FrsQ |agency=YouTube |publisher=DW News |date=24 May 2024}}</ref>

==Death and legacy==
{{Main|Death and funeral of Alexei Navalny}}

[[File:Grave of Alexey Navalny.jpg|thumb|Alexei Navalny's grave, March 2024]]
On 16 February 2024, the Federal Penitentiary Service announced that Navalny had died in prison in [[Yamalo-Nenets]] in [[Western Siberia]] after taking a walk and feeling unwell that morning. He reportedly died at 14:17 [[Yekaterinburg Time]]. The prison statement stated: "All necessary resuscitation measures were carried out but did not yield positive results [...]. The paramedics confirmed the death of the convict."<ref name="bbcd"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Russia-Ukraine war live: Alexei Navalny dies in prison after morning walk, says Russian prison service |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2024/feb/16/ukraine-war-live-russia-avdiivka-assault-continues-as-zelenskiy-set-to-visit-europe |website=Guardian |access-date=16 February 2024 |last1=Luscombe |first1=Richard |last2=Oladipo |first2=Gloria |last3=Slawson |first3=Nicola}}</ref> [[Kira Yarmysh]], Navalny's spokeswoman, confirmed his death the following day and demanded his body to be returned to his family.<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1758801430125695199 |user=Kira_Yarmysh |title=Alexey Navalny was murdered. His death occurred on February 16 at 2:17 p.m. local time, according to the official message to Alexey's mother. An employee of the colony said that the body of Navalny is now in Salekhard. It was picked up by investigators from the IC. Now they are conducting "investigations" with him. We demand that Alexey Navalny's body be handed over to his family immediately. |first=Kira |last=Yarmysh |author-link=Kira Yarmysh |date=17 February 2024 |access-date=17 February 2024}}</ref> Prior to his death, Navalny had been treated in a hospital after complaining of [[malnourishment]] and other ailments due to mistreatment in the prison.<ref>{{cite news |title=Russian activist and Putin critic Alexei Navalny dies in prison |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/feb/16/russian-activist-and-putin-critic-alexei-navalny-dies-in-prison |access-date=17 February 2024 |work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2024 |last1=Roth |first1=Andrew }}</ref> His body was returned to his mother on 24 February 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 February 2024 |title=Navalny's body returned to mother, spokeswoman says |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-68393412 |access-date=24 February 2024 |website=BBC News |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 27 February 2024, Vasily Dubkov, a lawyer for Navalny, was briefly detained in Moscow for "violating public order", as part of the ongoing crackdowns on Navalny's legal team and the [[Anti-Corruption Foundation]] by Russian authorities.<ref>{{Cite news |date=27 February 2024 |title=Alexei Navalny: Opposition leader's lawyer briefly held in Moscow – reports |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-68418193 |access-date=28 February 2024 |work=BBC News |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=27 February 2024 |title=Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny's lawyer 'arrested in Moscow' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/alexei-navalny-lawyer-russia-arrest-b2503426.html |access-date=28 February 2024 |website=The Independent |language=en}}</ref><ref name="bbc2">{{cite news |date=27 February 2024 |title=Alexei Navalny: Opposition leader's lawyer briefly held in Moscow - reports |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-68418193}}</ref>

On 13 October 2023, three of Navalny's lawyers, Igor Sergunin, Alexei Liptser and Vadim Kobzev, were arrested and charged with "participation in an extremist community" for passing on his messages from the penal colony to the outside world. The punishment for this crime is up to 6 years in prison.<ref name="mz1">{{cite news |url=https://en.zona.media/article/2023/10/13/lawyers |title=From courtroom to jail. Navalny's lawyers Vadim Kobzev, Alexei Liptser, and Igor Sergunin are now behind bars }}</ref>

''[[Patriot (book)|Patriot]]'', a memoir which Navalny started writing in Germany after being poisoned,<ref>{{cite web |last=Alter |first=Alexandra |title=Aleksei Navalny Wrote a Memoir Before He Died in Prison. It's Coming Oct. 22. |website=[[New York Times]] |date=11 April 2024 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/04/11/books/booksupdate/aleksei-navalny-memoir.html |access-date=24 October 2024}}</ref> was published posthumously on 22 October 2024, launched by his wife Yulia Navalnaya.<ref name=bbcinterview2024/> He said that he planned to write "an autobiography with an intriguing thriller about uncovering an assassination attempt using chemical weapons", but then he says it turned into more of "a prison diary", which has led to comparisons with [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]] and [[Vladimir Bukovsky]].<ref name="Cadwalladr"/> In 2025, the book was declared an "extremist material" by the Russian justice ministry.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Russia Declares Navalny Memoir ‘Extremist’ |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2025/07/31/russia-declares-navalny-memoir-extremist-a90046 |date=2025-07-31 |access-date=2025-07-31 |website=[[The Moscow Times]]}}</ref>

== Reception ==

=== Political activities ===
[[File:Yulia Navalny, Alexey Navalny and Ilya Yashin at Moscow rally 2013-06-12 2.JPG|thumb|Navalny, his wife [[Yulia Navalnaya|Yulia]] and Russian opposition politician [[Ilya Yashin]], 12 June 2013]]

In October 2010, Navalny was the winner of an online poll for the [[mayor of Moscow]], held by ''[[Kommersant]]'' and ''[[Gazeta.Ru]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Petrov|first=Nikolay |date=8 December 2010 |title=The Navalny Effect: RosPil.net |url=https://carnegiemoscow.org/2010/12/08/navalny-effect-rospil.net-pub-42105 |access-date=8 September 2021 |website=[[Carnegie Moscow Center]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=8 October 2010|script-title=ru:Выборы мэра Москвы|trans-title=Election of the mayor of Moscow|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/1512620|access-date=8 September 2021|newspaper=Kommersant|language=ru}}</ref> He received about 30,000 votes, or 45%, with the closest rival being "Against all candidates" with some 9,000 votes (14%), followed by former [[First Deputy Prime Minister of Russia|First Deputy Prime Minister]] of Russia [[Boris Nemtsov]] with 8,000 votes (12%) out of a total of about 67,000 votes.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ru:Выборы мэра Москвы|language=ru|newspaper=Gazeta.ru|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/2010/10/07_a_3426748.shtml|url-status=live|access-date=9 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012033845/http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/2010/10/07_a_3426748.shtml|archive-date=12 October 2010}}</ref>

The reaction to Navalny's actual mayoral election result in 2013, where he came second, was mixed: ''[[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]]'' declared, "The voting campaign turned a blogger into a politician",<ref name="ng" /> and following an October 2013 Levada Center poll that showed Navalny made it to the list of potential presidential candidates among Russians, receiving a rating of 5%, Konstantin Kalachev, the leader of the Political Expert Group, declared 5% was not the limit for Navalny, and unless something extraordinary happened, he could become "a pretender for a second place in the presidential race".<ref>{{cite news|author=Вера Кичанова|title=Republic.ru |script-title=ru:Навальный будет претендентом на второе место в президентской гонке|url=http://slon.ru/russia/navalnyy_budet_pretendentom_na_vtoroe_mesto_v_prezidentskoy_gonke-1028486.xhtml|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105065306/http://slon.ru/russia/navalnyy_budet_pretendentom_na_vtoroe_mesto_v_prezidentskoy_gonke-1028486.xhtml|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Slon.ru}}</ref> On the other hand, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' published a column by Milan Svolik that stated the election was fair so the Sobyanin could show a clean victory, demoralising the opposition, which could otherwise run for street protests.<ref>{{cite news|last=Svolik|first=Milan|date=12 October 2013|title=The best way to demoralise the opposition in Russia? Beat them in a fair election|newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/monkey-cage/wp/2013/10/12/the-best-way-to-demoralize-the-opposition-in-russia-beat-them-in-a-fair-election/|url-status=live |access-date=29 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514074201/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/monkey-cage/wp/2013/10/12/the-best-way-to-demoralize-the-opposition-in-russia-beat-them-in-a-fair-election/|archive-date=14 May 2015}}</ref> Putin's press secretary [[Dmitry Peskov]] stated on 12 September, "His momentary result cannot testify his political equipment and does not speak of him as of a serious politician".<ref name="navalnyisnopolitician">{{cite web|title=Песков отказал Навальному в звании "серьезного политика": Политика: Россия|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2013/09/12/peskov/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105215314/http://lenta.ru/news/2013/09/12/peskov/|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Lenta.ru}}</ref>

When referring to Navalny, Putin never actually pronounced his name in public, referring to him as a "mister" or the like;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/sep/03/this-gentleman-alexei-navalny-the-name-putin-dares-not-speak |title='This gentleman': Alexei Navalny, the name Putin dares not speak |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 September 2020 |access-date=15 October 2023}}</ref><ref name="navalnyisnopolitician"/> [[Julia Ioffe]] took it for a sign of weakness before the opposition politician,<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Ioffe |first=Julia |date=18 July 2013 |title=Aleksei Navalny Trial: Blogger Gets Five Years in Jail |magazine=[[The New Republic]] |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/113929/aleksei-navalny-trial-blogger-gets-five-years-jail#|url-status=live |access-date=27 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225170011/https://newrepublic.com/article/113929/aleksei-navalny-trial-blogger-gets-five-years-jail |archive-date=25 December 2015}}</ref> and Peskov later stated Putin never pronounced his name in order not to "give [Navalny] a part of his popularity".<ref>{{cite web |title=Песков: Путин не произносит имени Навального, чтобы не делать его популярнее |url=http://www.mk.ru/politics/russia/news/2013/09/30/923229-peskov-putin-ne-proiznosit-imeni-navalnogo-chtobyi-ne-delat-ego-populyarnee.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/http://www.mk.ru/politics/russia/news/2013/09/30/923229-peskov-putin-ne-proiznosit-imeni-navalnogo-chtobyi-ne-delat-ego-populyarnee.html |archive-date=31 January 2016 |access-date=27 December 2015 |website=Mk.ru |date=30 September 2013}}</ref> In July 2015, [[Bloomberg Businessweek|Bloomberg]]'s sources "familiar with the matter" declared there was an informal prohibition from the Kremlin for senior Russian officials from mentioning Navalny's name.<ref>{{cite news |last=Meyer|first=Henry |date=23 July 2015 |title=Murder, Poisoning, Raids: It's Election Season in Russia |publisher=Bloomberg News |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-23/murder-poisoning-police-raids-it-s-election-season-in-russia |url-status=live |access-date=5 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321185005/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-23/murder-poisoning-police-raids-it-s-election-season-in-russia |archive-date=21 March 2017 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> Peskov rejected the assumption there is such a ban; however, in doing so, he did not mention Navalny's name either.<ref>{{cite web |title=Песков опроверг запрет на упоминание имени Навального, не произнеся имени оппозиционера |url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/newsline/top/politics/news/2015/07/27/602285-peskov-oproverg-zapret-na-upominanie-imeni-navalnogo-ne-proiznesya-imeni-oppozitsionera |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228142441/http://www.vedomosti.ru/newsline/top/politics/news/2015/07/27/602285-peskov-oproverg-zapret-na-upominanie-imeni-navalnogo-ne-proiznesya-imeni-oppozitsionera |archive-date=28 February 2017 |access-date=4 April 2017 |publisher=[[Vedomosti]]}}</ref>

===Ratings===
[[File:Rally-concert in support of Alexey Navalny 2013-09-06 4708.jpg|thumb|Rally concert in support of Navalny, 6 September 2013]]
In a 2013 [[Levada Center]] poll, Navalny's recognition among the Russian population stood at 37%.<ref>{{cite web |last=Volkov|first=Dennis |date=5 April 2013 |title=Analysis of Navalny's Ratings |url=http://www.levada.ru/05-04-2013/analiz-reitinga-navalnogo-kommentarii-sotsiologa |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413233953/http://www.levada.ru/05-04-2013/analiz-reitinga-navalnogo-kommentarii-sotsiologa |archive-date=13 April 2013 |access-date=12 April 2013 |website=Levada Center}}</ref> Out of those who were able to recognise Navalny, 14% would either "definitely" or "probably" support his presidential run.<ref name="Bloomberg">{{cite news|last=Kravchenko|first=Stepan|date=5 April 2013|title=Putin, Allies Threatened With Jail as Navalny to Seek Presidency|publisher=Bloomberg News|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-05/putin-allies-threatened-with-jail-as-navalny-to-seek-presidency.html|url-status=live|access-date=12 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720020647/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-05/putin-allies-threatened-with-jail-as-navalny-to-seek-presidency.html|archive-date=20 July 2013|url-access=subscription}}</ref>

The Levada Center also conducted another survey, which was released on 6 April 2017, showing Navalny's recognition among the Russian population at 55%.<ref name="Protests on March 26 and Navalny">{{Cite web |date=6 April 2017 |title=Protests on March 26 and Navalny |url=http://www.levada.ru/2017/04/06/aktsii-protesta-26-marta-i-navalnyj/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604082325/http://www.levada.ru/2017/04/06/aktsii-protesta-26-marta-i-navalnyj/ |archive-date=4 June 2017 |access-date=6 June 2017 |website=Levada Center}}</ref> Out of those who recognised Navalny, 4% would "definitely" vote for him and 14% would "probably" vote for him in the presidential election.<ref name="Protests on March 26 and Navalny" /> In another poll carried out by the same pollster in August 2020, 4% of respondents said that they trusted Navalny the most (out of a list of politicians), an increase from 2% in the previous month.<ref>{{Cite web |date=3 September 2020 |title=ДОВЕРИЕ ПОЛИТИКАМ И ПРЕЗИДЕНТСКОЕ ГОЛОСОВАНИЕ |url=https://www.levada.ru/2020/09/03/doverie-politikam-i-prezidentskoe-golosovanie/ |website=levada.ru}}</ref>

According to polls conducted by the [[Levada Center]] in September 2020, 20% of Russians approved of Navalny's activities, 50% disapproved, and 18% had never heard of him.<ref name="not poisioned">{{cite web|date=2 October 2020|title=More than half of Russians do not believe Alexey Navalny was poisoned, Levada Center poll says|url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2020/10/02/more-than-half-of-russians-do-not-believe-alexey-navalny-was-poisoned-levada-center-poll-says|access-date=19 October 2020|website=Meduza}}</ref> Out of those who were able to recognise Navalny, 10% said that they have "respect" for him, 8% had sympathy and 15% "could not say anything bad" about him. 31% were "neutral" towards him, 14% "could not say anything good" about him and 10% disliked him.<ref>{{cite web|date=2 October 2020|title=Алексей Навальный: отношение и отравление|trans-title=Alexei Navalny: attitude and poisoning |url=https://www.levada.ru/2020/10/02/aleksej-navalnyj-otnoshenie-i-otravlenie/|access-date=19 October 2020|website=Levada Center|language=ru}}</ref><ref name="not poisioned"/>

=== Criminal cases ===
During and after the Kirovles trial, a number of prominent people expressed support to Navalny and/or condemned the trial. The last Soviet leader [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] called it "proof that we do not have independent courts".<ref name="nyt-31-may">{{cite news|date=31 May 2015|title=Mr. Putin Tries to Crush Another Rival|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/19/opinion/mr-putin-tries-to-crush-another-rival.html|url-status=live|access-date=31 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522205741/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/19/opinion/mr-putin-tries-to-crush-another-rival.html|archive-date=22 May 2015|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Former [[Ministry of Finance (Russia)|Minister of Finance]]<!-- and close Putin ally--> [[Alexei Kudrin]] stated that it was "looking less like a punishment than an attempt to isolate him from social life and the electoral process".<ref name="wsj-19-jul">{{cite news|date=19 July 2013|title=Reaction to Russia's Jailing of Alexei Navalny|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2013/07/18/reaction-to-russias-jailing-of-alexei-navalny/|url-status=live|access-date=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720052818/http://blogs.wsj.com/emergingeurope/2013/07/18/reaction-to-russias-jailing-of-alexei-navalny/|archive-date=20 July 2013}}</ref> It was also criticised by novelist [[Boris Akunin]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Herszenhorn|first=David M.|date=18 July 2013 |title=Russian Court Convicts Opposition Leader|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/19/world/europe/russian-court-convicts-opposition-leader-aleksei-navalny.html|url-status=live|access-date=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204205458/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/19/world/europe/russian-court-convicts-opposition-leader-aleksei-navalny.html|archive-date=4 February 2017|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and jailed [[Russian oligarch]] [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]], who called it similar to the treatment of political opponents during the Soviet era.<ref name="wsj-19-jul"/>

[[Vladimir Zhirinovsky]], leader of the nationalist [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia|LDPR]], called the verdict "a direct warning to our '[[fifth column]]'", and added, "This will be the fate of everyone who is connected with the West and works against Russia".<ref name="wsj-19-jul"/> A variety of state officials condemned the verdict. [[United States Department of State]] Deputy Spokesperson [[Marie Harf]] stated that the United States was "very disappointed by the conviction and sentencing of opposition leader Aleksey Navalniy".<ref>{{cite web|date=18 July 2013|title=On the Conviction and Sentencing of Alexey Navalniy and Pyotr Ofitserov|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2013/07/212143.htm|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822185746/https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2013/07/212143.htm|archive-date=22 August 2020|access-date=18 July 2013|publisher=U.S. State Department}}</ref> <!--The U.S. Ambassador to Russia, [[Michael McFaul]], followed up by stating that the trial had "apparent political motivations".<ref name="wsj-19-jul"/>--> The spokesperson for [[European Union]] High Representative [[Catherine Ashton]] said that the outcome of the trial "raises serious questions as to the state of the rule of law in Russia".<ref name="wsj-19-jul"/><ref>{{cite web|date=18 July 2013|title=Statement by the Spokesperson of High Representative Catherine Ashton on the sentencing of Alexey Navalny and Pyotr Ofitserov|url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/uedocs/cms_Data/docs/pressdata/EN/foraff/138137.pdf|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105014544/http://www.consilium.europa.eu/uedocs/cms_Data/docs/pressdata/EN/foraff/138137.pdf|archive-date=5 November 2013|access-date=18 July 2013|publisher=Council of the European Union}}</ref> Andreas Schockenhoff, Germany's Commissioner for German-Russian Coordination, stated, "For us, it's further proof of authoritarian policy in Russia, which doesn't allow diversity and pluralism".<ref>{{cite news|title=Germany criticises verdict against Navalny|date=19 July 2013|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=http://www.dw.de/germany-criticizes-verdict-against-navalny/a-16961300|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231234400/http://www.dw.de/germany-criticizes-verdict-against-navalny/a-16961300|archive-date=31 December 2014}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' commented in response to the verdict that "President Vladimir Putin of Russia actually seems weak and insecure".<ref name="nyt-31-may"/>

The verdict in the case of Yves Rocher caused similar reactions. According to Alexei Venediktov, the verdict was "unfair", Oleg Navalny was taken "hostage", while Alexei was not jailed to avoid "furious reaction" from Putin, which was caused by the change of measure of restraint after the Kirovles trial.<ref>{{cite news|title=Новости NEWSru.com :: Венедиктов объяснил смысл вердикта братьям Навальным: Олега сделали заложником Алексея|publisher=Newsru.com|url=http://www.newsru.com/arch/russia/30dec2014/zalozhnik.html|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105183759/http://www.newsru.com/arch/russia/30dec2014/zalozhnik.html|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> A number of deputies appointed by United Russia and LDPR found the verdict too mild.<ref>{{cite news|title=Реакция на приговор братьям Навальным|publisher=TASS|url=http://tass.ru/politika/1679903|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105171223/http://tass.ru/politika/1679903|archive-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> Experts interviewed by the [[BBC Russian Service]] expressed reactions close to the political positions their organisations generally stand on.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vendik|first=Yuri|date=30 December 2014|title=Олег Навальный приговорён к 3,5 годам по делу "Ив Роше"|language=ru|trans-title=Oleg Navalny sentenced to 3.5 years in the Yves Rocher case|publisher=BBC Russian Service|url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2014/12/141230_navalny_yves_rocher_sentence|url-status=live|access-date=30 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102074718/http://www.bbc.com/russian/russia/2014/12/141230_navalny_yves_rocher_sentence|archive-date=2 January 2015}}</ref> The spokesperson for EU foreign policy chief [[Federica Mogherini]] stated the same day that the sentence was likely to be politically motivated.<ref name="alexander">{{cite news|last=Alexander|first=Harriet|date=30 December 2014|title=Alexei Navalny breaks his house arrest to attend protest against his sentence|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/russia/11317813/Alexei-Navalny-breaks-his-house-arrest-to-attend-protest-against-his-sentence.html|url-status=live|access-date=30 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231113858/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/russia/11317813/Alexei-Navalny-breaks-his-house-arrest-to-attend-protest-against-his-sentence.html|archive-date=31 December 2014}}</ref><!-- Navalny made a statement, "The government is not just trying to jail its political opponents ... this time, they are destroying and torturing the families of the people who oppose them."<ref name=vasilyeva2014/>-->

Public opinion of Navalny in Russia varied over time. According to Levada Center, 20% of people thought the Kirovles case had been caused by an actual violation of law, while 54% agreed the rationale beyond the case was his [[anti-corruption]] activity in May 2011. In May 2013, the shares of people who held these opinions were 28% and 47%, respectively. In September 2013, the shares were 35% and 45%. The organisation suggested this had been caused by corresponding coverage in media.<ref>{{cite web|date=19 June 2014|title=Российский Медиа-ландшафт: Телевидение, Пресса, Интернетt|trans-title=Russian Media Landscape: Television, Press, Internet|url=http://www.levada.ru/sites/default/files/levadareportmedia.pdf|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020110941/http://www.levada.ru/sites/default/files/levadareportmedia.pdf|archive-date=20 October 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Levada.ru|language=ru}}</ref> By September 2014, the percentages had undergone further changes, and equaled 37% and 38%.<ref name="levada1">{{cite press release|date=7 November 2014|title=Навальный, "Болотное дело", Стрелков: знание и отношение|trans-title=Navalny, Bolotnoe delo, Strelkov: knowledge and attitude|url=http://www.levada.ru/07-11-2014/navalnyi-bolotnoe-delo-strelkov-znanie-i-otnoshenie|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912082543/http://www.levada.ru/07-11-2014/navalnyi-bolotnoe-delo-strelkov-znanie-i-otnoshenie|archive-date=12 September 2015|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Levada Center}}</ref> The center also stated the share of those who found the result of another criminal case against him was unfair and Navalny was not guilty dropped from 13% in July 2013 to 5% in January 2015, and the number of those who found the verdict was too tough also fell from 17% to 9%. The share of those who found the verdict to be either fair or too mild was 26% in July 2013, and has exceeded 35% since September 2013.<ref name="levada1"/>

== Political positions ==
[[File:Sun in the flags of protesters (50096710531).jpg|thumb|Navalny takes part in a march in memory of [[Assassination of Boris Nemtsov|assassinated]] opposition politician [[Boris Nemtsov]] in Moscow, 29 February 2020]]

=== Corruption ===
[[File:Edinaya Rossiya poster v2.svg|thumb|A poster that won the Navalny contest entitled [[United Russia]], a "[[party of crooks and thieves]]", 2011]]
In February 2011, in an interview with the radio station ''finam.fm'', Navalny called the main Russian party, [[United Russia]], a "[[party of crooks and thieves]]".<ref name="G105" /> In May 2011, the Russian government began a criminal investigation into Navalny, widely described in media as "revenge", and by Navalny himself as "a fabrication by the security services".<ref name="G105">{{cite news|last=Parfitt|first=Tom|date=10 May 2011|title=Russian blogger Alexei Navalny faces criminal investigation|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/may/10/russian-blogger-alexei-navalny|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910013651/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/may/10/russian-blogger-alexei-navalny|archive-date=10 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Belton|first=Catherine|date=10 May 2011|title=Russia Targets Anti-Graft Blogger|newspaper=Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/265120c6-7b3a-11e0-9b06-00144feabdc0|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814214542/https://www.ft.com/content/265120c6-7b3a-11e0-9b06-00144feabdc0|archive-date=14 August 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bratersky|first=Alexander|date=10 May 2011|title=Navalny Targeted in Fraud Inquiry|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2011/05/10/navalny-targeted-in-fraud-inquiry-a6871|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105091910/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/navalny-targeted-in-fraud-inquiry/436581.html|archive-date=5 January 2013}}</ref> Meanwhile, "party of crooks and thieves" became a popular slogan among the opposition.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sandford|first=Daniel|date=30 November 2011|title=Russians tire of corruption spectacle|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-15972326|url-status=live|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822185750/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-15972326|archive-date=22 August 2020}}</ref>

=== Non-Russian ethnic groups ===
His views about [[Russian nationalism]] evolved over time. In 2011, Navalny stated that he considered himself a "nationalist democrat".<ref>{{cite news|date=17 December 2011|title=The birth of Russian citizenry|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|url=https://www.economist.com/europe/2011/12/17/the-birth-of-russian-citizenry|url-status=live|access-date=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151217235217/http://www.economist.com/node/21541877|archive-date=17 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=31 March 2012|title=So where's the change in Russia? – Le Monde diplomatique – English edition|url=http://mondediplo.com/2012/04/02russia|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131235354/http://mondediplo.com/2012/04/02russia|archive-date=31 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|publisher=Mondediplo.com}}</ref> He previously participated in the "[[2006 Russian march|Russian march]]" from 2006, a parade uniting Russian nationalist groups of all stripes,<ref name="theAtlantic">{{cite magazine|last=Coalson|first=Robert|date=29 July 2013|title=Is Aleksei Navalny a Liberal or a Nationalist?|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/07/is-aleksei-navalny-a-liberal-or-a-nationalist/278186/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227125259/https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/07/is-aleksei-navalny-a-liberal-or-a-nationalist/278186/|archive-date=27 February 2021|magazine=[[The Atlantic]]}}</ref><ref name="russianMarch"/><ref>{{cite web|date=24 October 2011|title=В столице отрепетировали "Русский марш" / Регионы России / Независимая газета|url=http://www.ng.ru/regions/2011-10-24/1_rus_marsh.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026151901/http://www.ng.ru/regions/2011-10-24/1_rus_marsh.html|archive-date=26 October 2011|access-date=27 December 2015|website=Ng.ru}}</ref> and was one of the co-organisers of the 2011 march.<ref>{{cite web|date=10 January 2020|title="I Assert that Putin Was Behind the Crime"|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/world/alexei-navalny-on-his-poisoning-i-assert-that-putin-was-behind-the-crime-a-ae5923d5-20f3-4117-80bd-39a99b5b86f4|website=spiegel.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=21 October 2011|title=Алексей Навальный выходит на "Русский марш"|url=https://www.svoboda.org/a/24367290.html|work=Radio Svoboda}}</ref><ref name="russianMarch">{{cite news|date=6 November 2011|title=Russian March Resists Navalny|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2011/11/06/russian-march-resists-navalny-a10629|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117224422/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2011/11/06/russian-march-resists-navalny-a10629|archive-date=17 January 2021|newspaper=The Moscow Times.com}}</ref> Navalny also called for ending federal subsidies to the "corrupt" and "ineffective" governments of Chechnya and other republics part of the [[North Caucasus]].<ref name="theAtlantic" /><ref>{{cite news|date=8 October 2011|title=Russian Anger Grows Over Chechnya Subsidies|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/09/world/europe/chechnyas-costs-stir-anger-as-russia-approaches-elections.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009055549/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/09/world/europe/chechnyas-costs-stir-anger-as-russia-approaches-elections.html |archive-date=9 October 2011 |url-status=live|newspaper=The New York Times|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/russia-navalny-nationalist-fears/25059277.html|title=Russia's Aleksei Navalny: Hope Of The Nation – Or The Nationalists?|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130810073406/http://www.rferl.org/content/russia-navalny-nationalist-fears/25059277.html|archive-date=10 August 2013|author=Robert Coalson|publisher=RFE/RL|date=28 July 2013}}</ref>

In 2007, Navalny co-founded the [[National Russian Liberation Movement]], known as ''NAROD'' (The People), which sets immigration policy as a priority.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Shuster|first=Simon|date=29 December 2011|title=Russia Rising: The Blogger Who Is Putin's Greatest Challenger|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2103203-2,00.html|magazine=Time|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210126202730/http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2103203-2,00.html|archive-date=26 January 2021}}</ref> The movement allied itself with two nationalist groups, the [[Movement Against Illegal Immigration]] and [[Great Russia (political party)|Great Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|date=20 August 2020|title=5 things to know about Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/5-things-you-need-to-know-about-alexei-navalny/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210207110916/https://www.politico.eu/article/5-things-you-need-to-know-about-alexei-navalny/|archive-date=7 February 2021|website=politico.eu}}</ref> In the same year, he released several anti-immigration videos,<ref>{{cite magazine|date=15 February 2021|title=The Evolution of Alexey Navalny's Nationalism|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/the-evolution-of-alexey-navalnys-nationalism|magazine=The New Yorker}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=29 April 2017|title=Alexei Navalny on Putin's Russia: 'All autocratic regimes come to an end'|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/29/alexei-navalny-on-putins-russia-all-autocratic-regimes-come-to-an-end|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210226115506/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/29/alexei-navalny-on-putins-russia-all-autocratic-regimes-come-to-an-end|archive-date=26 February 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=18 March 2018|title=Putin crafts spectacle for re-election landslide|url=https://cambridgeglobalist.org/?p=1227|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180401072527/https://cambridgeglobalist.org/?p=1227|archive-date=1 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=1 August 2017|title=The man who would beat Putin|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/alexei-navalny-the-man-who-would-beat-vladimir-putin-russia-election/|website=Politico|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210207034147/https://www.politico.eu/article/alexei-navalny-the-man-who-would-beat-vladimir-putin-russia-election/|archive-date=7 February 2021}}</ref> including one where he advocated the deportation of migrants.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://time.com/6140102/alexei-navalny-russia-profile/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |title=The Man Putin Fears |date=19 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220119125433/https://time.com/6140102/alexei-navalny-russia-profile/ |archive-date=19 January 2022 |quote=His rhetoric turned many people off. Russian liberals were alarmed by Navalny's early flirtation with the far right, including a pair of videos he released in 2007, one calling for the deportation of migrants}}</ref> In one of the videos, in which he advocates for gun rights, he compares people from North Caucasus, home to many Muslims, to cockroaches and mimics shooting one who attempts to "attack" him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Amnesty strips Navalny of 'prisoner of conscience' status |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/2/24/amnesty-strips-navalny-of-prisoner-of-conscience-status |website=Al Jazeera |access-date=20 March 2024 |language=en |date=24 February 2021|quote=Navalny filmed a pro-gun rights video in which he compared people from the North Caucasus, home to many Muslims, as “cockroaches” and then pretended to shoot one with a pistol}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Antonova |first1=Natalia |title=Dissidents Aren't Saints |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2021/03/05/alexei-navalny-amnesty-prisoner-conscience-dissidents-saints/ |website=Foreign Policy |access-date=20 March 2024 |date=5 March 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Siddique |first1=Haroon |title=Muslim employee sues Amnesty over sacking after Alexei Navalny objections |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/feb/08/amnesty-international-employee-sacked-alexei-navalny |website=The Guardian |access-date=20 March 2024 |date=8 February 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barry |first1=Ellen |title=Rousing Russia With a Phrase |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/10/world/europe/the-saturday-profile-blogger-aleksei-navalny-rouses-russia.html |agency=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 December 2011 |quote=}}</ref><ref name="aljazeera2021">{{cite web |last1=Mirovalev |first1=Mansur |title=Has Alexey Navalny moved on from his nationalist past? |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/2/25/navalny-has-the-kremlin-foe-moved-on-from-his-nationalist-past |website=Al Jazeera |access-date=18 February 2024}}</ref> According to [[Leonid Volkov (politician)|Leonid Volkov]], Navalny later regretted making the 2007 video.<ref name="newyorker-gessen">{{cite magazine |last1=Gessen |first1=Masha |title=The Evolution of Alexey Navalny's Nationalism |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/our-columnists/the-evolution-of-alexey-navalnys-nationalism |magazine=The New Yorker |date=15 February 2021}}</ref>

In 2013, after [[2013 Biryulyovo riots|ethnic riots in a Moscow district]] took place, which were sparked by a murder committed by a migrant, Navalny sympathised with the anti-immigration movement and commented that ethnic tensions and crimes are inevitable because of failing immigration policies by the state.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Guillory|first=Sean|date=1 November 2013|title=How Russian Nationalism Fuels Race Riots|language=en|magazine=The Nation|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/how-russian-nationalism-fuels-race-riots/|access-date=22 December 2020|issn=0027-8378|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Shuster|first=Simon|date=14 October 2013|title=Russia Responds to Anti-Migrant Riots by Arresting Migrants|url=https://world.time.com/2013/10/14/russia-responds-to-anti-migrant-riots-by-arresting-migrants/|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> However, he later said that "The basis of my approach is that you have to communicate with nationalists and educate them... I think it's very important to explain to them that the problem of illegal immigration is not solved by beating up migrants but by other, democratic means".<ref name="rferl-25-feb">{{cite news|date=25 February 2021|title=Navalny's Failure To Renounce His Nationalist Past May Be Straining His Support|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/navalny-failure-to-renounce-nationalist-past-support/31122014.html|publisher=RFE/RL}}</ref>

Since 2016, Navalny deemphasized his past statements on immigration.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alexey Navalny's views on migrants run counter to his pro-democracy discourse |url=https://globalvoices.org/2021/02/09/alexey-navalnys-views-on-migrants-run-counter-to-his-pro-democracy-discourse/ |website=globalvoices.org |date=9 February 2021 |publisher=Global Voices |access-date=16 February 2024}}</ref>

In June 2020, he spoke out in support of the [[Black Lives Matter]] protests against racism.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rutland|first1=Peter|last2=Kazantsev|first2=Andrei|date=13 July 2020|title=Do Black Lives Matter in Russia?|url=https://www.russiamatters.org/analysis/do-black-lives-matter-russia|access-date=25 January 2022|website=Russia Matters.org|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Alexandrov|first=Ivan|date=18 June 2020|title=Россия в зеркале Black Lives Matter|trans-title=Russia in the mirror of Black Lives Matter|url=https://russian.eurasianet.org/россия-в-зеркале-black-lives-matter|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201125030451/https://russian.eurasianet.org/россия-в-зеркале-black-lives-matter|archive-date=25 November 2020|access-date=22 August 2020|website=[[eurasianet.org]]|language=ru}}</ref>

=== Same-sex marriage ===
In 2017, [[Leonid Volkov (politician)|Leonid Volkov]], Navalny's chief of staff, said that Navalny's team supports the legalisation of [[Recognition of same-sex unions in Russia|same-sex marriage]].<ref>{{cite web|date=2 August 2017|title=Волков: команда Навального выступает за свободу слова и гей-браки|url=https://www.lrt.lt/ru/novosti/17/181792/volkov-komanda-naval-nogo-vystupaet-za-svobodu-slova-i-gei-braki|trans-title=Volkov: Navalny's team stands for freedom of speech and gay marriage|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200822185747/https://www.lrt.lt/ru/novosti/17/181792/volkov-komanda-naval-nogo-vystupaet-za-svobodu-slova-i-gei-braki|archive-date=22 August 2020|access-date=22 August 2020|website=lrt.lt}}</ref>

===Foreign policy===
His views on foreign policy evolved over time.<ref name="newyorker-gessen"/> He had initially supported the [[Russo-Georgian War]] in 2008,<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Hess |first1=Maximillian |last2=Pigman |first2=Lincoln |date=21 May 2018 |title=For Navalny, Foreign and Domestic Policy Are One |url=https://carnegiemoscow.org/commentary/76403 |access-date=18 June 2022 |website=[[Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]]}}</ref> having asked the Russian army to strike the [[General Staff of the Defence Forces of Georgia|Georgian General Staff]], called [[Georgians]] "rodents"<ref name="jam-news">{{cite news|url=https://jam-news.net/navalnys-letter-on-saakashvili/|title=Navalny apologies for insulting Georgians in 2008|date=14 April 2023|work=JAMnews}}</ref> and requesting that all Georgian citizens be expelled from Russia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tpi.it/opinioni/alexey-navalny-chi-e-davvero-caucaso-crimea-trasformismo-20210128734493/|title=Chi è davvero Navalny (di Pietro Guastamacchia)|first=Pietro|last=Guastamacchia|newspaper=The Post Internazionale|date=28 January 2021|language=it}}</ref> He later apologized for insulting the Georgians, while stating that his principled position remained unchanged.<ref name="jam-news" /> Navalny also argued in 2008 and again in 2017 that Russia should recognize the independence of [[Moldova]]'s breakaway region of [[Transnistria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://noi.md/md/news_id/227322|title=Navalinîi: Transnistria, de facto, e independentă de Republica Moldova|work=Noi|date=7 June 2017|language=ro}}</ref>

====Ukraine====
In early 2012, Navalny said on Ukrainian TV that "Ukraine and Belarus are the natural allies of Russia and the Russian foreign policy should be maximally directed at integration with Ukraine and Belarus… In fact, we are one nation". During the same broadcast Navalny said that he is not against Ukraine's independence or national identity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://telegraf.by/en/2012/02/navalnii-integraciya-s-belarusyu-glavnaya-zadacha-rossii|title=Navalny: Integration with Belarus – Main Task for Russia|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928133450/http://telegraf.by/en/2012/02/navalnii-integraciya-s-belarusyu-glavnaya-zadacha-rossii|archive-date=28 September 2013|website=Telegraf.by|date=13 February 2012}}</ref><ref name="day"/> He also claimed to see in Ukraine "a conspiracy to invade Ukraine with the aim of joining Russia is visible everywhere", and added "I will disappoint you - there are not four people sitting in the [[Kremlin]] who decide to add Ukraine to Russia or not."<ref name="day"/>

In March 2014, after [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|Russia's annexation of Crimea]], Navalny urged further sanctions against officials and businessmen linked to Putin and proposed his own list of sanctions, saying that previous US and EU sanctions were "mocked".<ref>{{cite news|date=20 March 2014|title=Navalny Proposes Sanctions List to the West|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2014/03/20/navalny-proposes-sanctions-list-to-the-west-a33162}}</ref> In October 2014, Navalny suggested that the fate of Crimea should be resolved by holding a new and fair referendum.<ref name="tmt-crimea"/> Navalny also said that Putin's government should stop "sponsoring the war" [[War in Donbas (2014–2022)|in Donbas]].<ref name="tmt-crimea">{{cite news|date=16 October 2014|title=Navalny Wouldn't Return Crimea, Considers Immigration Bigger Issue Than Ukraine|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2014/10/16/navalny-wouldnt-return-crimea-considers-immigration-bigger-issue-than-ukraine-a40477}}</ref> Navalny has strongly criticised Vladimir Putin's policies in Ukraine: "Putin likes to speak about the '[[Russian world]]' but he is actually making it smaller. In Belarus, they sing [[Putin khuylo!|anti-Putin song]]s at football stadiums; [[Russia–Ukraine relations|in Ukraine]] they simply hate us. In Ukraine now, there are no politicians who do not have extreme [[Anti-Russian sentiment|anti-Russian]] positions. Being anti-Russian is the key to success now in Ukraine, and that is our fault".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/17/putin-is-destroying-russia-why-base-his-regime-on-corruption-asks-navalny|title='Putin is destroying Russia. Why base his regime on corruption?' asks Navalny|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202000017/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/17/putin-is-destroying-russia-why-base-his-regime-on-corruption-asks-navalny|last=Walker|first=Shaun|archive-date=2 December 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|date=17 October 2014}}</ref>

In 2018, after the establishment of the autonomous [[Orthodox Church of Ukraine]], an event labelled as the [[History of Christianity in Ukraine#Rule of the Empires|ending of more than three centuries]] of Russian spiritual and temporal control of the dominant faith in Ukraine, Navalny tweeted: "What took centuries to create has been destroyed by Putin and his idiots in four years ... Putin is the enemy of the Russian World."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/ukrainealert/russias-navalny-protests-provoke-mixed-emotions-in-ukraine/|title=Russia's Navalny protests provoke mixed emotions in Ukraine|publisher=[[Atlantic Council]]|date=26 January 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/ukrainian-orthodox-church-marks-one-year-of-independence-from-moscow/30393633.html|title=Prayers Answered? Ukrainian Orthodox Church Marks One Year Of Independence From Moscow|publisher=RFE/RL|date=23 January 2020}}</ref>

In February 2022, Navalny compared the recognition of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] and the [[Luhansk People's Republic]] by Russia to when Soviet leaders [[Soviet–Afghan War|deployed troops]] to Afghanistan in 1979, describing both events as a distraction to the population from real issues. He said that he believed that while Putin will not allow Ukraine to develop, Russia will pay the same price, and that Putin needed to be removed to save Russia.<ref>{{cite news|title="И тем, и этим нужно одно: отвлечение внимания от реальных проблем". Навальный сравнил признание ДНР и ЛНР с вводом войск в Афганистан|trans-title="Both of them need one thing: distraction from the real problems." Navalny compared the recognition of the DPR and LPR with the introduction of troops into Afghanistan|url=https://meduza.io/news/2022/02/22/i-tem-i-etim-nuzhno-odno-otvlechenie-vnimaniya-ot-realnyh-problem-navalnyy-sravnil-priznanie-dnr-i-lnr-s-vvodom-voysk-v-afganistan|access-date=23 February 2022|website=Meduza|date=22 February 2022|language=ru}}</ref>

On 2 March 2022, Navalny urged Russian citizens to stage daily [[Protests against the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|protests]] against [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|Russia's invasion of Ukraine]], saying Russia should not be a "nation of frightened people" and "cowards who pretend not to notice the aggressive war" launched by "our insane tsar".<ref>{{cite news|date=2 March 2022|title=«Все имеет цену, и сейчас, весной 2022 года, эту цену должны платить мы». Навальный призвал к ежедневным акциям против войны|trans-title="Everything has a price, and now, in the spring of 2022, we must pay this price." Navalny called for daily actions against the war.|language=ru|website=Meduza|url=https://meduza.io/news/2022/03/02/vse-imeet-tsenu-i-seychas-vesnoy-2022-goda-etu-tsenu-dolzhny-platit-my-navalnyy-prizval-k-ezhednevnym-antivoennym-aktsiyam}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2 March 2022|title=Navalny Calls on Russians to Take to the Streets to 'Stop the War'|language=en|newspaper=The Moscow Times|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/03/02/navalny-calls-on-russians-to-take-to-the-streets-to-stop-the-war-a76713}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2 March 2022|title=Russia's Navalny calls Putin insane and urges anti-war protests|language=en|publisher=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/kremlin-critic-navalny-calls-daily-anti-war-protests-russia-2022-03-02/}}</ref>

{{Cquote|If, to prevent war, we need to fill up the jails and police vans, we will fill up the jails and police vans. Everything has a price and now, in the spring of 2022, we should pay that price.
| author = Alexei Navalny
}}

On 5 April 2022, referring to war crimes that took place in Ukraine, Navalny said the "monstrosity of lies" in the [[Mass media in Russia|Russian state media]] "is unimaginable. And, unfortunately, so is its persuasiveness for those who have no access to alternative information."<ref name="state-media">{{cite news |title=Channelling Goebbels: The obscenity of Russian state TV news, as it conceals war crimes for Putin |url=https://inews.co.uk/opinion/channelling-goebbels-the-obscenity-of-russian-state-tv-news-as-it-conceals-war-crimes-for-putin-1559603?ico=best_of_opinion |work=[[i (British newspaper)|inews.co.uk.]] |date=6 April 2022}}</ref> He tweeted that "warmongers" among Russian state media personalities "should be treated as war criminals. From the editors-in-chief to the talk show hosts to the news editors, [they] should be sanctioned now and tried someday."<ref>{{cite news |title=Navalny Calls for Sanctions Against Russian State Media 'Warmongers' |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/04/06/navalny-calls-for-sanctions-against-russian-state-media-warmongers-a77237 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220406111407/https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2022/04/06/navalny-calls-for-sanctions-against-russian-state-media-warmongers-a77237 |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 April 2022 |work=The Moscow Times |date=6 March 2022}}</ref> The next month, Navalny called the invasion a "stupid war" based on lies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jailed Kremlin foe Navalny lambasts Putin's 'stupid war' in Ukraine |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/jailed-kremlin-foe-navalny-lambasts-putins-stupid-war-ukraine-2022-05-24/ |work=Reuters |date=24 May 2022}}</ref>

Navalny criticised the [[2022 Russian mobilization|2022 Russian mobilisation]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Putin orders partial mobilization of Russian reservists and hints using nuclear weapons still possible |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/putin-orders-partial-mobilization-of-russian-reservists-and-hints-using-nuclear-weapons-still-possible/ |work=CBS News |date=21 September 2022}}</ref> During a court hearing on 21 September, he said: "I don't understand one thing. The army has a million people, Rosgvardia has 350,000 people, the Interior Ministry has another million and a half or two million people, and the Federal Penitentiary Service is full of people. Why are they drafting civilians?"<ref>{{cite news |title='There will be five million draft dodgers running around the country.' Navalny on mobilization. |url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2022/09/21/there-will-be-five-million-draft-dodgers-running-around-the-country-navalny-on-mobilization |work=[[Meduza]] |date=21 September 2022}}</ref> In another court hearing two days later, Navalny said: "You won't shut my mouth with your ShIZO [punishment cell]. This is a crime against my country. I don't relate to it, and I won't be silent. I hope that everyone else who hears me will not be silent about it. Because what's happening now is much more terrible than any 12 or 112 days in a ShIZO [punishment cell]. This is a historic crime, this is involving hundreds of thousands of people in this crime".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spektr.press/vy-svoim-shizo-mne-rot-ne-zatknete-eto-prestuplenie-protiv-moej-strany-navalnyj-vystupil-na-sude/|title="Вы своим ШИЗО мне рот не заткнете. Это преступление против моей страны" — Навальный выступил на суде|website=[[spektr.press]]|date=23 September 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/news-63006176|title=Навального в пятый раз отправили в штрафной изолятор. На этот раз после речи о мобилизации|website=BBC News Russian|date=23 September 2022}}</ref>

On 20 February 2023, he condemned Putin for "destroying" Russia's own future "just to make our country look bigger on the map" and said that Russia must end its [[Russian-occupied territories of Ukraine|occupation of Ukraine]] and recognise Ukraine's borders as they were established in 1991 after the collapse of the Soviet Union. Navalny also said Russia would have to pay post-war [[Reparations from Russia after the Russo-Ukrainian War|reparations to Ukraine]] and called for an international investigation into [[War crimes in the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|war crimes]], saying: "Tens of thousands of innocent Ukrainians have been murdered and pain and suffering have befallen millions more."<ref>{{cite news |title=Navalny: Putin's war has pushed Russia to 'rock bottom' |last=Cordell |first=Jake |url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ukraine/navalny-putins-war-has-pushed-russia-to-rock-bottom-1435883.html |work=BreakingNews.ie |date=20 February 2023}}</ref>

On 1 February 2024, Navalny and his allies called on supporters to protest President Vladimir Putin and the invasion of Ukraine during the third day of the [[2024 Russian presidential election]] by all going to vote against Putin at the same time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Navalny Calls for Election Day Protest Against Putin, Ukraine Invasion |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2024/02/01/navalny-calls-for-election-day-protest-against-putin-ukraine-invasion-a83946 |work=[[The Moscow Times]] |date=1 February 2024}}</ref>

====Syria====
In 2016, Navalny spoke against the Russian intervention in the [[Syrian civil war]], believing that there are internal problems in Russia that need to be dealt with rather than to get involved in foreign wars.<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Leonid Bershidsky]]|date=14 December 2016|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2016-12-14/a-populist-challenge-to-putin|title=A Populist Challenge to Putin|publisher=Bloomberg News|url-access=subscription}}</ref> He also said Russia should not "try to save [[Bashar al-Assad|Assad]], who represents a military junta", and said entering the war in the same side as the [[Shia Islamism|Shia Islamist]] Iran and [[Hezbollah]] stoked anger among Russia's predominantly [[Sunni Islam|Sunni Muslim]] community.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Sharipzhan |first=Merhat |date=22 December 2016 |title=Russian Presidential Hopeful Slams Kremlin On Syria, Ukraine |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-navalny-presidential-candidate-criticizes-syria-ukraine/28189546.html |access-date=19 February 2024 |work=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] |language=en}}</ref>

== Awards and honours ==
[[File:Vyhlídka Alexeje Navalného (Praha 2021) I.jpg|thumb|Scenic viewpoint of Alexei Navalny in [[Prague]], 2021]]
Navalny was named "Person of the Year 2009" by Russian business newspaper ''[[Vedomosti]]''<ref>{{cite news|date=30 December 2009|title=Персоны года – 2009: Частное лицо года|language=ru|trans-title=Person of the Year 2009: Individual of the Year|newspaper=[[Vedomosti]]|url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article/2009/12/30/222496|url-status=live|access-date=9 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100119002421/http://www.vedomosti.ru/newspaper/article/2009/12/30/222496|archive-date=19 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=30 December 2009|title=Персоны года – 2009: Частное лицо года|trans-title=Person of the Year 2009: Individual of the Year|url=https://www.banki.ru/news/bankpress/?id=1650513|access-date=22 November 2020|website=banki.ru}}</ref> and by stock exchange observer ''Stock in Focus''.<ref>{{cite web|date=22 December 2009|title=Советник кировского губернатора стал человеком года|trans-title=Kirov Governor's Advisor became the person of the year|url=https://www.newsler.ru/politics/2009/12/22/navalny|access-date=3 September 2021|website=Newsler.ru|language=ru}}</ref>

On 22 April 2010, Navalny was awarded the ''Finance'' magazine prize in the nomination "for protecting the rights of minority shareholders".<ref>{{Cite web|date=26 April 2010|title=Новости Банка|trans-title=Bank News|url=https://www.cfb.ru/about/news/news_7.html|access-date=6 September 2021|website=cfb.ru|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=26 April 2010|title=Репортаж с церемонии вручения ежегодной премии журнала "Финанс."|trans-title=Report from the annual awards ceremony of the "Finance."|url=https://finparty.ru/market_parties/15694/|access-date=6 September 2021|website=finparty.ru|language=ru|archive-date=6 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210906011321/https://finparty.ru/market_parties/15694/}}</ref>

In 2011, ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine named Navalny to the FP Top 100 Global Thinkers, along with [[Daniel Domscheit-Berg]] and [[Sami Ben Gharbia]] of Tunisia, for "shaping the new world of government transparency".<ref>{{Cite web |date=December 2011 |title=The FP Top 100 Global Thinkers |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/11/28/the_fp_top_100_global_thinkers?page=0,23#thinker24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103190534/http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/11/28/the_fp_top_100_global_thinkers?page=0,23#thinker24 |archive-date=3 November 2012 |access-date=28 November 2012 |website=Foreign Policy}}</ref> ''FP'' picked him again in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 November 2012 |title=The FP Top 100 Global Thinkers |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/11/26/the_fp_100_global_thinkers?page=0,33 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130221322/http://www.foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/11/26/the_fp_100_global_thinkers?page=0,33 |archive-date=30 November 2012 |access-date=28 November 2012 |website=Foreign Policy}}</ref> He was listed by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine in 2012 as one of the world's [[Time 100|100 most influential people]], the only Russian on the list.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Kasparov|first=Garry|date=18 April 2012|title=Alexei Navalny|magazine=Time|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2111975_2111976_2112167,00.html|access-date=31 July 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120914070247/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2111975_2111976_2112167,00.html|archive-date=14 September 2012}}</ref> In 2013, Navalny came in at No. 48 among "world thinkers" in an online poll by the UK magazine ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=April 2013|title=The results of Prospect's world thinkers poll|url=http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/world-thinkers-2013/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530012443/http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/world-thinkers-2013/|archive-date=30 May 2013|access-date=30 May 2013|magazine=[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]}}</ref>

In 2015, Alexei and Oleg Navalny were chosen to receive the "Prize of the Platform of European Memory and Conscience 2015". According to the platform's statement, "The Members of the Platform have voted this year for the Navalny brothers, in recognition of their personal courage, struggle and sacrifices for upholding fundamental democratic values and freedoms in the Russian Federation today. By the award of the Prize, the Platform wishes to express its respect and support to Mr. Oleg Navalny whom the Platform considers a political prisoner, and to Mr. Alexei Navalny for his efforts to expose corruption, defend political pluralism and opposition to the mounting authoritarian regime in the Russian Federation".<ref>{{cite web|date=2 May 2015|title=Alexei and Oleg Navalny to receive Prize of the Platform of European Memory and Conscience 2015 &#124; Platform of European Memory and Conscience|url=http://www.memoryandconscience.eu/2015/05/02/alexei-and-oleg-navalny-to-receive-prize-of-the-platform-of-european-memory-and-conscience-2015/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105070356/http://www.memoryandconscience.eu/2015/05/02/alexei-and-oleg-navalny-to-receive-prize-of-the-platform-of-european-memory-and-conscience-2015/|archive-date=5 January 2016|access-date=27 December 2015|website=MemoryandConscience.eu}}</ref>

In June 2017, Navalny was included in ''Time''{{'}}s list of the World's 25 Most Influential People on the Internet.<ref>{{cite magazine|date=26 June 2017|title=The 25 Most Influential People on the Internet|magazine=Time|url=https://time.com/4815217/most-influential-people-internet/|url-status=live|access-date=1 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518224033/http://time.com/4815217/most-influential-people-internet/|archive-date=18 May 2019}}</ref> In December 2017, he was named "Politician of the Year 2017" by ''Vedomosti''.<ref>{{cite news|date=28 December 2017|script-title=ru:Политик года – оппозиционер Алексей Навальный|trans-title=Politician of the Year – Oppositionist Alexei Navalny|url=https://www.vedomosti.ru/opinion/articles/2017/12/28/746765-politik-goda-aleksei-navalnii|access-date=4 March 2021|website=[[Vedomosti]]|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Karaulova|first=Olga |date=28 December 2017|script-title=ru:СМИ России: Навальный стал политиком года|language=ru|trans-title=Russian media: Navalny became the politician of the year|work=BBC Russian Service|url=https://www.bbc.com/russian/features-42500300|access-date=4 March 2021}}</ref>

He was named "Politician of the Year 2019" by readers of ''Vedomosti''.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ru:Спецпроект "Персона года 2019"|trans-title=Special project "Person of the Year 2019"|url=https://persona2019.vedomosti.ru/|access-date=23 February 2021|work=[[Vedomosti]]|language=ru|archive-date=26 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226223010/https://persona2019.vedomosti.ru/}}</ref>

Navalny was nominated for the [[2021 Nobel Peace Prize]] by multiple Norwegian members of parliament.<ref name="aftenposten">{{cite news|date=31 January 2021|title=Flere fredsprisforslag før fristen gikk ut|newspaper=[[Aftenposten]]|agency=[[Norwegian News Agency]]|url=https://www.aftenposten.no/norge/politikk/i/jBL23A/flere-fredsprisforslag-foer-fristen-gikk-ut}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=31 January 2021|title=Hektisk nomineringsaktivitet før fredsprisfrist|trans-title=Hectic nomination activity before peace prize deadline|work=[[Dagsavisen]]|url=https://www.dagsavisen.no/nyheter/verden/hektisk-nomineringsaktivitet-for-fredsprisfrist-1.1827991}}</ref> An Internet petition to the Nobel Committee in support of Navalny's candidacy was signed by over 38,000 people.<ref>{{cite news|date=27 January 2021|title=Alexander Litvinenko's widow wants man standing up to Putin to get Nobel Prize|url=https://metro.co.uk/2021/01/27/alexander-litvinenkos-widow-wants-nobel-prize-for-man-opposing-putin-13977044/|access-date=5 February 2021|newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|language=en}}</ref>

Following Navalny's imprisonment in February 2021, the Boris Nemtsov Foundation for Freedom awarded Navalny with the Boris Nemtsov Prize for Courage.<ref>{{cite web|date=27 February 2021|title=Boris Nemtsov Prize for Courage-2021 awarded to Alexei Navalny|url=https://nemtsovfund.org/en/2021/02/boris-nemtsov-prize-for-courage-2021-awarded-to-alexei-navalny|access-date=1 March 2021|website=nemtsovfund.org|language=en}}</ref> A scenic viewpoint of Alexei Navalny was also set in [[Prague]] in direct view from the Russian Embassy, near [[Boris Nemtsov Square, Prague|Boris Nemtsov Square]] in front of the Russian Embassy and the [[Anna Politkovskaya]] Promenade.<ref>{{cite web|last=Šafhauser|first=Roman|date=5 February 2021|title=Vyhlídka Alexeje Navalného, hlásá cedule v Praze. Název však není oficiální|trans-title=Alexei Navalny's scenic viewpoint, the plaque says in Prague. However, the name is not official|url=https://www.idnes.cz/praha/zpravy/vyhlidka-alexeje-navalneho-stromovka.A210205_140122_praha-zpravy_rsr|access-date=28 March 2021|website=iDNES.cz|language=cs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sojka|first=Libor|date=12 February 2021|title=Alexei Navalny scenic viewpoint, Stromovka park, Prague|url=http://www.apimages.com/metadata/Index/Alexei-Navalny-scenic-viewpoint-Stromovka-park-/b0a0b87f8c9b4f13bb43e987b0f94df0/278/0|access-date=28 March 2021|website=AP Images|publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>

On 8 June 2021, Navalny's daughter accepted the Moral Courage Award at the [[Geneva Summit for Human Rights and Democracy]] on behalf of her father. Navalny dedicated the prize to political prisoners.<ref>{{cite news|date=8 June 2021|title=Russia: Jailed Kremlin critic Navalny dedicates human rights award to political prisoners|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=https://www.dw.com/en/russia-jailed-kremlin-critic-navalny-dedicates-human-rights-award-to-political-prisoners/a-57818529|access-date=8 June 2021}}</ref> In September 2021, Navalny was included in ''Time''{{'}}s list of the 100 most influential people. This was his second appearance on the list, having previously been included in 2012.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Kasparov|first=Garry|date=18 April 2012|title=Alexei Navalny|magazine=Time|url=https://time.com/collection/100-most-influential-people-2021/6096084/alexei-navalny/|access-date=16 September 2021}}</ref>

[[File:Berlin demonstration after Navalny's murder asv2024-02-18 img01.jpg|thumb|Memorial after Navalny's death in front of the [[Embassy of Russia, Berlin]], Germany]]
In September 2021, he was awarded the [[Knight of Freedom Award]] conferred by the [[The Casimir Pulaski Foundation|Casimir Pulaski Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|date=30 September 2021|title=Alexey Navalny – 2021 Knight of Freedom awardee|url=https://pulaski.pl/en/alexey-navalny-2021-knight-of-freedom-awardee/|access-date=7 October 2021|website=Casimir Pulaski Foundation|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=30 September 2021|title=Alexey Navalny – 2021 Knight of Freedom awardee|url=https://warsawsecurityforum.org/alexey-navalny-2021-knight-of-freedom-awardee/|access-date=7 October 2021|website=Warsaw Security Forum|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="german"/>

In October 2021, he received the [[Sakharov Prize]], the [[European Parliament]]'s annual human rights prize.<ref name="eu">{{cite news|last1=Emmott|first1=Robin|title=Kremlin critic Navalny wins EU rights prize for his "immense bravery"|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/russias-navalny-wins-eu-rights-prize-2021-10-20/|access-date=20 October 2021|publisher=Reuters|date=20 October 2021}}</ref> [[David Sassoli]], the [[President of the European Parliament]], announced that the award was to recognise that Navalny "has fought tirelessly against the corruption of Vladimir Putin's regime. This cost him his liberty and nearly his life".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Suliman|first1=Adela|title=Russia's Navalny awarded prestigious European human rights Sakharov Prize|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2021/10/20/navalny-sakharov-russia-europe/|access-date=20 October 2021|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=20 October 2021}}</ref>

Later that same year, he also received a German prize for his efforts in sustaining freedom of expression – the M100 Media Award.<ref>{{cite news|date=7 October 2021|title=German Freedom of Expression Prize Goes to Navalny|newspaper=The Moscow Times|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2021/10/07/german-freedom-of-expression-prize-goes-to-navalny-a75236|access-date=7 October 2021}}</ref><ref name="german">{{cite news|date=7 October 2021|title=Навальный стал лауреатом немецкой премии за вклад в свободу СМИ|trans-title=Navalny is the recipient of the German Media Freedom Award|url=https://www.golosameriki.com/a/navalny-became/6260831.html|access-date=7 October 2021|publisher=RFE/RL|website=Voice of America|language=ru}}</ref>

In 2022, he was awarded [[Civil Courage Prize|U.S. Prize For Civil Courage]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Russia's Imprisoned Navalny Awarded U.S. Prize For Civil Courage |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/navalny-russia-civil-courage-prize/32100971.html |access-date=2024-03-01 |work=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty |language=en}}</ref>

In 2023, the documentary film about him, ''[[Navalny (film)|Navalny]]'', directed by [[Daniel Roher]], won [[BAFTA Award for Best Documentary|Best Documentary]] at the [[76th British Academy Film Awards]] and [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature Film|Best Documentary Feature]] at the [[95th Academy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=BAFTA Film Awards 2023: The full list of winners |url=https://news.sky.com/story/bafta-film-awards-2023-the-full-list-of-winners-12815159 |access-date=21 February 2023 |website=[[Sky News]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/mar/12/oscars-winners-2023-list-in-full-latest-awards-actor-best-picture|title=Oscars 2023: the full list of winners|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=12 March 2023}}</ref><ref name=roher>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-68326718|website=bbc.co.uk|title=Navalny's life and future death captured in Oscar-winning documentary|first=George|last=Wright|year=2023|quote="We don't realise how strong we actually are. The only thing necessary for the triumph of evil is for good people to do nothing. So don't be inactive."|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref>

== Family and personal life ==
[[File:Алексей и Юлия Навальные после одного из заседаний суда.JPG|thumb|upright|Navalny and his wife Yulia in 2013]]
Navalny was married to [[Yulia Navalnaya]] (maiden name: Yulia Borisovna Abrosimova) and the couple had two children.<ref name="BBC 2024-02-16" /> His daughter Dasha began undergraduate studies at [[Stanford University]] in September 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last=Navalnaya|first=Daria|date=27 June 2019|title=What It's Like to Be a Teenager in Putin's Russia|newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/opinion/putin-russia-teenagers.html |url-status=live|access-date=11 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200518184140/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/27/opinion/putin-russia-teenagers.html|archive-date=18 May 2020 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>

Starting 1998, Navalny lived primarily in a three-room apartment in [[Maryino District]] in southeast Moscow.<ref>{{cite web|date=2018|title=Biography|website=Navalny.com 2018 |url=https://2018.navalny.com/en/biography/|url-status=live|access-date=11 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200713064227/https://2018.navalny.com/en/biography/|archive-date=13 July 2020}}</ref>

Navalny was originally an atheist, but later became a member of the [[Russian Orthodox Church]]. He has said that turning to the Orthodox church has made him feel a "part of something large and universal."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/odr/akunin-navalny-interviews-part-i/|title=The Akunin-Navalny interviews (part I)|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022202814/https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/odr/akunin-navalny-interviews-part-i/|archive-date=22 October 2019|website=Open Democracy}}</ref>

On 17 January 2021, Navalny was again arrested as he was returning to Russia, after having had to leave the country for medical treatment in Germany for a poisoning attempt against his life that had recently occurred in Russia.<ref name="poisoning"/> He remained incarcerated (initially in the [[Corrective colony No. 2, Vladimir Oblast|IK-2 penal colony]]) and was housed in the IK-6 maximum security prison in [[Melekhovo, Vladimir Oblast|Melekhovo]], [[Vladimir Oblast]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Muniz |first1=Liliana |date=15 June 2022 |title=Alexei Navalny moved to infamous maximum security prison, says aide |agency=[[Politico Europe]] |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/alexei-navalny-opposition-leader-move-maximum-security-prison/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=15 June 2022 |title=Алексея Навального отправили в "пыточную" колонию № 6 во Владимирской области |url=https://meduza.io/feature/2022/06/15/alekseya-navalnogo-otpravili-v-pytochnuyu-koloniyu-6-vo-vladimirskoy-oblasti |website=[[Meduza]]}}</ref><ref name="2022_domicile"/> Navalny was listed by [[Amnesty International]] (AI) as a [[prisoner of conscience]] in May 2021, meaning that AI held that Navalny's incarceration was primarily due to his political beliefs.<ref name="amnesty_title">{{cite web|date=7 May 2021|title=Statement on Alexei Navalny's status as Prisoner of Conscience|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2021/05/statement-on-alexei-navalnys-status-as-prisoner-of-conscience/|access-date=9 May 2021|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|language=en|archive-date=9 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210509093721/https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2021/05/statement-on-alexei-navalnys-status-as-prisoner-of-conscience/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In addition to his native [[Russian language|Russian]], Navalny also spoke [[English language|English]].<ref>{{cite web |title=CNN investigation uncovers tailing of Alexey Navalny prior to poisoning |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n74UMp2Kmp4 |website=YouTube | date=14 December 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=18 February 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alexey Navalny's interview for HARDtalk, BBC |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1u6XTUvaDBM |website=YouTube | date=20 January 2017 |publisher=Алексей Навальный |access-date=18 February 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alexey Navalny: The 2020 60 Minutes Interview |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O6zdi6Q6p7o |website=YouTube | date=4 August 2023 |publisher=60 Minutes |access-date=18 February 2024}}</ref>

== Books and publications ==
* ''Opposing Forces: Plotting the New Russia'' (8 December 2016)<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Legvold |first=Robert |date=January–February 2017 |title=Opposing Forces: Plotting the New Russia [review&#93; |url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/reviews/capsule-review/2016-12-08/opposing-forces-plotting-new-russia |journal=[[Foreign Affairs]]|volume=96 |issue=January/February 2017 }}</ref>
* "Vladimir Putin: The 100 Most Influential People of 2022", [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', 23 May 2022<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Navalny |first=Alexei |date=23 May 2022 |title=Vladimir Putin: The 100 Most Influential People of 2022 |url=https://time.com/collection/100-most-influential-people-2022/6177689/vladimir-putin-leaders/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=29 November 2022}}</ref>
*''[[Patriot (book)|Patriot]]'' (22 October 2024), a memoir written while he was in prison<ref name=bbcinterview2024>{{cite interview| first=Yulia| last=Navalnaya |interviewer-last=Razzall |interviewer-first=Katie |title=Alexei Navalny's widow Yulia says she'll stand as Russian President |website=BBC News |date=20 October 2024 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/ce3z4ydk90vo |access-date=23 October 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Yulia Navalnaya, widow of former Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny, says she will return to Russia to run for president |website=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=22 October 2024 |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2024-10-22/yulia-navalnaya-says-will-stand-for-russia-president-after-putin/104504472 |access-date=23 October 2024}}</ref>

